[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to the Course!"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23136185"]
[ECO "D86"]

{ Hello! I'm Polish-American Grandmaster Dariusz Swiercz. Welcome to Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1.d4 Part 1, where I will cover all systems after 1.d4 Nf6, as well as some other sidelines. 1.d4 d5 and others will be the subject of Part 2.

I have played 1.d4 since my childhood and have employed many of the systems I present in this course, such as 7.Bc4 against the Grünfeld or 4.e3 against the Nimzo Indian.

First of all, thanks for buying this course. I have made a great effort in its creation, and I hope you can benefit from my experience and my analysis. I believe this repertoire can be suitable for players of all levels - lower-rated players will find here the fundamentals and the important ideas behind these openings, but stronger players can also pick up some fresh ideas and novelties.

Every opening comes with its own introduction, where you will find a detailed explanation of the lines. Let's see an overview of the main systems covered in this Part 1: } 1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. c4 g6 ( { • } 2...e6 3.Nc3 Bb4 { The Nimzo Indian [/course/131435/14] is a very solid opening with a long history and has been employed by every World Champion at some point. } 4.e3 { My recommendation is the Rubinstein Variation. White's idea is to play Ne2, either with a previous Bd3 or without it, depending on Black's reaction. Then, a3 will come and after ...Bxc3 Nxc3 White keeps a very nice structure and gets the bishop pair. } 4...O-O 5.Bd3 { Followed by 6.Ne2, this is better than the immediate development of the knight. } { 5.Bd2 is offered as an alternative system. } ) ( { • } 2...c5 3.d5 e6 4.Nc3 exd5 5.cxd5 d6 { The Benoni Defense. [/course/131435/62] White has many options here - I have gone for the following approach to keep a unified repertoire. } 6.e4 g6 7.Be2 Bg7 8.Nf3 O-O 9.Be3 { Note this position can be reached via the KID move order. White's plan involves some Nd2 and Black struggles to develop the c8-bishop. Now } 9...b5 { is an interesting pawn sacrifice, whereas } { 9...Bg4 is a more positional approach. I believe White has better prospects in both cases. } ) ( { • } 2...c5 3.d5 b5 { The Benko or Volga Gambit. [/course/131435/48] Now } 4.cxb5 a6 5.e3 { is the system I propose. We don't want to take on a6, but rather invite Black to recapture on b5, where we would get an excellent setup on the queenside with Bxb5, Nc3, and a4. } ) ( { • } 2...e5 { The Budapest Gambit. [/course/131435/50] After the very solid and good approach } 3.dxe5 Ng4 4.Nf3 { , I believe Black can't equalize. } ) ( { • } 2...b6 { The Queen's Fianchetto [/course/131435/56] is also examined. } 3.Nc3 Bb7 4.Qc2 { This is my recommendation, aiming for a very strong center after } 4...d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.e4 Nxc3 7.bxc3 { . } ) ( { • } 2...d6 { The Old Indian Defense and other Sidelines [/course/131435/59] are covered too. } 3.Nc3 e5 4.Nf3 Nbd7 5.e4 { and } 5...g6 { would transpose to a King's Indian, but } { 5...Be7 is the independent approach. 6.Be2 O-O 7.O-O c6 8.Be3 and White will get a very nice position thanks to our central control. } ) 
3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld Defense. [/course/131435/1] Here, I have chosen a very sound system, the Classical line. } ( { • } 3...Bg7 { introduces the King's Indian Defense. [/course/131435/43] My recommendation is } 4.e4 d6 5.Be2 O-O 6.Be3 { A modern setup. While I haven't had the occasion of playing this system yet, I have studied it in detail, and it strikes me as very promising for White. } 6...e5 7.d5 { The point. We close the center and aim at some kingside attack with h4-h5 with support from our e2-bishop. Black has a number of possible setups, and I offer some deep analysis and guidelines to counter them. } { Note that after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N1B3/PP2BPPP/R2QK1NR b KQ - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6...c5 7.d5 e6 8.Nf3 exd5 9.cxd5 we have reached our system against the Benoni. [/course/131435/62] } ) 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 c5 
8. Ne2 {[%cal Rc8g4][%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge2]} { Our knight controls the center and is protected from attacks, as ...Bg4 will always be met by f3. I feel this is a very good choice for a Lifetime Repertoire, as Black has no way to force a draw, while White enjoys pretty good prospects thanks to our central control.

Whether you use this course as a digital book, you train and memorize the variations with the help of the MoveTrainer, or you follow my video explanations, I hope you find this content interesting and useful. It's a big course, so... let's get started! } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Grünfeld"]
[Black "Grünfeld 10...Bg4 11.f3 Na5 #1"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22575380"]
[ECO "D86"]

1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } Bg4 
11. f3 Na5 { This is the old main line that was extremely popular back even 1950s I believe. It was also played numerous times in the 4th Karpov-Kasparov match in 1987. } 
12. Bxf7+ { This would be my suggestion. There are two reasons why I recommend this line: first, it grabs a pawn and Black still needs to show compensation for it, and second, this is what Stockfish likes the most! } ( 12.Bd3 { is another popular line that I do not consider in this course, however, it is also incredibly interesting and leads to fighting positions. The line goes like this: } 12...cxd4 13.cxd4 Be6 14.d5!? Bxa1 15.Qxa1 f6 { with lots of theory. White sacrificed an exchange to weaken Black's king and build a strong center. Maybe there will be a course on this at some point! } ) Rxf7 
13. fxg4 Rxf1+ 
14. Kxf1 { This is the main position of this line. I admit openly that I don't really know the history of how the theory developed here over the years, however I will do my best to analyze the line as thoroughly as possible and provide more than sufficient guidance to anyone who plays it. } cxd4 
15. cxd4 { This position is achievable if Black begins with 12... cxd4. In my opinion, this trade of pawns really serves White as it can be (nearly) done anytime by Black and additionally in some lines the c3-pawn may be a target. } e5 { I believe that this move is the most natural follow-up to the trade on d4. If Black played it before this trade, not only there could have been an idea of dxc5 which is not the case here, but also after simple d5 the c5-pawn would be immediately attacked. } ( 15...Qd6? { after the trade of c-pawns, this move is just bad. The release of the tension rids White of the potential weak c3-pawn and the c-file can be controlled by White too. } 16.e5! Qd5 17.g5 Rd8 18.Qc2 $16 ) 
16. d5 Nc4 {[%cal Gc4e3]} 
17. Qd3! Nxe3+ { I believe this move only helps White. Right now, it will be very difficult to organize a counterplay for Black against the e4-pawn, while dark-square play by Black can be relatively easily neutralized. } ( { Keeping the knight active with } 17...b5 { makes sense and here I recommend } 18.Bf2!? { . Check it out here. [/variation/21215251/#/17/b] } ) 
18. Qxe3 Qh4?! {[%cal Gh4g4,Gh4h2]} { Winning back a pawn but at a cost of wasting precious tempi. } 
19. Kg1 Qxg4 { Black recaptured the pawn but the position is strategically bad. } 
20. h3 Qd7 
21. Kh1!? {[%cal Ge2g1,Gg1f3]} b5 
22. Ng1 $16  {[%cal Gg1f3][%csl Rg7]} { A recurring idea in this variation. Soon regrouped to f3, White's knight is much better than Black's bishop. } *

