3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } Na5 ( { This line was quite popular in the early 2010s but recently not so much anymore. In fact, it is a worse version of } 10...b6 { , as it is not common to be helpful for Black to play ...Na5 in these positions. The knight is sometimes misplaced. } ) 
11. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} b6 { This move is pretty much necessary. } 
12. Rc1 e5 { This is what Black generally does in this line. After kicking away the bishop from c4, there are no Bd5 ideas, and in the event of d5 Black can choose and/or combine from ...c4, ...f5 and ...Nb7-Nd6 ideas. } 
13. dxe5!? { A very aggressive option towards which the trend shifted recently due to games Shankland-Grandelius (2020) and Salem-Shirov (2020). } ( 13.dxc5 Be6 14.c4 { is a more positional approach. White just grabs a pawn and attempts to prove its worth. } 14...bxc5 15.Bxc5 Bh6 16.Rc3 Re8 17.Qc2 Qc7 18.Ba3 Rab8 19.h3 { This was played in Aronian-Mamedyarov (2018). Here, Mamedyarov made a mistake, while } 19...Nc6! { is the correct move, with an unclear game. } { 19...Red8?! 20.Bc1! $14 Aronian-Mamedyarov (2018); after 20...Bf8 21.Bg5! followed by c5 is unpleasant for Black. } ) Be6?! {[%cal Ga5c4]} { This continuation was tried in Salem-Kamsky (2020). I believe it is a clearly inferior option. } 
14. c4! {[%cal Ra5c4]} { A very strong move by Salem, stopping ...Nc4 ideas. } Qd7 ( { Intending ...Ra(f)d8. } 14...Bxe5 { is not good anymore as ...Be6 falls under a tempo: } 15.f4 Bg7 16.f5! Bd7 17.Nf4 $16 ) ( 14...Nc6 15.f4 g5 16.g3 $16 { is just an extra pawn. } ) 
15. Nc3! ( { This precise move gives White an advantage. Salem erred with } 15.Nf4?! { after which Kamsky could have played } 15...Nc6! { (instead of 15... Bxe5) with equality, thanks to the only moves: } 16.Nxe6 fxe6 17.f4 g5! 18.g3 gxf4 19.gxf4 Bh6! 20.Qe2 Rf7! $13 { with ...Raf8 next and sufficient compensation. } ) ( 15.f4? Rfd8 $17 ) Bxe5 
16. Nd5 { Here we are back in Salem-Kamsky. } Nc6 
17. f4 $16  -- ( { White has a very promising position. In the game followed } 17...Bxd5 18.cxd5 Bd4 19.Qd2 Bxe3+ 20.Qxe3 Nd4 21.f5!+- { with a powerful attack. } )
