18. d5 exd5 
19. Bxd5 $16  {[%cal Ge2g3,Ge2f4][%csl Gd5,Gf5,Rh5]} { White is much better. The destroyed pawn structure on Black's kingside along with the weakened king and additionally White's control over the center leads to serious problems for Black. The ideas of Nf4 and Bc3 are perhaps White's main attempts to continue. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Grünfeld"]
[Black "Grünfeld 10...e6 #1"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22575390"]
[ECO "D86"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } e6 { There are two ideas behind this move. One, it stops (at least for now) h4 ideas, and two, it does not allow White comfortably play d5 gaining the space. Recently it has gained some popularity. It is definitely less explored than 10...b6 which has been the mainstream theory for the past few years so some people may try it to avoid learning those lines and choose something less common.

White has some options now but I haven't found an objective advantage for White. This line is pretty decent, however, Black really needs to know many things. } 
11. dxc5 {[%mdl 32768]} { Capturing this pawn is by far the most critical option that must be investigated. } Qa5 { This is the main move. } 
12. f4! Rd8 
13. Qe1!? ( { This is the critical position in this line. White has some choice now. I think that three moves } 13.Qb3 { , } ) ( 13.Qc2 { and 13. Qe1 are all tricky for Black. } ) { A very tricky line. Black needs to be super careful. } Qa4! ( { Black must put pressure on the 4th rank. Now we enter a forced sequence. } 13...Bd7? 14.a4 $16 { and Black cannot win the pawn back. } ) ( 13...b6 14.cxb6 axb6 15.Rb1 $16 { is also just an extra pawn. } ) 
14. Bb3 Qxe4 
15. Ng3 Qd3 
16. Rc1! ( { Here, there is some choice. We will check both } 16.Rc1! { and } ) ( 16.Rd1 ) ( { This is more tricky. Right now, Black needs to be very careful. } 16.Rd1 { was tried too. It is more forcing but Black is just fine. You can check some analysis here. [/variation/21327533/#/16/w/0.0] } ) Bd7! { Black needs to quickly complete the development. } 
17. Qf2! {[%cal Gf1d1,Gg3e4]} { White's idea is Rfd1, kicking away the queen, followed by Ne4. } Na5! {[%cal Ra5b3]} { It makes sense to challenge the b3-bishop and hopefully trade it and it might, as seen after [/variation/21327534/#/17/b] 17... Ne7, cause lots of damage on this diagonal. } 
18. Bc2 Qa6 ( 18...Qxc3?! 19.Bxg6 Qb2 20.Bc2! $14 { followed by f5 looks great for White. } ) 
19. Bd4! { Trading the dark-squared bishops and hoping to create an attack on the kingside. A very good and practical try. } Bb5 { Black must start with this move. The position is really complex and it is very easy to go wrong here with Black. The best example of that is the game Praggnanandhaa-Duda (2022). In this position, Jan made a big mistake switching the move order and took on d4 first (see this variation [/variation/21327535/#/19/b]). } 
20. Rfd1 { I think that this position is very tricky to play with Black. } f5!! 
21. h4!? ( { White still retains some initiative. The line continues here. [/variation/21327536/#/21/w] Alternatively, } 21.Qe3!? { also deserves attention. } ) *

