12. Qxd8 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { This is a viable alternative. White has two options here: } 12.Qxd8 { (considered as main) and the rare [/variation/21445057/#/12/w] but interesting } ) ( 12.Bb3 { . Both options require certain precision from Black and it is good to have them in the repertoire. } ) Rxd8 
13. Rfd1 { This endgame is quite unpleasant for Black if caught off guard. I tried it myself twice. Very recently, I played it against Sam Shankland at the 2022 US Championships. } Bd7 
14. Bb3 Bc6 
15. f3 Rdc8 { This is perhaps the critical position of this line. Sam Shankland blitzed it out against me and I could not remember at the board my analysis and I was on my own here pretty much. } 
16. Nf4 {[%csl Re6]} ( { I tried this in my game and indeed it is quite a decent try. There are ideas of Nxe6 potentially. During the game I tried to analyze } 16.Nd4 { but I could not find anything after } 16...Bd7! { and I didn't see how to successfully defend the c5-pawn. } 17.h3!? { An interesting try. The idea is f4, while if ...Rxc5 is played there are available various discovery attacks. } { 17.Rab1 Bf8= } 17...Rxc5! { Black must calculate well and grab the pawn. However, things are far from obvious... } 18.Nxe6! Rxc3 19.Bd4 Rxb3 20.Nxg7 { it looks like White wins, but it is not the case. } 20...Nxf3+! 21.gxf3 Rxf3= { The resulting position is equal as the Ng7 is really badly placed. Black should be fine here, but it may not be obvious to understand or find if not prepared. } ) a5 
17. a4 {[%cal Ra5a4]} { White should not allow ...a4. } Be8 
