1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } c5 
5. Nge2 cxd4 
6. exd4 O-O 
7. a3 Be7 
8. d5! { White should seize space and not allow ...d5. } exd5 
9. cxd5 Re8 
10. d6! {[%mdl 32768]} { Of course, White should block Black's ways to develop pieces when possible. } Bf8 
11. g3! {[%cal Gf1g2]} { Fianchettoing the bishop. I believe it is not easy to play this position with Black, even if the d6-pawn is gone due to the lag in the development of the queenside. } Re6 
12. Bf4 Nh5 { Black may try to immediately deal with the d6-pawn. } 
13. Be3! { Even pawn down White retains a strong pressure. } Rxd6 
14. Nd5 {[%cal Gf1g2,Ge1g1]} { White has a simple plan: Bg2, O-O and put everything in the center. Black's position is difficult. Check it out here. [/variation/21472936/#/14/w] } *

