1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd3 c5 ( { This is the most popular variation. If Black does not do anything in the center, White wants Ne2, O-O etc. For this reason Black should react in the center with either } 5...d5 { or } ) ( 5...c5 { (I cover the alternatives as well, but they are not really critical and White should be better there). } { 5.Bd2!? is another approach that is a modern innovation in Rubinstein Variation. White wants to recapture with the bishop on c3 and avoid doubled pawns. } ) 
6. Nge2 d5 
7. cxd5 { Before Black gets the chance to play ...dxc4. } cxd4 
8. exd4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nxd5 
9. O-O Nc6 ( { By far the main move, but to my surprise, when I played this line in the 2022 US Championships against Leinier Dominguez, I faced } 9...Re8 { instead, which caught me by a big surprise. } ) 
10. a3 Bd6 { The main trend recently here. Black leaves the e7-square for the knight and keeps the diagonal open, potentially for Black's queen to go to h4. } 
11. Re1 { This is the recent trend. The rook is useful there in many lines, and White waits for Black to choose their setup now. It is a top suggestion by the engines, and many GMs have gone for it. One of the main ideas here is Bc2 and Qd3 trying to weaken Black's kingside. } ( 11.Bc2 { with the idea of Qd3 is premature for perhaps many reasons, but one of the clearest is } 11...Qh4 12.g3 Qh5 { when comparing to the position with Re1 instead of Bc2, White would be better off having the rook on the open file. } ) Qh4 {[%cal Gh4h2]} { This move is perhaps the most critical. The idea of jumping out with the queen and bringing it to h5 is common in Ne2-setups. } 
12. g3 Qh5 
13. Nxd5 exd5 
14. Bf4 Rd8 { Black should keep the tension. } 
15. Qd2 Bf8 { Probably the best move. In general, Black's main defensive idea is not allowing White to place the knight on f4. } 
16. Bc7!? ( { I would recommend this move here. In the recent game Sarana-Keymer (2022) there was some sophisticated maneuvering going on after } 16.Be3 Bd6 17.Bg5 Rf8 18.Bf4 Be7 { . Please note how Black avoids the bishop trade and does not allow the knight to land on f4. I am not sure if White has anything special here. } 19.Be5 Bg5 20.Nf4 Bg4 $13 { and I think Black is fine. } { Sarana played @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2bppp/2n5/3p3q/3P1B2/P2B2P1/1P1QNP1P/R3R1K1 w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@ 19.b4 but here instead of the passive 19...a6 Keymer should have gone for 19...Bh3! 20.Be3 Bd6! $132 and Black may even begin thinking about taking over. } ) Rd7 { Black must play a tempo move, not allowing Nf4 (or at least making it tactically less likely to be sound due to the hanging bishop on c7). } 
17. Ba5 ( { Fleeing with the bishop and keeping the game alive. } 17.Nf4 { allows } 17...Nxd4! { again and after } 18.Bxh7+ Qxh7 19.Qxd4 Rxc7 20.Nxd5 { White has enough compensation for a draw, but that is not what White normally wants to get. } 20...Rd7 21.Re8 Rxd5 22.Qb4 Qf5 23.Qxf8+ Kh7 24.Qh8+ Kg6 25.Rg8 Qf6 26.Rxc8 Qxb2= { . } { Notice @@StartFEN@@r1b2bk1/pp1r1ppp/2n5/B2p3q/3P4/P2B2P1/1P1QNP1P/R3R1K1 b - - 7 17@@EndFEN@@ 17...Bd6?? is insufficient now due to back rank issues: 18.Nf4 Bxf4 19.Re8 . } ) g5! {[%cal Re2f4][%csl Gf4]} { Again - Black must control the f4-square. A very logical move, of course, but not entirely easy to play - after all, it weakens the king... which White will try to exploit soon. } 
18. Bb4!? Nxb4 
19. axb4 {[%cal Ge2c3,Ge1e5,Gf2f4,Gh2h4][%csl Ga1]} { The a-file opens for White's rook in any case, but the main focus is on the kingside anyway. White's plan is Nc3, maybe Re5, and moves like h4 or f4. } Rd8! {[%cal Gd8h8][%csl Gc8]} { The back rank should be covered in any case, and Black needs to develop the c8-bishop. } 
20. Nc3!? { An interesting pawn sac for the initiative. } Bxb4 
21. h4 -- ( { Black's position looks somewhat scary. I think White has good practical chances, even though the engine claims Black is fine. Here are some sample continuations. First, } 21...gxh4? { runs into } 22.Re5 $16 { . } { 21...h6 22.Bc2 gxh4 23.Re5 f5 24.g4!? Qxg4+ 25.Kh2+- Black has no more checks, and Rg1 is coming. Therefore, Black's only move is @@StartFEN@@r1br2k1/pp6/7p/3pRp1q/1b1P2Pp/2N5/1PBQ1P2/R5K1 b - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@ 24...Qg5 but after 25.Qxg5+ hxg5 26.Bxf5 we keep some pressure as there are still some weaknesses in Black's camp. } )
