8. O-O { With this move, White transposes to a main KID system usually reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP2BPPP/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 2 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Nf3 e5 7.O-O Nbd7 , which is considered as a somewhat inferior line than 6...Nc6 or 6...Na6. Now, White could play 8.d5 too, but I think there is no reason to avoid this line. Now, Black has a vast number of options. } exd4 ( { The main line. Note that Black can't 'prepare' this exchange with } 8...a5? { intending to secure the c5-square for the knight because that weakens the queenside. White can take immediate advantage with } 9.dxe5! dxe5 11.Qc2! $16 { or similarly, @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1ppn1pbp/3p1np1/p3P3/2P1P3/2N1BN2/PP2BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ 9...Nxe5 10.Nxe5 dxe5 and again 11.Qc2! $16 . With the pawn on a7, these positions would be acceptable for Black, but now the queenside is severely weakened. White wants to play Rfd1 and perhaps at some point Nd5, which is highly unpleasant. Black can try ...c6, but, with the pawn on a5, the b6- and c5-squares are extremely weak. A way to exploit them is Na4! . } ) 
9. Nxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} Re8 
