11. Rad1 Qe7 
12. f3 { This is the main position. } a6 { I consider this the best move for Black. There are two main ideas connected to this pawn move: preparing a future ...b5 (say, ...Ne5 and ...b5) or ...c5!? as the a6-pawn controls the b5-square. } 
13. Bf2 Ne5 
14. Qc1 $146  { An excellent move which is technically a novelty. The idea is pure prophylaxis: the queen makes room for the knight in case of ...c5. If Black goes ...b5, the queen not only puts some pressure on the c-file but also does not run under a tempo with ...Nc4. } ( { To illustrate this point, let's say } 14.Qd2 b5 15.cxb5 axb5 { and now ...Nc4 will always attack the queen, and perhaps Bxc4 would be necessary. For this reason, c1 is a better square for the queen. } 16.a3 Qb7 17.h3 Nc4 { is a possible continuation. } ) ( 14.a4?! { stopping ...b5 has some merit, but Black can play } 14...c5! { and there is no Nc2-Ne3 maneuver. } 15.Nb3 Be6 16.Nd2 Nc6 $13 { is unclear. } ) b5 
15. cxb5 axb5 ( 15...cxb5 { is not any better. } 16.Rfe1!? { is Stockfish's suggestion, but I like } { 16.a3 more. There is no need to worry about ...b4 anymore. 16...Bb7 17.Nc2 Rac8 18.Ne3 $16 with a comfortable edge. } ) 
