1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 Bg7 
4. e4 d6 
5. Be2 O-O 
6. Be3 Nc6 { This is quite an unorthodox system for Black. Its idea is to try to play ...e5 and meet d5 with ...Nd4. And in case of Nf3, there are ...Ng4 ideas. This setup, however, induces White to expand very quickly in the center and seize a lot of space. } 
7. d5! {[%mdl 32768]} Ne5 { The main move, of course. I don't think the others require much attention, but we needed to briefly cover them as well. } 
8. f4 { Expanding in the center! } Neg4 
9. Bd2 Nh6 ( { Surprisingly, } 9...e6 { occurred in some games, and even more surprisingly, no one grabbed a free piece! } 10.Bxg4 Nxg4 11.Qxg4 exd5 12.Qg5+- { . } ) ( { Everything else is just bad. } 9...h5 10.h3 Nh6 11.Nf3 { is a much worse version of 9...Nh6 - ...h5 only weakens Black's kingside, while h3 helps White as it restricts the h6-knight. } ) 
10. Nf3 ( { I like this direction more than } 10.h3 { , which is another interesting move here. } ) e6 { An alternative tried in some games. } 
11. dxe6 fxe6 { Black makes space for the knight on f7. Now, White has many interesting ways of playing this position. I like an aggressive approach that immediately puts pressure on Black's kingside. } ( 11...Bxe6 12.O-O $16 { is simply bad for Black. The h6-knight is horrible and has no future. } ) 
12. Ng5 Nf7 
13. h4! {[%cal Gg5f7,Gh4h5]} { Thus, White initiates an attack on the kingside. There are ideas of Nxf7 followed by h5 or g4. Of course, White is interested here in castling queenside. Black's position is very shaky, as illustrated here [/variation/21780217/#/13/w] and in the subsequent lines. } *

