4. a3! {[%mdl 32768]} { A strong prophylactic move. Black's main idea here is normally ...Bb4 and this move just kills it. } d6 ( { Perhaps Black should play this move seeking quick counterplay. } 4...Bc5? 5.e3 O-O 6.Qd5+- { and White wins a piece. } ) 
5. Qc2! Nc5 ( 5...Bf5? 6.Nc3+- ) 
6. exd6 Bxd6 { This is a little bit better version of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/2P1n3/P7/1P2PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Nc6 5.Nf3 d6 variation as Black did not play ...Nc6 yet and this knight does not run under tempo with b5 in some lines (after b4-...Ne6). White can play through b4 here too but I would not be rushing it. } 
7. Nc3 $146  O-O 
8. Nf3 { Normal development is pretty strong. Black should try to exploit a slight lead in the development but with few accurate moves White neutralizes all the danger and retains a healthy extra pawn. } Qf6 { With the idea of ...Bf5. Right now White does not have time to play g3, so White chooses another way to complete development. } 
9. e4!? {[%cal Gc1e3]} { Followed by Be3 is good. } Bg4 
10. Be3! Bxf3 
11. gxf3 Qxf3 { Black can regain the pawn but it does not help his position. } 
12. Rg1 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1c1]} Nbd7 
13. Be2 Qf6 
14. O-O-O+- {[%cal Yc1b1,Yf2f4,Gc3d5,Gb2b4]} { With ideas of b4, Nd5 or even Kb1-f4. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Queen's Fianchetto"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23066591"]
[ECO "A50"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 b6 { I have never known the name of this line until I looked at it for the needs of this course. The Queen's Fianchetto Defense is a rare guest at the top level but still, it is used sometimes either as a surprise weapon or as a way to deviate from the main lines in Nimzo and instead achieve a Queen's Indian setup. White should try to get to play e4 as soon as possible. } 
3. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bb7 
4. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4]} { Preparing e4. Now Black has to play ...d5, otherwise, Black's play makes no sense. } d5 ( 4...c5? 5.d5 $16 { followed by e4 is clearly much better for White. } ) 
5. cxd5 Nxd5 
6. e4 Nxc3 
7. bxc3 e6 {[%cal Gc7c5]} ( { Black has two main options here, } 7...e6 { and } ) ( 7...e5!? { . } ) { A more standard approach, going for ...c5 in the future. } 
8. Nf3 Be7 { Here, I found a very interesting idea that puts lots of pressure on Black. } 
9. Bf4 $146  ( { The point of this move is that right now Black cannot play ...c5 which reduces options for Black. } 9.Bb5+ c6 10.Bd3 c5 { is just the same as 9. Bd3. } ) O-O 
10. Bd3 c5 
11. d5! exd5 ( { There is nothing better. } 11...h6 12.dxe6 fxe6 13.Bg3 $16 ) ( 11...c4 { gives away a pawn due to the pin on the d-file. } 12.Bxc4 exd5 13.Rd1 Qe8 14.Bxd5 Bxd5 15.Rxd5 $16 ) 
12. exd5 Qxd5 { It looks critical to capture this pawn. Otherwise, White plays c4 with clear advantage. } 
13. O-O! Qh5□ 
14. Rae1↑ { White has a strong initiative here. } Nc6 
15. Re3! {[%cal Gf3e5,Gf1e1]} { The rook is very well placed on e3, combining ideas of Ne5 and swinging the rook to the kingside, as well as simple Rfe1. White is on top against any attempt. You can check it out. [/variation/21815988/#/15/w] } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Sidelines - Old Indian"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23066593"]
[ECO "A55"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 d6 { The Old Indian Defense is quite a rare guest at the top level. There are possible transpositions to King's Indian or some sort of Philidor with c4. I remember that in 2014 I employed it in one of my games as Black when I tried to avoid Saemisch Variation in King's Indian and get some other pawn structure. I succeeded in doing so in my game but if we are going for relatively standard lines in King's Indian, there is no need to fear this. } 
3. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 ( 3...Nbd7 { is a possible move order too but it would most likely transpose to 3... e5. } 4.e4 e5 5.Nf3 { and we are back to the main line. } ) 
4. Nf3 Nbd7 { This is the Philidor setup, but with White's pawn already on c4, which allows White gather more space than in a 'normal' Philidor with pawn on c2. } 
5. e4 Be7 
6. Be2 O-O 
7. O-O c6 
8. Be3 { The most standard move. It goes well with other King's Indian lines that I recommend where White plays Be2 and Be3 anyway. White's plan is pretty simple: centralize all the pieces and/or consider playing d5 at some pont to gather even more space. } a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ( { Typically the most expected plan from Black. The idea is to play ...b5. } 8...exd4 9.Nxd4 $16 { is obviously great for White. Similar positions I analyze in King's Indian where Bg7 is normally better placed than the one on e7. } ) 
9. Qc2 ( 9.d5!? { is an alternative option. Grabbing more space cannot be bad! } 9...cxd5 { After 9...c5 there are many options, but I like 10.Kh1 $16 similarly to what I analyze in the King's Indian, ...Nbd7 variation. The idea is to begin expanding on the kingside with g4 at some point! } 10.cxd5 b5 11.Nd2 $16 ) b5 
10. Rfd1 Qc7 
11. cxb5 cxb5 
12. Rac1 $16  { With such development and control in the center White must be doing great here. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Benko Gambit"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23066588"]
[ECO "A57"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 b5 
4. cxb5 {[%mdl 32768]} a6 { Alternatives to this move are really dubious. } 
5. e3 { I would suggest this move against Benko. My rationale for the choice of this line is the following. First, Black cannot get a typical 'Benko position' in which Black gets an easy game on a and b files - here, White plans on recapturing with the bishop on b5. A quick setup with a4 and Ra3 further restricts Black's play on the queenside.

And second, this line is not as popular as 5.bxa6 which makes it a choice that is less expected and there is a chance people playing with Black may not be too familiar with this line. Nonetheless, I believe this system against Benko Gambit can be played often, making it a good choice for a Lifetime Repertoire. Black has three main approaches here:

  1) playing with ...g6;

  2) playing with ...e6 quickly;

  3) playing with ...Bb7 and then attacking the center with ...e6.

} ( { There are also others that are less popular. } 5.bxa6 { is the most popular and there would be for sure some courses in the future on that. } ) g6 ( { Black decides to fianchetto the bishop right away, steering towards typical Benko setups. } 5...d6 { This move order would likely transpose to 5... g6: } 6.Nc3 g6 7.a4 Bg7 8.e4 O-O 9.Nf3 { with a transposition. } ) ( 5...Qa5+ { This is a rare move order, but anyway we reach a position which I discuss after 5. axb5. } 6.Bd2 Qb6 7.Nc3 axb5 8.Bxb5 Bb7 { with a transposition. } ) 
6. Nc3 Bg7 
7. a4! { A typical move that strengthens the queenside and limits Black's counterplay prospects. } O-O 
8. e4 { It seems that White wasted a tempo playing e2-e3 first and now e3-e4. In reality, e3 had the purpose of having an option of meeting ...axb5 with Bxb5 and now, once this goal has been accomplished and Black does not have easy queenside play, it makes perfect sense to strengthen the center. Black has a couple of options now but I believe there is no way for Black to equalize. } d6 { This is the most natural move but there are other options too. } 
9. Nf3 { This position can appear from many move orders. In this position, Black has two possible plans: either ...e6 or ...axb5 and then try the queenside play. } axb5 
10. Bxb5 Ba6 { In the spirit of Benko, but White has a great version of it - the construction of a4 and Bb5 is usually a great asset for White in such positions. } 
11. Nd2!? {[%cal Gd2c4,Gd2e4][%csl Re4]} { Not the only good move, but it makes sense to bring the knight to c4 eventually, while at the same time defending the e4-pawn, enabling the Nxb5 recapture. } Nfd7 
12. Ra3!? {[%csl Ga3]} ( { A typical move in Benko, preventing any counterplay, as the Ra3 does not run under any tactics. } 12.O-O?? { would lose a piece: } 12...Bxc3 13.bxc3 Bxb5-+ ) Bxb5 ( 12...Bxc3 13.Rxc3 Bxb5 14.axb5 $16 ) 
13. Nxb5 Na6 
14. O-O Nc7 
15. Nxc7 Qxc7 
16. Qc2 $16  {[%cal Gd2c4,Gb2b3,Ga4a5,Gc1d2,Gd2c3]} -- ( { Black does not have any compensation. A sample continuation is } 16...Rfb8 17.Nc4 Ne5 18.Nxe5 Bxe5 19.b3 $16 { . } )
*

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide: Other Defenses"]
[Black "Benoni #1"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23066584"]
[ECO "A65"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 e6 
4. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} exd5 
5. cxd5 d6 { The Benoni is a very fighting, yet strategically risky setup for Black. In order to create an unbalanced position Black concedes control over the center and attempts to create counterplay by either challenging it (ideas of ...Re8, maybe ...f5 sometimes) or trying to play ...b5.

There are many systems available for White. There is a very sharp system connected with quick e4-f4 and Bb5+, there is more classical e4-Nf3-Nd2, there are also systems with g3, e4-Nge2-Ng3 or even Nf3-Bf4. In this course I decided to keep things rather simple and suggest a system that can be achieved from the King's Indian move order. This simplifies the repertoire and makes it very flexible, regardless of the move orders and other subtleties. } 
6. e4 g6 
7. Be2 ( { I would recommend starting with this move to avoid ...a6-Bg4 line. } 7.Nf3 a6 8.a4 Bg4 { is quite a decent option for Black. } ) Bg7 
8. Nf3 a6 ( { Right now, the main move, of course, is } 8...O-O { . Then we play } 9.Be3 { and we transpose to a position that can be achieved from the KID move order. The only way to deviate from a regular Benoni/KID is to play 8... a6. } ) ( 8...O-O 9.Be3 { transposes back to the King's Indian move order. } ) 
9. Bf4!? ( { I think this is a very strong move for White. Incidentally, it transposes to another system (Nf3-Bf4). Why this move? What is the point and what is its advantage over 'normal' } 9. a4? Well, the key point is that now after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p3pbp/p2p1np1/2pP4/4PB2/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@9...b5 { White can play } { 10.e5! with strong pressure. For this reason, we don't need to worry about ...b5. The idea of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p3pbp/p2p1np1/2pP4/4P3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Bf4 is aimed against 9...Bg4 as well - now, we can play 10.Qa4! , as the analysis shows.

Finally, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p3pbp/p2p1np1/2pP4/4PB2/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@ 9...O-O (which is the most expected) only then White plays 10.a4 achieving a favorable setup over 9. a4 Bg4, where Black has not castled yet (please look at 9. a4 to see the difference). } ) O-O 
10. a4 Bg4 { Black pretty much must play this move. Everything else is just terrible. } 
11. Nd2! {[%cal Gd2c4]} ( { White is just in time to prevent the trade of the bishop for the knight and keep an option of transferring the knight to c4. An alternative is } 11.O-O Bxf3 12.Bxf3 Qe7 { Black wants to play ...Nbd7 with a solid position. Thanks to the move order, White can now play } 13.e5!? dxe5 14.d6 { with some pressure, but with correct play I think Black should be fine. You can check some analysis here. [/variation/21843226/#/11/w/0.6] } ) Bxe2 
12. Qxe2 { The bishop on f4 disturbs Black's development of the queenside. Black needs to play ...Nh5. } Nh5 
13. Be3 Nd7 
14. O-O { This is the main position of this line. Black has some choice now. } Re8 
15. g4 Nhf6 
16. f3 { Strengthening control over the center. This is one of the most popular positions in this line where Black has played many moves. } b5!? ( { The engine's suggestion - I guess thanks to inhuman calculation engine realized that the best bet for Black here is to sac a pawn right away before White begins the squeeze. } 16...Qc7?! { was tried in some games but I don't get the point of this move. The queen seems to be just useless there. } 17.Kh1!? $16 ) ( 16...h6?! { was tried in an old game, Portisch-Kasparov (1981). Stopping g5 is not necessary and in reality ...h6 is just a waste of time. } 17.Bf4!? Ne5 18.Bg3 $16 { or } { 17.Kh1!? is also good, which is what Portisch played. } ) ( 16...Ne5 { Placing the knight on e5 prematurely is unlikely good. } 17.Kh1 Qb6 18.Rfb1 $16 { or } { 17...h5? 18.g5 Nh7 19.f4+- } ) 
17. axb5 Nb6! 
18. Qd3!? {[%csl Ge4,Gb5]} -- ( { Sidestepping the threats. Now Black will have to go for } 18...axb5 19.Nxb5 { and I believe our extra pawn will tell. See more details here. [/variation/21843226/#/18/w] } )
*

