[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "1) The Grünfeld Defense: Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21138160"]
[ECO "D86"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } ( { • } 7...Nc6 8.Ne2 e5?! { some people played here like that but it is simply wrong due to } 9.Ba3! { and Black cannot castle. White has great chances here. } ) ( { • } 7...O-O 8.Ne2 Nc6 { 8...b6?! 9.h4! is strong now. } 9.O-O b6 10.Bg5! { followed by Qd2 and Rad1. If Black eventually plays ...c5, very likely White should react by playing d5. } ) 
8. Ne2 O-O 
9. O-O Nc6 
10. Be3 { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. }  b6! { I think that this is the best line for Black as this is what top players and Grunfeld experts play these days. I think I found some interesting new (or at least very fresh) paths for White that can put Black under some pressure. } ( { • } 10...Bg4 11.f3 Na5 { This is the old line (also played with the inclusion of ...cxd4-cxd4) that was played mostly since the 1940s to early 2000s - roughly 60 years of theory! Recently it has not been that common, even though there were some games by top players. } 12.Bxf7+ { Grabbing a pawn would be my recommendation. Let Black prove his compensation for it! } 12...Rxf7 13.fxg4 Rxf1+ 14.Kxf1 { Black has here many options and probably he is able to eventually equalize, but this would require highly precise play. Overall, I like White's chances here. } 14...Qd6 { I keep this as a main move as there was a recent game Giri-Carlsen (2021) and if Magnus played it I guess it should be considered as the main option for Black. } 15.e5 Qd5 16.Ng1! Nc4 17.Qe2 cxd4 18.cxd4 b5 19.Nf3 a5 { So far, we follow a game Giri-Carlsen (2021). Here, White has two options. } 20.Bg5 { The most logical move, played by Anish. } { 20.Bf2!? is a decent alternative, with idea of h4-h5 and kingside attack. Both options are playable! }) ( { • } 10...Bg4 11.f3 Na5 12.Bxf7+ Rxf7 13.fxg4 Rxf1+ 14.Kxf1 cxd4 15.cxd4 e5 { is probably the main alternative and here both 16. Kg1 and 16. d5 are possible. I analyze both but I would perhaps stick with 16. d5, as I would want to create a passed pawn and worsen Bg7. } 16.d5 Nc4 17.Qd3 b5 { and here both } 18.Ng1!? { and } { 18.Bf2!? look promising according to my analysis. } ) ( { • } 10...Bg4 11.f3 Na5 12.Bd3 cxd4 13.cxd4 Be6 14.d5 Bxa1 15.Qxa1 f6 { is another tabiya here. I decided not to analyze it and picked 12. Bxf7 as the line of choice. Nonetheless, these positions here are also very interesting. } ) ( { • } 10...Bg4 11.f3 Bd7 { This line became popular mid 2010s and is still quite popular these days (perhaps it is the second most popular variation against Bc4-Ne2). The idea is to provoke f3 which can be useful sometimes for Black and it improves 10...Bd7 variation. } 12.Rb1 Qc7 { Here, there would be two recommendations.

1) } 13.Qd2 Rad8 { 13...Rfd8 This move weakens slightly the kingside and White may try to exploit it right away. 14.Bh6!? If Black is unprepared, this move can simply win the game in 20 moves! 14.Rfc1 can be played too, with 'normal' play. } 14.Rfc1 Bc8 { This is considered as the main line. } 15.h4!? { This typical pawn push on the kingside potentially gives Black some problems. } { 15.Kh1!? is more positional and also good. }{ 2) @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/ppqbppbp/2n3p1/2p5/2BPP3/2P1BP2/P3N1PP/1R1Q1RK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@ 13.Bf4 Qc8 13...e5 14.Bg3 is generally considered annoying for Black due to the pin. Additionally White may consider Bd5!? 14.d5 I think this line is quite challenging, especially if Black does not know it. 14...Na5 14...Ne5 15.Bxe5 Bxe5 16.f4 and with next e5 White builds here a very strong center which results in a position that is definitely not easy to play with Black. 15.Bd3 e6 16.Qd2! exd5 17.exd5 c4 18.Bc2 I think that this position is playable. The Na5 is out of play, the d5-pawn is strong. White's idea is to play g4!? followed by Ng3 and Ne4. }) ( { • } 10...Na5 { This line was popular in the 2010s but nowadays not as much. The Na5 is sometimes simply misplaced. } 11.Bd3 b6 12.Rc1 e5 13.dxe5! { I think this move that builds pawn majority on the kingside is really testing. } 13...Bxe5 14.f4 Bg7 15.Ng3 Be6 { 15...Bg4 16.Qc2 Qd7 was played in Shankland-Grandelius (2021) and here I would suggest an improvement over Sam's 17. Rf2 (which is also interesting): 17.f5! with certain issues with Bg4. } 16.Qe2 { Black's position looks shaky. } 16...Bxa2! { is the best move. It is not even about winning a pawn here, but mostly acquiring the b3-square for the bishop. Anyway, here, White can proceed with either } 17.f5 { or } { 17.e5 , in both cases with promising positions. } ) ( { • } 10...Qc7 { This is one of the old lines. The main idea is to play ...Rd8 and exert some pressure on the center. However, putting the queen so early (and voluntarily) on c7 has a drawback in that White can play Rc1 and in case of ...cxd4 and opening of the c-file, the queen would run under some pressure. } 11.Rc1! Rd8 { Here, many moves have been played in the past, but I think that the strongest here is } { If 11...b6 then 12.h4! is an improved version of 10...b6 line as Black's queen does not come to h4. } 12.h4! { Black has many moves here, but the best one is } 12...e6! { with idea of ...Qe7. } 13.Bg5! { White should not allow it! } 13...Rd7 14.Qe1!? { getting the queen out of the d-file and preparing d5. White is better. } ) ( { • } 10...e6!? { This line is actually a legit option for Black. Also developed in the 2010s, it acts against d5 in many lines, but also it prevents h4 ideas from White. } 11.dxc5 { grabbing the pawn is the most critical approach. } 11...Qa5 { After 11...Ne5 White has two options, the more aggressive 12.Bb3!? or 12.Qxd8 Rxd8 13.Rfd1! Such endgames are normally better for White. } 12.f4! Rd8 { Here White has some choice. I analyzed deeply the following 13. Qe1, 13. Qc2 and 13. Qb3, with the first two being perhaps the most promising, but 13. Qb3 can be also testing if one does not remember lines with Black. } 13.Qe1!? { This move is perhaps the best try for White. } 13...Qa4 14.Bb3 Qxe4 15.Ng3 Qd3 16.Rc1! { This is a challenging line. White wants Qf2 and Rfd1 with some initiative. This was played recently by Gukesh and Praggnanandhaa. } ) ( { • } 10...e6!? 11.dxc5 Qa5 12.f4! Rd8 13.Qc2 { with the idea of f5. } 13...Bf8 14.f5 { 14.Nd4!? Qxc5 15.Bb3 is also good for White, preparing f5 for later or maybe a more positional approach with e5. } 14...Bxc5 15.Nd4 { Here Black cannot take on d4, like in the same position with Qb3 instead of Qc2: I'll show you why: } 15...Nxd4?? 16.cxd4 Bxd4 17.Bxd4 Rxd4 { runs into } 18.fxg6 hxg6 19.Qf2 { with a double attack on the rook and the f7-pawn, only possible when the queen is on c2. } { @@StartFEN@@r1br2k1/pp3p1p/2n1p1p1/q1b2P2/2BNP3/2P1B3/P1Q3PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@ 15...exf5?! 16.exf5 Bxd4 17.Bxf7+! is incredibly risky for Black, as in Bacrot-Krasenkow (2011). } ) { Therefore, Black should go for @@StartFEN@@r1br2k1/pp3p1p/2n1p1p1/q1b2P2/2BNP3/2P1B3/P1Q3PP/R4RK1 b - - 1 15@@EndFEN@@ 15...Ne5 16.Be2 when I think Black still needs to work hard to earn equality. } ( { • } 10...e6!? 11.dxc5 Qa5 12.f4! Rd8 13.Qb3 Bf8 14.f5 Bxc5 15.Nd4 { here Black can equalize by force after } 15...Nxd4 16.cxd4 Rxd4! 17.fxe6 Rxe4 18.exf7+ Kf8 19.Bxc5+ Qxc5+ 20.Kh1 Qxc4 21.Qb2! { and here thanks to ...Rf4 idea Black should hold. Still, it requires a good calculation and play from Black to retain the balance. } ) 
11. Rc1 { This turned out to be the most popular line against 10...b6 recently. } ( { • } 11.dxc5 Qc7 12.Nd4 Ne5 13.Nb5 Qb8 { has been topical throughout the 2010s but the current state of theory here is that Black holds comfortably. White tried many things here and possibly some things still should be discovered but overall I do not expect much trouble for Black. In general, the trend switched to different attempts. } ) ( { • } 11.h4!? { A new approach to 10...b6 line that I had looked at some time ago and then there was a game Praggnanandhaa-Giri (2022) in which Pragg convincingly won. After analyzing it deeper, I figured this is a pretty good and testing try too. } 11...e6 12.h5 Qh4 { a usual response by Black. } 13.Qc1! { This is a deep idea played by Pragg. } { 13.hxg6 hxg6 14.f3 Bb7 does not offer that much to White. } 13...cxd4 14.cxd4 Bb7! 15.h6 Bf6 16.f3 { As my analysis shows, this position can be quite challenging to play with Black. } { 14...Qxe4?! was played by Giri and here, after 15.Rd1↑ White has a dangerous initiative! }) Bb7 
12. Bb5 Rc8 
13. Qd2 ( { Again the most popular move. } 13.Bxc6!? { One of my suggestions here would be this line. It has been played only in some correspondence games so far. It is a rare and fresh approach that, if Black is not familiar with it, can pose serious problems. } 13...Rxc6 { 13...Bxc6 14.d5 is less good as Black's pieces will be here more passive. } 14.d5 Rd6 15.c4 { Here, Black must challenge White's center - otherwise White's space advantage will become pretty much overwhelming. } 15...e6! 16.Qd2 f5! 17.Bg5! { The best chance for White. Black needs to decide where the queen goes which is a practical problem to resolve. } ) e6 ( 13...cxd4!? 14.cxd4 Qd6 { was tried recently in Ding-Rapport game from Candidates 2022 and I think it is an excellent option for Black. There are not many games played so far but clearly, we can expect further developments here. } 15.Rfd1 Na5! 16.d5 { With correct play Black should equalize here, but as analysis shows there still could be some difficulties. } { Rapport played 15...Qb4?! 16.Qd3 but it does not bring much to Black and White should be better. }) 
14. Rfd1 cxd4 ( 14...a6!? { is the main alternative. Here I would suggest following a game Sjugirov-Ivic (2021). } 15.Bxc6 Bxc6 16.d5 Ba4 17.Re1 exd5 18.exd5 h6! { (preparing ...Qh4) } 19.c4 Qh4 20.Qd3 { with the idea of Qa3 with some pressure. } ) 
15. cxd4 Na5 ( 15...Qd6 { leaves the h4-square unattended and in a way it is a worse version of what Rapport played against Ding. } 16.Bf4! Qa3 17.h4↑ { 16...e5 17.d5! is also very shaky for Black. }) 
16. Rxc8 Qxc8 
17. Bg5! { Threatening to win the exchange with Be7. I analyzed this position quite extensively and my conclusion is that White should have decent chances. } *

