1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 cxd4 
10. cxd4 Qa5+ 
11. Bd2 ( { In my game in 2010 against Piotr Bobras, I played } 11.Kf1!? { , but it is not that great. There is no reason to take away the right to castle voluntarily. } ) Qd8 { The most solid response. Black is content with repeating moves, but White should not concede to that and be ambitious. } 
12. Bc3! { Supporting the center and avoiding repetition. And additionally, the bishop on c3 neutralizes its counterpart on g7, and potentially these bishops will be traded - which generally works in White's favor. } O-O 
13. Qd2! { An important move. White delays castling - which is actually quite common in modern chess. First, White fully secures the center, given that there's always time for O-O. Additionally, at times White may play h4-h5 and activate the h1-rook! But of course, more standard O-O, Rac1, and d5 with central play is also good. } ( { The direct } 13.O-O { is met by } 13...Bg4! 14.f3 Bd7 { and surprisingly, there could be certain issues with holding the center. One of the main ideas is to play ...b5!? and there are ideas of ...Nxd4 in various versions. For example: } 15.Qd2 b5! 16.Bxb5 Nxd4 17.Nxd4 Bxb5 18.Nxb5 Qb6+! { That's why 13...Bg4 was played - now this check is vital! } 19.Nd4 e5= { and Black should be completely fine here. } ) Bd7 
14. O-O { Now, White can play this move safely as there is no f3 played, and any attempts of ...b5 and ...Nxd4 will not work. } Rc8 
15. Rac1 {[%mdl 32768]} a6 
16. Bb3 {[%cal Gd4d5]} -- ( { This is simply a much better version of the main line. White will potentially play d5, leading to the trade of dark-squared bishops. A sample continuation is } 16...b5 17.d5 Bxc3 18.Rxc3 Ne5 19.Rxc8 Qxc8 20.Qd4 Qc7 21.f4 Nc4 22.Bxc4 bxc4 23.Nc3 $16 { and White's knight is better than Black's bishop. } )
*

