23. Nd4! ( { Here, Black has a difficult choice again. } 23.Kh1!? { another option. White moves the king away from any possible checks and sets a trap. } 23...Kh8! 24.e6 Be8 25.h4 $13 { 23...fxe5? 24.d6! exd6 25.fxe5 $16 }) fxe5?! ( 23...Kg7 24.Qe3!? { the potential ideas of d6, e6, f5 or h4 could be unpleasant to meet. And if } 24...fxe5 25.fxe5 Bxe5 { then } 26.Rxf8 Qxf8 27.Bf5! { is tricky for Black too, e.g. } 27...Bxh2+ 28.Kxh2 gxf5 29.Kg1!?↑ { and Black still has to do some work to fully equalize due to the weak king. } ) 
24. f5!! {[%cal Gf5g6,Ge4h7][%csl Gf5,Rg6,Rh7]} -- ( { This continuation is highly risky for Black, even if the engine finds equality in the end... The king is very weak, and we have a powerful attack on the light squares. } 24...gxf5 25.Qg5+ Kh8 26.Nxf5 Bxf5 27.Bxf5 Qe8 28.Rf3↑ { . } { We don't care about our knight as long as we can get to Black's king, who is missing the g7-bishop: 24...exd4 25.fxg6 hxg6 26.Qg5 with a crushing attack - there is no good way to protect g6. } )
