12. Rb1 Qc7 { The main move in this position. } 
13. Qd2 {[%mdl 32768]} Rfd8 { This move has been tried recently a couple of times too, most notably by Ian Nepomniachtchi and Sam Shankland. In my opinion, though the rook performs important functions on f8 as in many lines it supports the kingside and also helps with ...f5 ideas. For this reason, I consider 13... Rfd8 inferior to 13... Rad8. There are some interesting options for White, but I would suggest either 14. Rfc1 or 14. Bh6!?. } 
14. Bh6!? { Is an interesting alternative to normal 14. Rfc1. I think it is extremely dangerous to Black, especially if unfamiliar with the line. 14. Rfc1!? This is the main move which of course can be played too, with 'normal' play. } cxd4! ( { Other moves are worse. A) } 14...Bh8 { Generally it helps White to push back this bishop. } 15.Bf4 Qc8 { 15...e5 16.Bg3 $16 } 16.Rfc1 Be8 17.Bg5 $16 ) ( { B) } 14...e5?! 15.d5 Na5 16.Bd3 $16 { is great for White as Black would benefit a lot from having ...Rf8 here which would support potentially ...f5. Actually, one of the best moves for Black here is } 16...Rf8 { which speaks for itself... } ) ( { C) } 14...e6 15.Bxg7 Kxg7 16.h4 $14 { without dark-squared bishops and with ...e6 played, Black's kingside looks pretty vulnerable. } ) 
15. Bxg7! ( { Black's idea unfolds after } 15.cxd4 Nxd4! 16.Bxf7+ Kxf7 17.Nxd4 Bf6 $13 { with an unclear position. } ) d3! ( { The best reply, leading to a sharp fight, yet Black is on the brink of losing a miniature here... } 15...Kxg7 16.cxd4 $16 { is obviously something that White wants. } ) 
16. Qh6! ( 16.Bh6 dxe2 17.Qxe2 { is also quite interesting, with some pressure; but the text move is more testing. } ) dxe2?? { Suddenly loses. } 
17. Bxf7+!! Kxf7 
18. Qxh7 exf1=Q+ 
19. Rxf1+- {[%cal Rg7e5]} { And Black is either getting mated or will lose lots of material (Be5 is a big threat). } *

