3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } Bg4 
11. f3 Bd7 { This line became popular mid 2010s and is still quite popular these days (perhaps it is the second most popular variation against Bc4-Ne2). The idea is to provoke f3, which can be useful sometimes for Black, and it improves on the 10...Bd7 variation. } 
12. Rb1 Qc7 { The main move in this position. } 
13. Qd2 Rad8 ( { In this line, generally, this is the rook that should go to d8. } 13...a6 { Black may try ...a6-b5 setup even though it does not bring anything great: } 14.Rfc1 b5 15.Bb3 Rfd8 16.h4 $14 { 15...c4 16.Bc2 $14 }) ( 13...Nxd4 { is actually the same as 13... cxd4 [/variation/21151924/#/13/b]: } 14.cxd4 cxd4 15.Bxf7+ Rxf7 16.Nxd4 ) 
14. Rfc1 Bc8 { Here, White has a lot of options. I would suggest two that I like the most but there are other as well. } 
15. h4 { I would recommend going for this typical plan. It is extremely common in these positions here. } Na5 
16. Bd3 Nc6!? { Black can try to put pressure in the center, but this looks pretty awkward. Black in a way loses some tempi. } 
17. h5 {[%mdl 32768]} gxh5 { Something like this is really difficult to play for people. } 
18. Qc2! e5 
19. d5! {[%cal Ge2g3]} -- ( { This is problematic for Black too: } 19...Ne7 20.Ng3 h4 21.Nh5 f5 22.Qf2 $14 { White wins back the pawn (both c5 and h4 pawns are under attack) and with Nh5 Black's position looks pretty uncomfortable. White can win a pair of bishops with Nxg7 when convenient. } )
