14. Kxf1 { This is the main position of this line. I admit openly that I don't really know the history of how the theory developed here over the years, however I will do my best to analyze the line as thoroughly as possible and provide more than sufficient guidance to anyone who plays it. } cxd4 
15. cxd4 { This position is achievable if Black begins with 12... cxd4. In my opinion, this trade of pawns really serves White as it can be (nearly) done anytime by Black and additionally in some lines the c3-pawn may be a target. } Qb6 { This move was tried even by Garry Kasparov himself in his match against Anatoly Karpov. I am not sure what was the theory back in the day, but retracing steps and checking it with the engine gave me a better understanding of this line. One of Black's ideas is to play ...Qe6 and create a double attack on pawns e4 and g4. Another one, if possible, quickly activate all the pieces (...Rf8, ...Nc4, ...Qb2 etc). } 
16. Kg1! { I believe that the king must be put to safety first, even at a cost of a pawn. } Qe6 
17. Qd3 Qxg4 ( { With pawns still on c3 and c5, Black could play } 17...Qc4 { trying to get to the endgame. Here, White has an additional option of } 18.Qd2! $16 { with a tempo on the knight! } ) 
18. Rf1 { This continuation was tried in many games, including Karpov-Kasparov (1987). } Rc8 
19. h3 Qd7 
20. d5 Nc4 
21. Bd4 e5! ( { A typical idea. } 21...Ne5? 22.Qd1 $16 ) 
22. dxe6 Qxe6 
23. Bxg7 Kxg7 
24. Nf4 Qd6 
25. Qc3+ Kh6 { So far we have been following Karpov's footsteps (Kasparov's moves were by far the best ones too) and only now I would suggest an improvement. } 
26. Nd3 $146  {[%csl Ge5,Rh6]} ( { Fighting for the e5-square and trying to exploit Black's vulnerable king. } 26.Nd5 { was Karpov's move but here Kasparov equalized with } 26...Qe5! 27.Qd3 Kg7 28.Nf6 Qd6= { the game was eventually drawn after a long fight. } ) Nb6 { Is more resilient. Here, White has two options. 27. Qd2+ and 27. Qb3. } 
27. Qd2+ {[%mdl 32768]} ( 27.Qb3 { Trying to keep queens on the board and achieve Nf2-Ng4. } 27...Qd4+ 28.Nf2 Kg7 29.Qa3 { Black should be able to hold it but of course, he is under some pressure. } ) Kg7 
28. Qb2+ Kg8 
29. Qb3+ { White wins a pawn, as ...Nc4 is forced. } Nc4 
30. Qxb7 Qb6+ 
31. Qxb6 axb6 
32. Rf2 $14  {[%csl Ge4]} { With an extra pawn. Of course, Black has good chances to hold it, but still, the game is pretty much on two results. } *

