The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } Bg4 
11. f3 Na5 { This is the old main line that was extremely popular back even 1950s I believe. It was also played numerous times in the 4th Karpov-Kasparov match in 1987. } 
12. Bxf7+ { This would be my suggestion. There are two reasons why I recommend this line: first, it grabs a pawn and Black still needs to show compensation for it, and second, this is what Stockfish likes the most! } ( 12.Bd3 { is another popular line that I do not consider in this course, however, it is also incredibly interesting and leads to fighting positions. The line goes like this: } 12...cxd4 13.cxd4 Be6 14.d5!? Bxa1 15.Qxa1 f6 { with lots of theory. White sacrificed an exchange to weaken Black's king and build a strong center. Maybe there will be a course on this at some point! } ) Rxf7 
13. fxg4 Rxf1+ 
14. Kxf1 { This is the main position of this line. I admit openly that I don't really know the history of how the theory developed here over the years, however I will do my best to analyze the line as thoroughly as possible and provide more than sufficient guidance to anyone who plays it. } cxd4 
15. cxd4 { This position is achievable if Black begins with 12... cxd4. In my opinion, this trade of pawns really serves White as it can be (nearly) done anytime by Black and additionally in some lines the c3-pawn may be a target. } e5 { I believe that this move is the most natural follow-up to the trade on d4. If Black played it before this trade, not only there could have been an idea of dxc5 which is not the case here, but also after simple d5 the c5-pawn would be immediately attacked. } ( 15...Qd6? { after the trade of c-pawns, this move is just bad. The release of the tension rids White of the potential weak c3-pawn and the c-file can be controlled by White too. } 16.e5! Qd5 17.g5 Rd8 18.Qc2 $16 ) 
16. d5 Nc4 
17. Qd3! b5 ( { It makes sense to keep the knight active and it was played in many games too. } 17...Nd6 18.Bc5 Rc8 19.Bxd6 Qxd6 20.Rb1 b6 21.Ng1 $16 { White got what he wanted! } ) 
18. Bf2!? {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Ge2c3]} { This deserves serious attention. White's knight may go to c3. } Rc8 
19. Nc3 ( 19.Bxa7 { White can grab this pawn, but unfortunately Black obtains now a lot of activity. } 19...Ra8!? 20.Bf2 Ra3 21.Qc2 Qa5 $13 ) a6 { Here, White has a very strong move in his hand. } 
20. d6!! {[%csl Gd5]} { White returns a pawn to access the d5-square and dramatically changes the flow of the game. Earlier, Black was looking for the compensation being a pawn down and now it is White that has a nice piece play and an initiative. } Nxd6 ( 20...Qxd6 21.Nd5 $14 { is similar. Of course, White wants to keep queens on board. } ) 
21. Kg1 $14  {[%cal Ga1d1,Gc3d5,Yh2h4,Yh4h5][%csl Rg7,Gd5]} { Keeping our king safe. Next, we'll improve our rook with Rd1. Our control of the d5-square, where our knight can land, gives us a long-term advantage. From a practical point of view, this position is hard to play for Black because we have many dynamic ideas - maybe even h4-h5! } *

