18. cxd4 b5! { Black wants to make use of the pawn majority on the queenside. } 
19. Nf3 a5 { This is an important position. Now, White has a couple of options. I am not sure which one is objectively the best, but each of them can be really tried as they require Black to be very accurate to hold it. } 
20. Bf2!? {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5]} { This is a decent alternative. White wants h4-h5! } b4 
21. h4! Rc8 {[%csl Gc4]} ( { Black should support the c4-knight as sometimes Rc1 may be problematic. For example, ...a4-Rb8 with an idea of ...b3 is too naive: } 21...a4 22.Kg1 Rb8? 23.Rc1! { and suddenly Black loses the blockade. } 23...Nb6 24.Rc5+- ) 
22. Kg1 { Here, Black has only one good move. } Bh6!! ( { Black must improve his worst piece. Also, Black provokes g5 which makes h5 ideas less effective, as the analysis shows. } 22...a4? { runs into } 23.Rb1! { with problems. } 23...b3 24.axb3 axb3 25.Rxb3 Nxe5 26.Rb5 Nxf3+ 27.gxf3 $16 { with a healthy extra pawn for White! } ) 
23. g5 Bf8 
24. h5 gxh5! 
25. Rf1!? -- ( { Here, we can go very deep of course. In general, though, I think that White has decent practical chances. Black's king is weak and Black needs to be careful here. It is a playable position but I believe White has an easier game. Some example lines: } 25...a4 26.Qd3 Rc6 27.Be3 Bg7 28.Bf4 Nb6 29.Nh4 e6 30.g6 h6 31.Kh2↑ { 25.Nh4!? e6 26.g6 h6 27.Rf1 Bg7 28.Nf3 a4 29.Rb1↑ } )
