[ECO "D86"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } Bg4 
11. f3 Na5 { This is the old main line that was extremely popular back even 1950s I believe. It was also played numerous times in the 4th Karpov-Kasparov match in 1987. } 
12. Bxf7+ { This would be my suggestion. There are two reasons why I recommend this line: first, it grabs a pawn and Black still needs to show compensation for it, and second, this is what Stockfish likes the most! } ( 12.Bd3 { is another popular line that I do not consider in this course, however, it is also incredibly interesting and leads to fighting positions. The line goes like this: } 12...cxd4 13.cxd4 Be6 14.d5!? Bxa1 15.Qxa1 f6 { with lots of theory. White sacrificed an exchange to weaken Black's king and build a strong center. Maybe there will be a course on this at some point! } ) Rxf7 
13. fxg4 Rxf1+ 
14. Kxf1 { This is the main position of this line. I admit openly that I don't really know the history of how the theory developed here over the years, however I will do my best to analyze the line as thoroughly as possible and provide more than sufficient guidance to anyone who plays it. } Qd6 { I think this is the best option for Black here. } 
15. e5!? ( { I think that this move is the most challenging as White builds a strong center and makes Bg7 really bad. On the other hand, however, Black has now nice control over the light squares so there is this trade-off. Still, I think it is White's best chance. } 15.Kg1 { is another decent option that definitely can be tried too. However, I like } ) ( 15.e5 { - I believe it poses serious practical problems to Black. } ) Qe6 { This is a possible alternative but it looks somewhat odd to place the queen there when it can go to more active d5-square. } 
16. Nf4! {[%mdl 32768]} Rf8 
17. Kg1 Qc4 { In case ...Qd5 was played, there could have been ...Qe4 available! } 
18. Qd2 { I think that Black's position is quite dangerous here. The extra pawn means something and I don't see immediate counterplay. White consolidated in the center and enjoys a certain advantage. Perhaps the critical line now is following: } cxd4 
19. cxd4 Bh6! { Improving a terrible bishop. } 
20. Nd5!? ( 20.g3!? $14 { is also better for White. } ) Qxd5 
21. Bxh6 Rd8 
22. Rd1 Nc6 
23. Be3 $14  { But even here White is better. White's plan is to regroup and create some attack against Black's king. Black faces a long defense ahead. } *

