24. Bf2 Qc6 
25. Re1 ( 25.Bxa7 e6! { with the threat of ...b6 pretty much nearly forces the bishop to go back. } 26.Bd4 { and then } 26...Rxf3! 27.gxf3 Nd2! { gives Black a strong compensation, e.g. } 28.Qd1 Nxf3+ 29.Kf2 Nxd4 30.cxd4 Qe4!= ) e6 { Some choice now. } 
26. h3!? ( { Perhaps trying to be 'smart' is a decent try for White. } 26.Ng5 { is interesting and playable too. } 26...Re8 27.h4!? ) ( 26.Nd4 { in this way White can also transpose to 23. Rd1. [/variation/21215273/#/23/w] } 26...Bxd4 27.cxd4 Qd5 ) a6 { A very human move, but it is a bit inaccurate. } 
27. Nd4 Bxd4 
28. cxd4 { Here, we have a bit better version of 23. Rd1 line, as Black played ...a6 and normally Black plays ...b5 and ...a5, while here Black wasted a tempo on ...a6. } b5 
29. Re2 Qd5 
30. Kh2 $13  { Of course, still nothing special, but playable. } *

