11. Bd3 b6 { This move is pretty much necessary. } 
12. Rc1 e5 { This is what Black generally does in this line. After kicking away the bishop from c4, there are no Bd5 ideas, and in the event of d5 Black can choose and/or combine from ...c4, ...f5 and ...Nb7-Nd6 ideas. } 
13. dxe5!? { A very aggressive option towards which the trend shifted recently due to games Shankland-Grandelius (2020) and Salem-Shirov (2020). } ( 13.dxc5 Be6 14.c4 { is a more positional approach. White just grabs a pawn and attempts to prove its worth. } 14...bxc5 15.Bxc5 Bh6 16.Rc3 Re8 17.Qc2 Qc7 18.Ba3 Rab8 19.h3 { This was played in Aronian-Mamedyarov (2018). Here, Mamedyarov made a mistake, while } 19...Nc6! { is the correct move, with an unclear game. } { 19...Red8?! 20.Bc1! $14 Aronian-Mamedyarov (2018); after 20...Bf8 21.Bg5! followed by c5 is unpleasant for Black. } ) Bxe5 { Black definitely should recapture the pawn, even though the practice has seen an alternative approach too. } 
14. f4 Bg7 
15. Ng3 { Here Black has some choice. } Be6! {[%cal Ga5c4][%csl Ra2]} { No matter how scary it looks, Black needs to play this move. There are two ideas - The greedy ...Bxa2, of course, and making use of c4-square with ...Nc4 or ...Bc4. } 
16. Qe2! {[%mdl 32768]} { Controlling the c4-square and in some way defending the a2-pawn (or at least keeping an eye on it). } Bxa2! {[%csl Gb3]} { Black must be super greedy and have nerves of steel to keep the balance here. No doubt, over the board playing like that is not easy. Black's idea of capturing this pawn is not really for the sake of capturing the pawn - it is more about gaining the b3-square for the bishop. } 
17. e5!? Bb3 
18. Ne4 Qd5! { This move is also the only way for Black to maintain the balance. } 
19. c4 { Main try here. } Qd7 
20. h4!? ( { It makes sense to launch an attack on the kingside. I like } 20.Nd6 { less as even though the knight is well placed here, for now, it is not clear if it could not have been more useful on the kingside. } 20...Ba4 21.Bf2 f6! { and this is another drawback of Nd6 - this center undermining is now possible. } 22.Be4 Bc6 $13 ) Rad8 
21. Rc3 h5 ( { The only move. } 21...f5? { is bad due to } 22.Ng5 { with the unstoppable idea of h5. } 22...Ba4 23.h5 $16 { 22...h5? 23.Ra1+- and the bishop is trapped! }) 
22. Ng5! { Black is under pressure here, even though with correct play he manages to save it. } f6!! { This crazy, unbelievable move is actually legit. White has many tries here, but it all fizzles out in the end. After anything else, White has a strong initiative, but engines manage to hold Black's position with this ridiculously-looking move. } 
23. Nh7!? ( { This move seems to be winning on the spot, but in fact, it doesn't. } 23.e6!? Qe7 24.Bxg6 fxg5 25.Rxb3 g4! { Black holds here. } 26.Rd3 { 26.Bf7+ Rxf7 27.exf7+ Qxf7 28.Rd3 Re8! 29.Rfd1 Nc6! $13 } 26...Qxe6 27.f5 Qe5 28.Rxd8 Rxd8 29.Bxh5 Rd4!! { another crazy move that holds the balance. Again Black manages to hold this crazy position, e. g. } 30.f6 Bxf6 31.Qf2 Rd6 32.Bg5 Qxg5 33.hxg5 Bd4 34.Re1 Bxf2+ 35.Kxf2 Nxc4 36.Re8+ { with a draw. } ) ( 23.f5!? fxg5 24.f6 { leads to an absurd mess too where Black also manages to make a draw in the end. } 24...gxh4 25.Rxb3 Nxb3 26.Bxg6 Qg4! 27.f7+ Kh8 28.Qxg4 hxg4 29.e6 Nd4 30.e7 Ne2+ 31.Kf2 Ng3 32.Bg5 Bd4+ 33.Ke1 Bc3+ 34.Kf2 Bd4+ { with a draw! } ) Bxc4!! ( { Surprisingly, this works and it is still equal! } 23...Kxh7? 24.Qxh5+ Kg8 25.Bxg6+- ) 
24. Nxf6+ Rxf6 
25. Bxc4+ { It looks like we are winning, but engines find a precise way to hold. } Nxc4 
26. exf6 ( { Winning the exchange is our best practical chance because, unfortunately, } 26.Qxc4+ Re6 { is fine for Black. } ) Nxe3 
27. Rxe3 Bxf6 
28. Kh2 $13  {[%cal Ge3e6,Gf4f5,Ge2c4,Ge2c2][%csl Rg8,Rg6]} { The position is objectively equal but it is still quite playable. I believe White can push for a win risk-free: Black's queenside pawns are not that far advanced and his king is still weak. Both Re6 and f5 have potential and our queen can pose problems. } *

