The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } Qc7 { This move is the most popular choice over the time, however recently it is not as popular as it used to be. I would say that this line is nearly forgotten, and perhaps for a reason - alternatives are simply better according to modern engines, so the trend shifted. However, it is useful to understand why 10... Qc7 went out of fashion.

I believe the main reason for that is that the queen has no role in supporting the queenside and plans with h4 become right now extremely annoying. Additionally, when White plays Rc1, the queen would be always under some potential X-ray and ...cxd4 unlikely would be a good idea for Black. } 
11. Rc1! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc1c7][%csl Rc7]} b6 { This move was played twice by Sam Shankland, but quite a long time ago (2013 and 2016). The idea is to bring a8-rook to d8. Still, in comparison with immediate 10... b6 Black wasted a tempo on ...Qc7 which is not really useful. } 
12. h4! { Without Black's queen on d8, this idea is generally stronger than with the Qd8. } Na5 { Black can include these moves but it mostly helps White. } 
13. Bd3 Bb7 
14. h5 Qd7?! { A rather awkward move after ...Qc7 was played earlier. It was successful in an online rapid game Salem-Tari (2017) but the engine is pretty much just refuting it. } 
15. h6! ( { A logical improvement over } 15.f3 { , played in the aforementioned game. } ) Bh8 
16. e5! { Locks up the bishop for now with a big advantage for White. } c4 ( { Forcing the bishop away to attempt ...f6. } 16...f6? { is even worse due to } 17.Qc2!+- ) 
17. Bc2 f6 
18. exf6! Bxf6 
19. Ng3 $16  {[%cal Gg3e4]} { With a big positional advantage, despite the bishop getting out. } *

