[Black "11...Rd8 12.h4 e6 #6"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21290553"]
[ECO "D86"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } Qc7 { This move is the most popular choice over the time, however recently it is not as popular as it used to be. I would say that this line is nearly forgotten, and perhaps for a reason - alternatives are simply better according to modern engines, so the trend shifted. However, it is useful to understand why 10... Qc7 went out of fashion.

I believe the main reason for that is that the queen has no role in supporting the queenside and plans with h4 become right now extremely annoying. Additionally, when White plays Rc1, the queen would be always under some potential X-ray and ...cxd4 unlikely would be a good idea for Black. } 
11. Rc1! {[%cal Gc1c7][%csl Rc7]} Rd8 ( { The most popular move here. Others are not great either but have been tried by strong GMs, so they definitely deserve attention. } 11...Na5 12.Bd3 { The inclusion of these moves helps White as the knight is on the rim not doing much. Very often there is a transposition to lines analyzed elsewhere: } 12...Rd8 { 12...b6 13.h4 is analyzed after [/variation/21290535/#/11/b] 11... b6 12. h4 Na5 13. Bd3 } 13.h4 { is analyzed after 12... Na5 13. Bd3 Rd8 } ) 
12. h4!? { A typical idea in these positions, but again, after the queen moved to c7, h4 acquires additional strength as ...e5 or ...e6 does not allow the queen to go to the kingside. } e6! { I believe that this is the only move here after which Black is not much worse. The idea is... to bring the queen to e7! This already proves that the Qc7 line cannot be good. } ( 12...Bd7? { is even worse than ...Bg4-Bd7. } 13.h5 $16 ) 
13. Bg5! ( { A good tempo move, provoking weakening of Black's kingside. } 13.h5 Qe7 $14 { and the queen gets where it belongs. The engine claims it is quite acceptable for Black, but of course, White is still better. } ) Rd7 { Not the ideal square for the rook, but there is none better. } 
14. Qe1! { An instructive move - the queen goes away from the pin preparing d5. It is worth noting that the pawn on d4, even though is attacked many times, cannot be captured due to again Rc1 eyeing the Qc7. } a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} { The idea of ...b5 makes sense but White's initiative is fast and strong. } 
15. d5! {[%mdl 32768]} exd5 
16. Bxd5 b5 
17. h5 $16  {[%cal Gh5h6,Gf2f4]} -- ( { With ideas of h6, f4 etc. For instance, } 17...Bb7 18.h6 Bh8 19.f4 c4 20.Rd1 Re8 21.Qf2 $16 )
*

