3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } e6 { There are two ideas behind this move. One, it stops (at least for now) h4 ideas, and two, it does not allow White comfortably play d5 gaining the space. Recently it has gained some popularity. It is definitely less explored than 10...b6 which has been the mainstream theory for the past few years so some people may try it to avoid learning those lines and choose something less common.

White has some options now but I haven't found an objective advantage for White. This line is pretty decent, however, Black really needs to know many things. } 
11. dxc5 { Capturing this pawn is by far the most critical option that must be investigated. } Qa5 { This is the main move. } 
12. f4! Rd8 { This is the critical position in this line. White has some choice now. I think that three moves 13. Qb3, 13. Qc2 and 13. Qe1 are all tricky for Black. } 
13. Qb3 { This move can be tried too. Black can equalize perhaps with one forcing line but some things were there still not explored. } Bf8 { This is critical for the entire line. } 
14. f5! {[%mdl 32768]} Bxc5 
15. Nd4 { Here Black must go for a forced sequence. } Nxd4 
16. cxd4 Rxd4! ( 16...Bxd4? 17.Bxd4 Rxd4 18.fxe6+- { destroying Black's kingside. } ) 
17. fxe6 Rxc4?? { This move lost quickly in L'Ami - Harika (2012). } 
18. exf7+ Kf8 
19. Kh1! -- ( { And the f7-pawn is too strong, just as Black's king is too weak. } 19...Bxe3 20.Qxe3 g5 21.e5 h6 22.e6 Bxe6 23.Qxe6 Rc6 24.Qe4 Qc3 25.Rae1 Kg7 26.f8=Q+ { 1-0 (26) L'Ami, E (2596)-Harika, D (2516) Wijk aan Zee 2012. } )
