[Black "13...e6 14.Rfd1 a6 #2"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21328445"]
[ECO "D86"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } b6 
11. Rc1 Bb7 
12. Bb5 Rc8 
13. Qd2 { The main line nowadays in the 10... b6 line. } e6 
14. Rfd1 a6!? { This move was played in Sjugirov-Ivic (2021) and I think it is a pretty good way to fight for equality. } 
15. Bxc6 Bxc6 ( { This move seems more normal than the previously [/variation/21328444/#/15/b] analyzed } 15...Rxc6 ) 
16. d5! {[%mdl 32768]} exd5 ( { Black can play } 16...Ba4 17.Re1 { at first, but anyway ...exd5 should be played sooner or later. } ) 
17. exd5 Ba4 
18. Re1 h6! {[%cal Gh6g5,Gd8h4][%csl Rg5]} { This move had to be prepared by Ivic as he was still playing quickly. As far as I understand, the idea of this move is to prevent Bg5 in some lines and prepare ...Qh4. I analyzed it for a long time and I could not find here any idea that could objectively give an advantage, but there are at least some practical tries. } ( 18...c4?! 19.Ng3 Qd7 20.d6 Rfd8 21.Bf4 $14 { looks really unpleasant for Black. The d6-pawn is strong and potential h4-h5 could launch a strong attack. } ) 
19. c4 { I think that this could be the best try for White. Even though the position is approximately equal, it is not so easy to play for Black. This is also what Sjugirov played. Engines claim equality here, but due to Black's mistake, White got a much better position very quickly. } ( 19.Bxh6 Bxh6 20.Qxh6 Qxd5 { is just equal. } ) ( 19.Ng3!? { A new move which is quite challenging. The idea is to get the knight to e4. Black needs to play now the following moves... } 19...Qh4! 20.Bf4 Rce8! { and here Black will eventually manage to equalize. Tactically everything holds just fine for Black, even though it's pretty close... } 21.Ne4 { This move looks really promising and at first I thought it could be giving White an advantage. Unfortunately, Black forces a draw here. } { 21.f3 Rxe1 22.Rxe1 Re8! simplifying the position equalizes. But not 22...Bxc3?? 23.Qxc3 Qxf4 24.Re4+- 23.Ne4 f5 24.Bg3 Qd8 25.Nd6 Rxe1+ 26.Qxe1 Kh7 with an equal endgame. } 21...f5! 22.Nd6 Rxe1+ 23.Rxe1 Bxc3! 24.Qxc3 Qxf4 { even though this position looks quite scary for Black, due to White's back rank issues, it is just fine. } 25.Re6 Qd4! 26.Qxd4 cxd4 27.Kf1 Kg7 28.Ke2 Bb5+! { A final important move, stopping Kd3. And if } 29.Nxb5 axb5 30.Kd3 { then Black activates his rook with a draw: } 30...Ra8! 31.Re2 Kf6 32.Kxd4 Ra4+ ) Qh4! 
20. Qd3! {[%cal Gd3a3][%csl Gc4]} ( { Right now, we can't play } 20.Nc3 { due to } 20...Qxc4 { . This move protects the c-pawn and prepares Qa3. } ) Rfe8 ( 20...Bd7 21.Qa3 Ra8 22.Qb3 $14 { and our pressure on b6 could be annoying in the long term. Our next moves could be Bd2-Bc3 to trade Black's important dark-square bishop. } ) 
21. Qa3 {[%csl Ra4,Ra6]} { As announced! Here is the critical position. Black has to decide what to do about our threat against the a4-bishop: retreat it or support it? It's by no means easy - both options involve a pawn sacrifice. } Bd7? { A mistake! } 
22. Qxa6 Be5 
23. Ng3 $16  -- ( { With an extra pawn and great winning chances. In the game Sjugirov-Ivic (2022), followed } 23...f5 24.Qxb6 f4 { and here Sjugirov should have given a piece with } 25.Bxc5! { instead of 25.Qxg6+? after which the game eventually ended in a draw. } 25...fxg3 26.Qxg6+ Bg7 { 26...Kh8 27.hxg3+- } 27.Rxe8+ Rxe8 28.hxg3+- { and White has way too many pawns for a piece. } )
*

