17. Bg5 ( { The only way to pose problems to Black. } 17.f3 { does not lead anywhere: } 17...fxe4 18.fxe4 exd5 19.exd5 Rxf1+ 20.Rxf1 Rf6= ) Qe8! ( { This is the best retreat for Black that equalizes. However, in a practical game, it may not be easy to be found. } 17...Bf6 18.Bxf6 Qxf6 19.f3 $14 { The bishop trade helps White. White wants to play in general against bad Bb7. } ) 
18. Rfe1!? { Setting up an X-ray against the queen. } fxe4 
19. Ng3 { Here, Black has only one move that keeps the game equal. } Rd7!! { Deep prophylactic move. Black simply moves away from Nxe4 tempo. } 
20. Rxe4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( 20.Nxe4? { is bad due to } 20...Qa8! $17 { and White's center collapses. } ) Qa8?! { A tactical idea one may be tempted to go for. } 
21. Rxe6 Bxd5 { As now White cannot take on d5. However, White has another option. } 
22. Re7! ( { This move gives White an advantage. } 22.cxd5? Rxd5 23.Qe2 Rxg5 $17 { 23.Qe3 Bd4-+ }) Rxe7 { Forced, as the bishop is also under attack. } 
23. Bxe7 Rf7 
24. cxd5 Rxe7 { Black would probably be fine if not for the detail that it's White to move! } 
25. d6! {[%csl Re7]} Rd7 {[%cal Gg3e4]} { Now, White needs to bring the knight to e4. } 
26. Re1! {[%cal Gg3e4][%csl Ge1]} { A very important move, improving our worst piece and enabling Ne4 to secure the d-pawn. } Bd4 
27. Ne4 $14  {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5][%csl Rg8,Ge4,Gd6]} { The game goes on and White has better chances: Black's king is chronically weak and h4-h5 could be a future idea. Our powerful tandem d6-pawn + e4-knight restrict the black pieces. } *

