[White "10) Grünfeld, 10...b6 11.Rc1 Bb7"]
[Black "13...Rxc6 14.d5 Rd6 #7"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21340610"]
[ECO "D86"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } b6 
11. Rc1 Bb7 
12. Bb5 Rc8 
13. Bxc6!? { At the moment of creating this course, to the best of my knowledge, this move has not been played yet in tournament games, but it occurred in quite a bit of correspondence games. I was intrigued by this idea and decided to investigate it further.

As a result of my analysis, I believe that this line can be tricky to face if one is unfamiliar with it and it can be an interesting surprise weapon, even though objectively Black is fine here (like everywhere else pretty much in 10... b6 line...). Still, it is worth a shot in my opinion. White's idea is to build a strong center and play against Black's light-squared bishop. In an ideal scenario, it would be good to trade dark-squared bishops too. } Rxc6 
14. d5 Rd6 
15. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Ge4]} { A very healthy and natural way of playing. White built a very strong center. } e6! { The only reasonable way to play this position. Otherwise, White stabilizes fully in the center. } 
16. Qd2 ( 16.Qa4 { is a possible alternative, but it seems less promising. } ) f5! 
17. Bg5 ( { The only way to pose problems to Black. } 17.f3 { does not lead anywhere: } 17...fxe4 18.fxe4 exd5 19.exd5 Rxf1+ 20.Rxf1 Rf6= ) Qe8! ( { This is the best retreat for Black that equalizes. However, in a practical game, it may not be easy to be found. } 17...Bf6 18.Bxf6 Qxf6 19.f3 $14 { The bishop trade helps White. White wants to play in general against bad Bb7. } ) 
18. Rfe1!? { Setting up an X-ray against the queen. } fxe4 
19. Ng3 { Here, Black has only one move that keeps the game equal. } Rd7!! { Deep prophylactic move. Black simply moves away from Nxe4 tempo. } 
20. Rxe4 ( 20.Nxe4? { is bad due to } 20...Qa8! $17 { and White's center collapses. } ) b5! { Final important move that guarantees the equality. If Black finds all these moves, then it is equal. I tried to find some ideas here but unfortunately Black is just fine. } 
21. Qe1!? {[%mdl 32768]} { This move could be some practical try, but Black is fine in many ways. Still, the position requires precise calculation and even though it is 0.00, for people it may not be obvious. } bxc4 
22. Rxe6 Qf7 ( { The most human move, even though Stockfish claims 0.00 after few other retreats, including } 22...Qa8!? 23.Ne4 Bxd5 24.Nf6+ Bxf6 25.Rxf6 Rxf6 26.Bxf6 Bxg2 27.Qe6+ Rf7= { Unfortunately, White does not have more than a draw here. } 28.Bc3 Bh1 29.f3 Qxf3 30.Qe8+ Rf8 31.Qe6+= ) 
23. Ne4!? { Trying to make somehow Nf6 work. Unfortunately, Black holds in various ways but it may be scary to be facing such an idea over the board. } Bxd5?! { This is an example of how things may slowly begin going out of control for Black. } 
24. Nf6+ Bxf6 
25. Rxf6 Re8! 
26. Qc3! Qg7 
27. h3 { Such position could be playable as the dark squares around Black's king are very weak. Of course, it is roughly equal objectively but there could be some practical difficulties for Black. } *

