3. Nc3 d5 { The Grünfeld is one of the most dynamic openings against } { 1. d4 that has caused many players playing with White dread facing it and look for either various move orders (for instance, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 , resulting in Anti-Grünfeld), switching between many lines in Grünfeld itself, or abandoning 1. d4 altogether if someone played Grunfeld. I can confirm it from personal experience, as I faced such a situation when playing both as White and as Black.

The Grünfeld can be a really annoying opening for White as Black in many lines can achieve a draw nearly by force or if White plays something imprecise to avoid such draws, he can take over the initiative. For this reason, the choice of a line was not easy here for me. Still, I decided to choose a line that I believe offers some practical chances, poses some practical problems for Black, and most importantly avoids direct draw and keeps the position alive and playable. Even if the objective advantage is not there at times, this can give White a practical edge during the game. } 
4. cxd5 Nxd5 
5. e4 Nxc3 
6. bxc3 Bg7 
7. Bc4 { Classical system Bc4-Ne2! In this variation White manages to control the center and not allow Black to easily undermine it with ...Bg4 ideas, as f3 always can be played there. } c5 { A usual reaction in Grunfeld. Sometimes, however, people try to either delay it or play without ...c5 altogether. } 
8. Ne2 Nc6 
9. Be3 O-O 
10. O-O { This is the main position of the entire Bc4-Ne2 variation in Grunfeld. Over the years Black tested many lines and thanks to the help of chess engines the theory grew here exponentially in the last 10-15 years. } b6 
11. h4!? { This is a relatively fresh approach to this particular line, but the idea, as seen already many times in other lines, it is a quite common push. } e6! ( { The best reaction to this line is to quickly bring the queen to h4. Black can include } 11...cxd4 12.cxd4 e6 { 12...e5? 13.Bg5! Another benefit of h4! 13...Qd6 14.dxe5 Qxe5 15.Rc1 $16 } 13.h5 Qh4 { and here White can transpose [/variation/21341373/#/14/w] with } 14.Qc1 ) 
12. h5 { White should be consequent. } Qh4 { This is an important position. } 
13. Qc1!? {[%cal Ge3g5,Gf1d1]} { This apparently mysterious move deserves serious attention. White frees the d-file for the rook and sets the immediate threat of Bg5. It was recently successfully tried by Praggnanandhaa versus Giri. } ( { Instead, } 13.hxg6 hxg6 14.f3 { was tried in some games but White did not get much there. } 14...cxd4 15.cxd4 Rd8 16.Qd2 Bb7 { This position is still playable of course, but objectively Black is fine. } ) cxd4 ( 13...Qxe4?? 14.Ng3! { and the queen is trapped! } 14...Qh4 15.Bg5 Qg4 16.Be2+- ) 
14. cxd4 { The first moment where Black is at crossroads. } Bb7! { Black should complete the development and ignore the e4-pawn. } 
15. h6 {[%mdl 32768]} Bf6! {[%cal Gg6g5][%csl Rh6]} ( { Black must go here to have an idea of ...g5 and win the h6-pawn. } 15...Bh8? 16.f3 $16 { and the h6-pawn is a big issue for Black. } ) 
16. f3 { Here, Black has some choice. } Rac8 { Probably the most natural move. } 
17. Qb2!? { Just like in the main line. [/variation/21341378/#/17/w] } g5 ( 17...Bg5?! 18.Qd2 $14 { and Black does not win the pawn. } ) 
18. Rac1 Qxh6 { Here, as Nc6 is well defended, but d4 is not attacked as much, White should not play Bb5, but go for direct kingside play. } 
19. f4! { Here, Black is under serious pressure. } Qh4! ( { The best move for Black but incredibly difficult one. } 19...g4? { is bad due to } 20.Qd2 $14 { with the threat of f5. As there is no Rfd8, Black cannot play ...Nxd4! } ) 
20. Rc3!? {[%cal Gf1c1,Rc3h3]} { A multipurpose move. Potentially, White may want to swing rook over to the kingside, but there is also an idea of Rfc1. } g4 { Closing the kingside seems reasonable, but now White switches to the queenside play. } 
21. Bf2 Qh5 
22. Rfc1= $13  { The position remains playable. I am not claiming White is better, but with good prep and Black being likely out of the book, this seems like a decent try. White controls the center, and Black's king is weak... Still, lots of play ahead, but I feel like White is not taking much risk here, and playing it with Black may be tricky. } *

