[White "12) The Nimzo Indian Defense: Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21469323"]
[ECO "E49"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . Other main replies by Black include } ) ( 4...c5 { , } ) ( 4...d5 { and } ) ( 4...b6 { . } ) ( { • } 4...c5 { In this move order White has two decent options again. } 5.Nge2!? { A classical Rubinstein approach - defending the c3-knight right away and preparing a3. } { 5.Bd3 can be played too, followed by Nge2, very likely transposing back to 4.e3 O-O 5.Bd3 c5 6.Ne2. [/variation/21469323/#/5/b/0.1] } 5...cxd4 6.exd4 { There are two options for Black. } 6...d5 7.c5! { This gives White good chances. } 7...e5! { If not this move, Black's position is clearly worse. } 8.a3 Bxc3+ 9.Nxc3 exd4 10.Qxd4 O-O 11.Bb5! { I think that Black here is under pressure. } ) ( { • } 4...c5 5.Nge2!? cxd4 6.exd4 d5 7.c5 Ne4 8.a3 Bxc3+ 9.Nxc3 Nxc3 10.bxc3 { followed by Bd3, Qh5 etc is great for White. } ) ( { • } 4...c5 5.Nge2!? cxd4 6.exd4 O-O 7.a3 Be7 8.d5! { seizing control over the center. } 8...exd5 9.cxd5 Re8 { 9...Bc5 10.b4 Bb6 11.Na4! winning a pair of bishops. After 11...Re8 12.Bb2 d6 13.Nxb6 axb6 14.f3! White goes for Kf2 and Ng3, completing his development and retaining an edge thanks to the center and the pair of bishops. } 10.d6 Bf8 11.g3! { thanks to the wedge pawn on d6 Black may have a hard time completing his development, even if the d6-pawn falls as Black would need to spend some time to win it. } ) ( { • } 4...d5 { Here, I would suggest two options. } 5.a3 Bxc3+ { 5...Be7 is pretty much the same as 4...O-O 5.Bd3 d5 6.a3. [/variation/21469323/#/6/w] } 6.bxc3 { This is an improved version of the 4.e3 O-O 5.Bd3 d5 6.a3 [/variation/21469323/#/6/w] line as White has not played yet Bd3, which allows ...dxc4 and the bishop moves twice. } 6...c6 { is a recent trend here and there were lots of developments. } 7.a4!? { delaying the development of the f1-bishop is the way to go. } 7...O-O 8.Ba3 Re8 9.Nf3 { as analysis shows, White should have some edge here. } ) ( { • } 4...d5 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 O-O { is the old line and here White is considered to be better after } 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Bd3 c5 9.Ne2 { following ideas of f3, Ng3 and eventually e4, as demonstrated as early as 1938 in the game Botvinnik-Capablanca. } ) ( { • } 4...d5 5.Bd2 { allows White to transpose to 4...O-O 5.Bd2 d5 6.Nf3. [/variation/21649358/#/6/w] } ) ( { • } 4...b6 5.Nge2 { The most principled line against the 4...b6 move order. White wants to immediately win the pair of bishops with a3 on the next move. Black has many ways to play here. } 5...Ba6 6.Ng3 { An alternative to 6.a3, which in this case does not really work that well. } 6...Bxc3+ { 6...O-O 7.e4! Nc6 8.Bg5 is really unpleasant for Black. } 7.bxc3 d5 { The best reaction. I would recommend here the following: } 8.cxd5 Bxf1 9.Rxf1 Qxd5 10.f3 { or @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/p1p2ppp/1p2pn2/3P4/3P4/2P1P1N1/P4PPP/R1BQKb1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Nxf1 Qxd5 10.f3 with a slight edge for White. } ) ( { • } 4...b6 5.Nge2 c5 6.a3 Ba5 7.Rb1 Na6 { 7...Qe7 8.d5! is quite an important detail } 8.g3! { Bringing the bishop to the long diagonal and supporting d5. } 8...Bb7 9.d5 b5 10.b3! { I find it the simplest and the strongest. } 10...exd5 11.Bg2 { recapturing the pawn soon with an edge. } ) ( { • } 4...b6 5.Nge2 Bb7 6.a3 Bxc3+ 7.Nxc3 d5 8.Bd3 O-O 9.O-O { White banks on the pair of bishops in these positions. } ) 
5. Bd3 d5 ( { This is the most popular variation. If Black does not do anything in the center, White wants Ne2, O-O etc. For this reason Black should react in the center with either } 5...d5 { or } ) ( 5...c5 { (I cover the alternatives as well, but they are not really critical and White should be better there). } { • 5.Bd2!? This is another approach that is a modern innovation in Rubinstein Variation. White wants to recapture with the bishop on c3 and avoid doubled pawns. 5...d5 6.Nf3 This is the main line, very popular these days, as it can arise from Nimzo and Ragozin. I think the positions there are playable and I tried them myself in some games. 6...b6 Black's main reply. The alternative is 6...c5, along with 6...Nbd7 or 6...Re8, which are also playable but less common. 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Bd3 is the main tabiya here. White has a couple of plans available, depending on what Black plays, but the main idea by far is to play Ne5 and f4 which comfortably controls and stabilizes the center and then launch an attack on the kingside by bringing in more pieces. Another idea is to play e4 at some point with central play, of course, if Black allows it. There is also an idea of Qb1, which acts against ...Ne4 ideas, but mainly enables White to play b4. 8...Bb7 is the main move, but I analyze bunch of alternatives too. 9.O-O Bd6 10.Qb1!? preventing ...Ne4, preparing b4, and potentially e4. 10...Re8 10...c5 11.dxc5 bxc5 12.e4!? is also very tricky for Black. 11.b4!? restricting ...c5. As analysis shows, White has good chances here. } { • 5.Bd2 c5 is a very decent alternative. 6.a3 Bxc3 7.Bxc3 Ne4 8.Ne2! the knight reinforces the c3-square - the essence of Rubinstein Variation! 8...b6 8...d6?! is inaccurate due to 9.dxc5! dxc5 10.Qc2! Nxc3 11.Nxc3 $14 with ideas of Bd3, O-O-O and a subsequent attack on the kingside, as in Bluebaum-Duda 2019 . 9.d5 followed by kicking away the knight from e4 (with f3 or Qc2) and then bringing own knight to c3 allows White to stabilize the center and hope to take advantage of some space advantage in the future. Black's position is fine here too, but he must show certain degree of knowledge and understanding - otherwise, things may get tricky for Black. } { • 5.Bd2 d5 6.Nf3 c5 is met by 7.a3 Bxc3 8.Bxc3 Ne4 9.Rc1 Nxc3 10.Rxc3 cxd4 11.Nxd4 where despite soon-to-be symmetric pawn structure (after ...dxc4), White retains better chances due to more active pieces. 11...e5!? is perhaps critical for the entire line, but it is not by any means easy: 11...dxc4 12.Bxc4 Bd7 13.O-O Nc6 14.Nf3! keeping the pieces on the board is essential. Next, ideas of Qc2, Rc1, maybe Bd3 or Ba2-Bb1 give White better chances. 12.Nf3 d4 13.exd4 e4 14.Ng1 Nc6 15.Ne2 White has an extra pawn and only with perfect play does Black manage to keep it balanced, but as my analysis shows, not only Black needs to come up with a bunch of difficult moves, a novelty, and even then, I must admit that I prefer White from a human point of view (despite engine somehow holding it...). } ) ( { On } 5...c5 { my suggestion would be } 6.Nge2 { which generally leads to interesting positions with an isolated d4-pawn. } 6...d5 7.cxd5 cxd4 8.exd4 Nxd5 9.O-O Nc6 { and here White has many options. I focus my attention on } 10.a3 Bd6 11.Re1!? { which is a recent, quite promising trend. } ) 
6. a3 { I would recommend this line. White attempts to get a pair of bishops right away, hoping that it will prove beneficial in the long term. } ( { The mainstream theory follows after } 6.Nf3 dxc4 7.Bxc4 c5 8.O-O { and here Black has a vast number of options. In my book I suggest } 8...Nc6 9.a3 Ba5!? { which is an interesting approach avoiding lots of theory, but @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/4pn2/2p5/1bBP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 8...cxd4 9.exd4 b6 is very topical and well-studied, which I believe gives Black equality. } ) Bxc3+ ( 6...Be7 { Not giving away the pair of bishops means that Black loses a tempo which sounds great for White of course, but it is not necessarily clear. My analysis shows that Black is still very solid but White can pose some practical problems. } ) 
7. bxc3 dxc4 
8. Bxc4 c5 
9. Nf3 ( { I think this is the most promising. } 9.Ne2 { is another option and even though it is also playable, I find it less attractive than 9. Nf3. } ) Qc7 
10. Be2 b6 
11. Bb2! { An important move order - White in a way 'prevents' ... Ba6 lines (well, not in 100%, but they seem to work less well than after 9. O-O). } Bb7 ( 11...Ba6 12.c4! { is the point, as the analysis indicates. } ) 
12. O-O { Here, Black has plans related to ...Nbd7 and ...Nc6. White generally goes sooner or later for c4, but there are also some ideas that delay it, potentially preparing e4. I think that this position has some potential and may offer White good practical chances where understanding and knowledge are more important than studying and memorizing exact lines - which makes this line perfectly playable. } *

