Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } b6 
5. Nge2 { The most principled line against the 4... b6 move order. White wants to immediately win the pair of bishops with a3 on the next move. Black has many ways to play here. } c5 { This line is generally considered to be somewhat dubious for Black. } 
6. a3 Ba5 
7. Rb1 Na6 
8. g3! {[%cal Gf1g2]} { White develops the bishop to g2 to support the center when he plays d5. } Bb7 
9. d5 {[%mdl 32768]} b5 ( { Fighting for the center. } 9...exd5? 10.Bg2 $16 { followed by cxd5 gives White big advantage. Black is unable here to fight for the center and remains with bad pieces. } ) ( 9...Ne4? { was tried by Aronian. It was an unsuccessful innovation: } 10.Bg2 Bxc3+ 11.Nxc3 Nxc3 12.bxc3 d6 14.Qa4+ Ke7 14.O-O Nc7 15.e4 $16 { Gelfand-Aronian (2010). } ) 
10. b3!? { A rare move in this particular position, but I think it puts Black under pressure. The point is that Black is unable to damage White's center. Even when Black plays ...exd5, White has a key idea of Bg2, which pins on the long diagonal. Only then can White recapture. } ( 10.Bg2 { This is the most popular move here, but I think it is not that clear. } 10...bxc4! 11.O-O O-O 12.e4 exd5 13.e5 { 13.exd5 d6 is not so clear. } 13...Ng4 14.Bxd5 Bc6! { with the idea of ...Nc7 on top of targeting the e5-pawn. } 15.Bf4 Re8 16.Bxc6 dxc6 17.Qa4 Nxe5 $13 { . } ) b4?! 
11. axb4 Nxb4 
12. Bg2 {[%cal Ge1g1]} exd5 
13. O-O! {[%cal Gg2b7]} { And White recaptures the pawn soon, establishing a strong center. } Rb8 
14. Nxd5! Nbxd5 ( 14...Nfxd5? 15.cxd5 O-O 16.Bb2+- { the b4-knight is pretty much useless. } ) 
15. cxd5 $16  {[%cal Gc1b2,Ge2f4]} { By maintaining the pawn on d5, White enjoys more space and central control. Black is strategically worse. Next, we'll improve our minor pieces with Bb2 and Nf4. } *

