3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } b6 
5. Nge2 Ba6 
6. Ng3!? ( { A very interesting approach that is far less common than normal } 6.a3 { , which I must admit, I took dogmatically for granted and thought White must play it. However, I ran into some issues there with finding an advantage due to innovative engine solutions that made me question if } ) ( 6.a3 { is even the right move. A simple technique of 'looking for candidates' helped me find } ) ( 6.Ng3 { I think it is an excellent practical try for White for two reasons. First, it is simply objectively good, and it leads to unbalanced positions that are definitely playable. And second - I am pretty sure it should be a surprise for anyone playing the 5...Ba6 line, as normally 6. a3 is nearly automatic (that's why we played Ne2 in the first place!). White prepares e4 and does not mind ...Bxc3, hoping to achieve a position similar to Saemisch Variation (4. a3) but without wasting time for a3. } ) ( 6.a3 { is another move; my issue with it is what happens after } 6...Bxc3+ 7.Nxc3 d5 { Here, there are many options for White, with the main attempt being } 8.b3 { . I focused mostly on this, but I looked at others and did not find anything special anywhere. } 8...O-O 9.Be2 c5! 10.dxc5 dxc4! { A rare line that I believe equalizes. I spent here quite a bit of time, but I did not manage to find anything I liked. } ) h5 { This move was played in two games between Stockfish and Komodo in 2020. Both games ended with draws, but it does not mean that things are easy here for Black. } 
7. h4 { I believe that inclusion of ...h5 and h4 helps White. Black cannot play ...O-O now, while e4 is still an issue for Black. } c5 
8. d5 { Of course, White should close the center and gain space. is analyzed after 6...h5. } Bxc3+ 
9. bxc3 {[%mdl 32768]} Qe7 
10. Rh3!? {[%cal Ge3e4,Rh3e3]} { Preparing e4 and central play, as e4-pawn will not be hanging due to Re3 in the end. } g6 
11. e4! Ng4 ( 11...exd5 12.cxd5 Nxe4 { fails to } 13.Nxe4 Qxe4+ 14.Re3+- { which was the point behind Rh3! } ) 
12. Be2!? ( 12.f3 { was played by Stockfish, and it is also very good. However, engines also like } ) ( 12.Be2 { , which I believe is more direct. } ) d6 ( 12...Ne5? 13.f4+- ) ( 12...exd5 13.cxd5 Bxe2 14.Qxe2 $16 ) 
13. Bxg4 hxg4 
14. Qxg4 Bxc4 
15. Bg5! { Forcing further weakening of Black's position. } f6 
16. Bf4 Rg8 ( 16...Kf7 17.h5 g5 18.e5! $16 ) 
17. Nf1 $16  {[%cal Gf1e3]} { Regrouping the knight to e3 to kick the black bishop. This is strategically very unpleasant for Black. After Ne3, we may be ready to push h5. Of course, the position stays complicated, but our central control secures us a more comfortable game. }-- ( { In case of } 17...e5 { I like } 18.Bd2 { , but } { 18.Bc1 could be an option too. We want the e3-square for our knight. } )
