2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } b6 
5. Nge2 Ba6 
6. Ng3!? ( { A very interesting approach that is far less common than normal } 6.a3 { , which I must admit, I took dogmatically for granted and thought White must play it. However, I ran into some issues there with finding an advantage due to innovative engine solutions that made me question if } ) ( 6.a3 { is even the right move. A simple technique of 'looking for candidates' helped me find } ) ( 6.Ng3 { I think it is an excellent practical try for White for two reasons. First, it is simply objectively good, and it leads to unbalanced positions that are definitely playable. And second - I am pretty sure it should be a surprise for anyone playing the 5...Ba6 line, as normally 6. a3 is nearly automatic (that's why we played Ne2 in the first place!). White prepares e4 and does not mind ...Bxc3, hoping to achieve a position similar to Saemisch Variation (4. a3) but without wasting time for a3. } ) ( 6.a3 { is another move; my issue with it is what happens after } 6...Bxc3+ 7.Nxc3 d5 { Here, there are many options for White, with the main attempt being } 8.b3 { . I focused mostly on this, but I looked at others and did not find anything special anywhere. } 8...O-O 9.Be2 c5! 10.dxc5 dxc4! { A rare line that I believe equalizes. I spent here quite a bit of time, but I did not manage to find anything I liked. } ) Bxc3+ ( { An important detail is that } 6...d5?? { loses a piece to } 7.Qa4++- ) 
7. bxc3 d5 ( { Perhaps this is what Black should do - otherwise, White will play e4. Of course, it can be considered as a success if Black played ...Bxc3 without a3, and then also help White get rid of the doubled pawns. But still, things are far from easy. } 7...Bb7 8.Qc2 $16 { and e4 comes anyway. } ) 
8. Qf3 { Initially, I thought that the text move was the best move here, pinning the d5-pawn and potentially creating an e4 idea. However, during my preparation for the game against Elshan Moradiabadi during the 2022 US Championships, I discovered a big hole in my initial analysis and decided to play something else. Still, I would like to share the discovery that made me reject 8. Qf3. } O-O 
9. cxd5 { Here I initially assumed that Black needs to recapture on d5 with the queen, but then White is indeed slightly better in a number of ways. However, there is a big problem. } Bxf1!! { This move was played only once, in the correspondence game Scheffknecht-Loschnauer (2020). I looked at it too, and it seemed like I had it all worked out to White's advantage, but the reality is different. } ( { After } 9...Qxd5 { the simplest is } 10.Bxa6 Qxf3 11.gxf3 Nxa6 12.Ke2 $14 { . } ) 
10. dxe6 Bc4! 
11. Qxa8 Nd5! { The best way to play as Black. Now White's queen may potentially be trapped, so lack of material does not really matter that much from Black's perspective. } 
12. e4 ( { I thought that this was my refutation, 'forcing' the knight to move. } 12.Qxa7 { was played in the aforementioned correspondence game, but after } 12...Na6! 13.Ba3 Re8 { things are far from clear too. } 14.Ne4 Rxe6 15.Nd2 Bd3 16.Nf3 Qc8! 17.Rc1 Bc4 18.Nd2 Bd3 19.Nf3 Bc4 20.Nd2 Bd3 21.Nf3 Bc4 22.Nd2 { ½-½ (22) Scheffknecht, P (2119)-Loschnauer, R (2448) ICCF 2020. } ) a6 $13  {[%csl Ra8]} { However, after this brilliant move, White's queen may never get back into the game, and the position is great for Black. After a long think, engine gives 0.00, which in such a sharp position with such a terrible queen on a8 can only mean trouble from a practical point of view. This discovery in my game preparation made me reject 8. Qf3 and choose another path. } ( { Initially, I considered only } 12...Nxc3? { which, after } 13.Be3+- { , gives White a winning position. } ) 
