[White "16) Nimzo Indian: 4...b6 5.Ne2 Bb7 & 5...O-O"]
[Black "5...O-O 6-a3 Bxc3+ #1"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21453685"]
[ECO "E43"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } b6 
5. Nge2 O-O { Here I consider what happens if Black plays without ...Bb7. } 
6. a3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bxc3+ 
7. Nxc3 d5 { The difference between this position and the one with ...Bb7 played instead of ... O-O is that now Black has an option of ...Ba6. } 
8. cxd5!? { Here, Bd3 is less good perhaps. However, there is also an idea of capturing on d5 right away. } Nxd5 
9. Be2!? {[%csl Ge2]} { I discovered this is a better square than d3 for the bishop. In some lines, when Black plays ...c5, the bishop may be a little bit unstable on d3. } Nxc3 ( 9...Ba6 10.Bd2 $14 ) 
10. bxc3 Bb7 
11. O-O c5 
12. a4 $14  {[%csl Gc1,Ge2]} { And the position transposes to what I analyzed after 5... Bb7. I believe that many people will find such a position good for White. In fact - I think it is a better version of what I recommend in 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. a3 variation. } *

