7. Nxc3 d5 { White can play here with and without cxd5. } 
8. Bd3 ( { Here, Black has two main options: ...O-O or take on c4. } 8.cxd5!? { is also possible, transposing very likely to what I analyze after 5... O-O. } 8...Nxd5 9.Bb5+ c6 { 9...Bc6 10.Bxc6+ Nxc6 11.Ne2!? $14 } 10.Be2 Nxc3 11.bxc3 O-O 12.O-O c5 13.a4 $14 ) O-O 
9. O-O c5 ( { Apart from } 9...dxc4 { (which just transposes to 8... dxc4), this is the best alternative. } ) 
10. dxc5 bxc5 ( 10...dxc4 11.Bxc4 { is covered after 8... dxc4. } ) 
11. cxd5 exd5 ( 11...Nxd5 12.Bd2 $16 ) 
12. b4! { Fighting for the dark squares. } d4 { The only logical continuation. Otherwise, White will obtain full control over the dark squares. } 
13. exd4 Qxd4 
14. Ra2!! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%csl Rc3]} { An important move to play. The Nc3 is untouchable and Rd2 comes! } Nc6 
15. Rd2 Qh4 { Here, the position may get slightly sharper but tactically White is doing well. } 
16. bxc5 Ne5 
17. Be2 Qg5□ 
18. Rd5! Qg6 
19. Bd3! Qg4□ 
20. Qxg4 Nfxg4 { Here, the best chance for White is to sac an exchange. } 
21. Bf5! Bxd5 
22. Nxd5 $14  { And thanks to the pair of bishops (again!) and the strong c5-pawn Black is under pressure. } *

