8. cxd5 {[%mdl 32768]} exd5 ( 8...Nxd5?! { is down a tempo compared to the regular Semi-Tarrasch, a sound opening we'll cover in Part } { 2. Nearly anything is good for White thanks to the extra tempo (the black bishop has moved back and forth): for example, we can immediately castle because our bishop is already out. Black will probably exchange ond4 at some point, and we are fully ready to mobilize our pieces. } ) 
9. dxc5 Bxc5 
10. b4 { This is a dream version of playing against the isolated pawn. The bishop moved so many times already and is still chased around, while at the same time White completes his strategic goal of installing a blockade on d4 and preventing Black from getting an active play. } Be7 ( 10...Bd6 11.Nb5! Be7 12.O-O $14 ) ( 10...Bb6 11.Na4! { A strong tempo-move, seizing control over the d4-square. } 11...Bc7 12.Bb2 Nc6 13.h3 $16 ) 
11. Bb2 a5 
12. b5 Nbd7 
13. O-O Nc5 
14. Rc1 $14  {[%csl Rd5,Gd4]} { Generally, White will always be better in these positions due to the isolated d5-pawn and the strong d4-square that comes with it. A move like ...Nxd3 shouldn't worry us, because it helps us develop and build up some pressure on the IQP. } *

