[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21457228"]
[ECO "E40"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } d5 
5. a3 Bxc3+ 
6. bxc3 O-O 
7. cxd5 {[%mdl 32768]} exd5 
8. Bd3 c5 
9. Ne2 { The main position. Black has some plans available here. The most popular option is ... b6 and ...Ba6. There are ideas of ...Bg4 and ...Bh5. Another way of playing is ...Nc6, ...Na5, ...Bd7, ...Rc8 in a style of Ragozin. It is important to note that generally playing ...c4 is not advised.

There are lines when ...c4 is playable in similar positions though, but the main difference is that then it is played to prevent Bd3 from White. Here, however, the bishop is already developed. } Bg4 {[%cal Gg4h5,Gh5g6][%csl Rd3]} { Black wants to solve the problem of the light-squared bishop by trading it on g6. } 
10. f3 Bh5 
11. Nf4 Bg6 { Now it is an important moment. } 
12. Be2! {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4][%csl Rg6]} { White should not rush with trading. Having played Nf4, Nxg6 is always available. Instead, White should go for g4, h4 and try to either trap the bishop and/or gain space on the kingside. } Nc6 
13. Ra2!? {[%csl Rc2]} { I think I like this move the most. The idea is to control in any case the c2-square and potentially swing the rook to the center or the kingside through the 2nd rank. Ideas of h4 and g4 can be played later. } Rc8 
14. O-O Re8 
15. g4!? cxd4 ( 15...h6?! 16.Nxg6 fxg6 17.Bd3 $16 { . } ) 
16. cxd4 Na5 {[%csl Rc2]} { We can see how useful Ra2 was - no issues with ...Bc2 or something like that. } 
17. h4! -- ( { White can just continue with their plan, for example, } 17...Qc7 { and now either } 18.Rb2 $14 { or } { 18.Qa4 $14 , or 18.Bb5!? Red8 19.Ba4 $14 . } )
*

