1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } d5 
5. a3 Bxc3+ 
6. bxc3 O-O 
7. cxd5 exd5 
8. Bd3 c5 
9. Ne2 { The main position. Black has some plans available here. The most popular option is ... b6 and ...Ba6. There are ideas of ...Bg4 and ...Bh5. Another way of playing is ...Nc6, ...Na5, ...Bd7, ...Rc8 in a style of Ragozin. It is important to note that generally playing ...c4 is not advised.

There are lines when ...c4 is playable in similar positions though, but the main difference is that then it is played to prevent Bd3 from White. Here, however, the bishop is already developed. } Nc6 
10. f3 Re8 { Could also have been played in 9...Re8 move order. } 
11. O-O Bd7!? { Going for some sort of Ragozin-style setup. } 
12. Nf4!? {[%mdl 32768]} Na5 
13. Ra2 { Bringing the rook to the center or kingside through the second rank. } Rc8 
14. g4 $14  {[%cal Ga2g2,Gg4g5]} { Definitely, White has better chances. } *

