[White "18) Nimzo Indian: 4...d5, 5...Bxc3, 6...O-O & 6...c5"]
[Black "Alternative to 11.f3 #1"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21457231"]
[ECO "E40"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } d5 
5. a3 Bxc3+ 
6. bxc3 O-O 
7. cxd5 exd5 
8. Bd3 c5 
9. Ne2 { The main position. Black has some plans available here. The most popular option is ... b6 and ...Ba6. There are ideas of ...Bg4 and ...Bh5. Another way of playing is ...Nc6, ...Na5, ...Bd7, ...Rc8 in a style of Ragozin. It is important to note that generally playing ...c4 is not advised.

There are lines when ...c4 is playable in similar positions though, but the main difference is that then it is played to prevent Bd3 from White. Here, however, the bishop is already developed. } b6 { Generally, it is considered the best approach by Black. It is in Black's interest to get light-squared bishops off the board as often this bishop may have a hard time finding optimal squares. } ( 9...c4? 10.Bc2 $16 { is great news for White. Now White can run f3-e4 idea pretty much unopposed. } ) 
10. O-O Ba6 { Here, there are two possible plans for White. } 
11. Bxa6!? {[%mdl 32768]} Nxa6 
12. Qd3 {[%cal Ga6c7,Gc7e6][%csl Ra6]} { It makes sense to misplace the knight. On the other hand though, the knight may find his path to e6. } Nc7 ( { The most logical move in my opinion. } 12...c4? 13.Qc2 { followed by f3, Ng3 and e4 is again great for White. } ) ( 12...Qc8 13.f3 Re8 14.Ng3 Qb7 15.Ra2!? $14 ) ( 12...Nb8?! 13.dxc5! bxc5 14.c4 $14 { is a better version of the main line. } ) 
13. dxc5!? ( { Even though there were some games like this, it is a rare approach in this line. } 13.f3 Re8 14.Ng3 Ne6 { is less clear. } ) bxc5 
14. c4! {[%cal Gc1b2]} { White opens the position and goes here for a slight edge thanks to the better pawn structure and bishop vs knight which in open positions generally favors the side with the bishop. } dxc4 
15. Qxc4 Qd5 
16. Qc2!? {[%cal Ge2f4,Gc1b2]} -- ( { I would keep queens on the board. The game might continue } 16...Rfd8 17.Nf4 Qc6 18.Bb2 $14 { and no doubt that Black is under pressure. } { However, I must acknowledge that the endgame is also better for White. Therefore, 16.Qxd5 is a valid alternative and after 16...Nfxd5 17.e4 Nb6 18.Be3 $14 White retains some edge. } )
*

