[White "19) Nimzo Indian: 4...d5, 5...Bxc3 with 6...c6"]
[Black "6...c6 7.a4 O-O #1"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21458383"]
[ECO "E40"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } d5 
5. a3 Bxc3+ 
6. bxc3 c6 { This is a recent trend in such and similar positions. The idea is to have an option of recapturing ...cxd5, not allowing Bd3-Ne2 setups when Black recaptures with the e-pawn. Next, Black generally wants ...b6 and ...Ba6, seeking positional play on the light squares. } 
7. a4! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc1a3]} { I think White should immediately improve the c1-bishop. } O-O 
8. Ba3 Re8 
9. Nf3 { This is the main position. Right now Black has two possible plans: ...b6 and ...Ba6 (which is the main approach) or the more modern ...Qc7, which can be considered a specialty of Parham Maghsoodloo. } b6 ( { The most popular move, but inferior to the fresh } 9...Qc7 { . } ) 
10. cxd5! { Defining the pawn structure before Black plays ...Ba6. } exd5 { This is an alternative to ...cxd5, but it seems a bit strange. Black played ... c6 to recapture with the c-pawn, after all. } 
11. Bd3 Ba6 
12. O-O Ne4 ( { Exchanging the light-squared bishops doesn't help Black; after } 12...Bxd3 13.Qxd3 { and our idea is to play c4 next; because Black played ...b6, the c6-pawn is always weak. } 13...Nbd7 14.c4 Ne4 15.cxd5 cxd5 16.Rfc1 $16 { White is better. } ) 
13. Rc1! {[%cal Gc3c4][%csl Rb8]} ( { I would recommend this move. White prepares c4 and does not help to develop Nb8. } 13.Bxa6 Nxa6 14.Qd3 { was tried in Yu-Mastrovasilis (2021) but I don't think White should help bring the knight to e6. } 14...Nc7 15.c4 Ne6! { A novelty, and even though White is a bit better. Black solved the problem of the Nb8 and brought it to e6. } { 15...f6?! 16.Rfc1 $14 Yu-Mastrovalis (2021) }) Bxd3 
14. Qxd3 Nd7 
15. c4 { Again, the c6-pawn is a target. } dxc4 
16. Qxc4 Rc8 
17. Rc2 $14  {[%cal Gf1c1][%csl Ga3]} { Even if Black breaks in the center with ...c5, we'll have better play, because the position will open to our advantage thanks to our bishop. } *

