13. O-O ( { White wants to play c4. } 13.c4 { could be played immediately too, but I wanted to prepare it, as I analyze in the main line. } ) e5 ( { Black should go for this. It creates an IQP on d5, but alternatives are much worse. } 13...Qc7?! 14.c4! $16 ) 
14. dxe5 Nxe5 
15. Nxe5 Rxe5 
16. Bb2 $14  ( { According to the statistics in correspondence games, Black seems fine, but objectively on a human level I believe White is slightly better. The bishop pair and the potential for the opening of the position should give White some edge. } 16.c4!? { could be played too. } ) Bg4 ( { Trying active play. } 16...Re8 { looks passive. White can freely open the center and enjoy the bishop pair. } 17.c4! dxc4 18.Bxc4 Rc8 19.Be2 $14 ) ( 16...Bf5 17.Be2! { Of course - White should not trade the light-squared bishop. } ) 
17. Qe1!? {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc3c4][%csl Ge3]} { This is an interesting alternative. The queen supports the e3 pawn in case f3 or f4 (see the main line) is played. Next, of course c4 is on the agenda. } Qe7 ( 17...Bf5 18.Be2 $14 { again not trading! } ) 
18. c4 Rh5 
19. f4!? { An interesting idea. It seems like it weakens the e4-square and creates a backward e3-pawn but in fact, it does not matter. White will play Bd4 to defend the pawn if needed, while the e4-square seems not stable as the d5-pawn is already undermined. } ( 19.f3 Bf5 { is probably fine for Black as Be2 drops the e3-pawn and as a result, the bishops will be traded. } ) Re8 
20. cxd5 ( { An alternative is } 20.Bd4!? ) Rxd5 
21. Bc4 Rdd8 
22. Bd4 { Black seems solid but the pair of bishops still should give White some edge. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "19) Nimzo Indian: 4...d5, 5...Bxc3 with 6...c6"]
[Black "6...c6 7.a4 O-O #5"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21458387"]
[ECO "E40"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } d5 
5. a3 Bxc3+ 
6. bxc3 c6 { This is a recent trend in such and similar positions. The idea is to have an option of recapturing ...cxd5, not allowing Bd3-Ne2 setups when Black recaptures with the e-pawn. Next, Black generally wants ...b6 and ...Ba6, seeking positional play on the light squares. } 
7. a4! { I think White should immediately improve the c1-bishop. } O-O 
8. Ba3 Re8 
9. Nf3 { This is the main position. Right now Black has two possible plans: ...b6 and ...Ba6 (which is the main approach) or the more modern ...Qc7, which can be considered a specialty of Parham Maghsoodloo. } Qc7! { This is what Parham Maghsoodloo succesfully tried in his games. } 
10. Rc1 { This is another option. At first I thought it could be really good as it is the first choice of the engine, but thorough analysis proved otherwise... } Nbd7 
11. Be2 a6! { A strong move played twice by Maghsoodloo. The idea is to play ...dxc4 and ...b5. } 
12. c5 ( { The engine claims that this is the only way to White's 'advantage' but I am not sure about it at all. } 12.cxd5?! exd5 { with next ...b5 is good for Black. Liem Le Quang continued with } 13.c4 Qa5+ 14.Kf1 b5! $17 { and Black pretty much takes over. Le Quang-Maghsoodloo (2021). } ) ( 12.Qb3 dxc4 13.Qxc4 b5 { with next ...c5 is also double-edged, like in Bluebaum-Maghsoodloo (2021). } ) e5 $132  { Black gets here lots of counterplay on the kingside. If anyone is interested to analyze it deeper, go ahead. However, my analysis with strong engines showed that it is very difficult to play it as White, while Black has very simple plans: ...e4 and then either ...Nf8-...Ng6-...Nh4, or ...h5-...Ng4, or maybe some combination of the two. I really wanted to suggest this but my conclusion was that White takes here too much risk and it is simply not a practical choice, regardless of the engine's excitement... } 
*

