1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } c5 
5. Nge2 d6 
6. dxc5!? { I would recommend this rare move. The idea is to enter an endgame which I believe is favorable for White as Bb4 will be misplaced and if Black ever plays ...Bxc3 then White will have a pair of bishops advantage. } dxc5 
7. Qxd8+ {[%mdl 32768]} Kxd8 { Here, White has some choice. } 
8. b3!? { I like this approach. There was only one correspondence game here which makes this position nearly completely unexplored. White wants Bb2, O-O-O, f3. The plan is to slowly expand on the kingside and create some weaknesses for Black there. } ( 8.Bd2 { has been played mostly so far, and it's a decent move too. } ) Nc6 
9. Bb2 Ke7 
10. O-O-O b6 ( 10...Ng4? 11.Ne4+- ) ( 10...Ba5 { Black may try to bring the bishop back. Here, White has an interesting idea. } 11.h3 h5 12.Rg1 $14 ) 
11. f3 Bb7 
12. Nf4 Rhd8 
13. Nd3 Bxc3 ( 13...Ba5 14.Be2 $14 { ...Ba5 is bad! } ) 
14. Bxc3 $14  { Sooner or later Black should concede the pair of bishops but such an endgame is more pleasant for White. } *

