Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } c5 
5. Nge2 d5 ( 5...b6 { transposes to 4... b6, but line with c5 which is generally regarded as not that good for Black. } ) ( 5...Nc6 6.a3 Bxc3+ 7.Nxc3 cxd4 8.exd4 d5 9.c5 { should transpose, sooner or later, to the mainline. } ) ( 5...O-O 6.a3 Bxc3+ 7.Nxc3 cxd4 8.exd4 d5 9.c5 { transposes back to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1ppp/4pn2/2p5/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP2NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@ 5...cxd4 6.exd4 O-O 7.a3 Bxc3 8.Nxc3 d5 9.c5 . } ) 
6. a3 Bxc3+ 
7. Nxc3 cxd4 
8. exd4 dxc4 
9. Bxc4 Nc6 
10. Be3 O-O 
11. O-O { All these moves were logical and there were hardly any decent alternatives for both sides. Here, Black has some choice though. This position, however, may arise from a different move order as well - @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1ppp/4pn2/2p5/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP2NPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@ 5...cxd4 6.exd4 d5 7.a3 Bxc3 8.Nxc3 etc. } b6 
12. Qf3 ( { White should bring pieces to the game first, before any action in the center. } 12.d5?! { is premature, } 12...exd5 13.Nxd5 Be6= ) Bb7 
13. Bd3! {[%cal Gf3h3,Ga1d1,Ge3g5]} { White's plan is Qh3, Bg5, Rad1. I think that this position is promising for White. Here Black has many options. } Qd7 {[%cal Re3g5][%csl Gb7]} { This is the most popular move. The queen supports Bb7 and gets away from potential Bg5 pin. } 
14. Qh3 Ne7 
15. Bg5 Ng6 
16. Bxf6 gxf6 
17. Rad1 {[%cal Gd4d5,Rh3d7,Gd3e4]} { Pushing d5 is already a threat thanks to the pressure on the h3-d7 diagonal. White's main idea is Be4 to trade bishops and bring the knight over to the kingside. } Rad8 
18. Be4 {[%cal Ge4b7,Gb7e4,Gc3e4]} { There are other options too but I think that this is the most challenging. White wants to trade bishops to bring the knight to the kingside. } Bxe4 ( 18...f5 19.Bxb7 Qxb7 20.d5 $14 ) 
19. Nxe4 { The knight enters the game. } Qe7 
20. Qh6 f5 
21. Ng3 {[%mdl 32768]} Kh8 
22. Nh5!? Rg8 
23. Rd3! {[%cal Gd3h3,Gf1d1]} { Bringing the rook to the kingside, but also keeping an idea of Rfd1. } Rd6 ( 23...Qf8 24.Qe3 Qd6 25.Rfd1 $14 ) 
24. Rh3 Nf8 
25. Nf6 Rg7 
26. Rg3! Ng6 
27. Qg5↑ {[%cal Gf1c1,Gh2h4]} { Black is under pressure. Ideas of Rc1 and h4 are the main threats. } *

