1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} Re8!? ( { This is the most popular variation. If Black does not do anything in the center, White wants Ne2, O-O etc. For this reason Black should react in the center with either } 5...d5 { or } ) ( 5...c5 { (I cover the alternatives as well, but they are not really critical and White should be better there). } { 5.Bd2!? is another approach that is a modern innovation in Rubinstein Variation. White wants to recapture with the bishop on c3 and avoid doubled pawns. } ) { This is a flexible and tricky move whose point is that Black keeps an option of choosing his setup depending on what White plays. } 
6. Nge2 ( { I would play this. } 6.Nf3 Bxc3+ 7.bxc3 d6 { would transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@ 5.Nf3 Bxc3!? 6.bxc3 d6 7.Bd3 Re8 , which I recommend for Black in my book on the Nimzo-Indian. The line goes like this: 8.O-O e5 9.e4 exd4 10.cxd4 Nxe4 $13 Black wins a pawn and White definitely has some compensation, but my analysis shows that it yields no more than equality. } ) d5 { The point of ...Re8 is that someone who plays mostly Nf3 systems might be out of their comfort zone. Luckily, White has some chances here. } 
7. O-O b6?! { This is not working here. } 
8. e4! dxe4 
9. Nxe4 Nbd7 
10. c5!? {[%csl Rb4]} { The bishop is misplaced on b4. } bxc5 
11. a3 $14  {[%csl Rc5]} { And when the bishop retreats, we will recapture on c5 with a better structure. } *

