1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd3 b6 ( { This is the most popular variation. If Black does not do anything in the center, White wants Ne2, O-O etc. For this reason Black should react in the center with either } 5...d5 { or } ) ( 5...c5 { (I cover the alternatives as well, but they are not really critical and White should be better there). } { 5.Bd2!? is another approach that is a modern innovation in Rubinstein Variation. White wants to recapture with the bishop on c3 and avoid doubled pawns. } ) { The most popular alternative. } ( 5...d6 6.Nge2 e5 7.O-O { is analyzed via @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.e3 d6 . } ) ( 5...Bxc3+?! { is generally premature, as I discussed after 4...Bxc3. White again goes for Ne2 and O-O, followed by e4, Ng3, f4 etc. } 6.bxc3 d6 7.e4 e5 8.Ne2 Nc6 9.O-O $16 { . } ) ( 5...Nc6 { also looks wrong. White gets to comfortably create a setup with Ne2 and O-O and Black can no longer play ...c5. } 6.Nge2 d6 7.O-O e5 8.Nd5 $16 { is great for White, and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppp1ppp/2n1pn2/8/1bPP4/2NBP3/PP2NPPP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6...d5 7.cxd5 exd5 8.a3 $14 is also pleasant. } ) 
6. e4!? { Trying to take advantage of the somewhat weird move order chosen by Black. } d5! ( { The best reply. } 6...d6 7.Nge2 e5 8.d5 $14 { does not require much analysis - it is clear that in such a position, thanks to the space advantage, White should have better chances. } ) 
7. cxd5 { Right now, Black has only one, but very difficult, move to keep the game relatively balanced. } c5!! { A surprising move, in 'Grünfeld' style! However, it makes perfect sense to attack the center in this fashion. Right now, we have many tempting ideas at our disposal. } 
8. a3 { This is the most principled. } cxd4 
9. axb4 dxc3 
10. dxe6 ( { Winning a pawn. Instead, } 10.bxc3 exd5 11.e5 Qc7! { is less clear. } ) Bxe6 
11. bxc3 { White is slightly behind in the development, but an extra pawn is an extra pawn. For now, there are no serious threats, and White should be able to complete his development and retain the advantage. } Nc6?! { The most logical, but not so good. } 
12. Nf3 Qc7 ( { The best defense. } 12...Qd7 13.Be3 Rfd8 14.Nd4 $16 { is good for White. } ) ( { Also } 12...Bg4 13.O-O Bxf3 14.gxf3+- { or @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p4ppp/1pn2n2/8/1P2P1b1/2PB1N2/5PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@ 13...Ne5 14.Be2 $16 are excellent, thanks to the bishop pair. } ) 
13. O-O Bg4 
14. h3 Bh5 { This is relatively better. } 
15. Bb5!? {[%mdl 32768]} Ne5 
16. Bf4! { A very strong move. We'll soon see the point. } Bxf3 { White can play } 
17. Qd4! {[%cal Gf4c7][%csl Re5]} { Here it is! White gets a large advantage: } Rfe8 
18. Bxe8 Rxe8 
19. Rfe1 Nfd7 
20. Bh2 $16  {[%cal Rf3h5,Gf2f4]} -- ( { Preventing } 20...Bh5 { , as there would follow } 21.f4 { , pretty much trapping the bishop. For example, } 21...Nc6 22.Qd5 Nf6 23.Qc4 Qd7 24.e5+- { Black is tied up, and his pieces are very shaky. The current material balance favors White. } { Black should try 20...f6 21.Ra4 $16 and we will double up on the a-file. } )
