5. Bd3 c5 ( { This is the most popular variation. If Black does not do anything in the center, White wants Ne2, O-O etc. For this reason Black should react in the center with either } 5...d5 { or } ) ( 5...c5 { (I cover the alternatives as well, but they are not really critical and White should be better there). } { 5.Bd2!? is another approach that is a modern innovation in Rubinstein Variation. White wants to recapture with the bishop on c3 and avoid doubled pawns. } ) 
6. Nge2 d5 
7. cxd5 { Before Black gets the chance to play ...dxc4. } cxd4 
8. exd4 Qxd5 
9. O-O Qh5 { With the white knight on e2, Black sometimes brings his queen to h5, just like in the main line. Here it works less well, though. } 
10. Ne4! Nxe4 ( 10...Nd5 { allows } 11.Ng5!? { which forces some weakening on the kingside. } 11...h6?! { is not good, as after } 12.Nf3 { ...f6 should be played anyway, or otherwise, the queen is trapped. Therefore, Black should play @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/pp3ppp/4p3/3n2Nq/1b1P4/3B4/PP2NPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 5 11@@EndFEN@@ 11...f6 but White is better after 12.Nf3 Nc6 13.a3 Bd6 14.Re1 $14 . } ) 
11. Bxe4 Bd6 { Here, White can either go for a better endgame or keep more pieces on the board, with better chances in both cases. } 
12. h3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( 12.Bf4 Bxf4 13.Nxf4 Qxd1 14.Rfxd1 $14 { and in this endgame, White is also better, e.g. } 14...Nd7 15.Rac1 Nf6 16.f3!? { threatening Rc7 } 16...Nxe4 17.fxe4 Bd7 18.Rc7 Bc6 19.d5 exd5 20.exd5 Rfd8 21.b3 $14 { . } ) Nc6 
13. Be3 Rd8 ( { White is also better after } 13...Qh4 14.Nc3 Rd8 15.Qe2 $14 { followed by Rad1. } ) 
14. Nc3 Qxd1 
15. Rfxd1 $14  {[%cal Gd4d5][%csl Ge4,Ge3,Rc8,Ra8]} { Such endgame, with d5 coming next, is also better for White. } *

