12. Bc2 Bd7 
13. Qd3! { Suddenly, there is no convenient defense for the h7-pawn. } f5 ( { Perhaps the best move (the lesser evil), but it also has its drawbacks. } 13...g6?! { weakens all the dark squares around Black's king and creates a hook that White may immediately try to exploit with } 14.h4!? $14 { . } ) 
14. Bb3! {[%mdl 32768]} Qb6 
15. Nxd5! ( { Here, White has a choice between } 15.Ba2 { or } ) ( 15.Na4 { , but I think keeping things simple makes a lot of sense. } ) Nxd5 
16. Bxd5 exd5 
17. Bf4 { With this operation, White begins to play against the bad light-squared bishop, trying to exploit it by playing on the dark squares. } Rae8 
18. Qd2!? ( { This would be my suggested improvement. Duda played } 18.g3?! { and after the precise } 18...Bxf4 19.Nxf4 Re4! { Nakamura equalized fully. } ) h6 { Black should sort of stall for now, but maybe prepare ...g5 at some point. } ( 18...Bxf4?! 19.Nxf4 Re4 { does not work now as White's queen is on d2 now and does not run under a tempo after } 20.Rxe4 dxe4 { . Therefore, we can continue with } 21.Rc1 $16 { with a clear advantage due to the control over the dark squares and our better pieces. } ) 
19. f3 $14  {[%cal Gf3e4][%csl Rd7,Re4]} { Controlling the e4-square. I think that in the long term, White can put here a lot of pressure on Black and issues with the d7-bishop can be troubling further down the road. } *

