10. a3 Bd6 { The main trend recently here. Black leaves the e7-square for the knight and keeps the diagonal open, potentially for Black's queen to go to h4. } 
11. Re1 { This is the recent trend. The rook is useful there in many lines, and White waits for Black to choose their setup now. It is a top suggestion by the engines, and many GMs have gone for it. One of the main ideas here is Bc2 and Qd3 trying to weaken Black's kingside. } ( 11.Bc2 { with the idea of Qd3 is premature for perhaps many reasons, but one of the clearest is } 11...Qh4 12.g3 Qh5 { when comparing to the position with Re1 instead of Bc2, White would be better off having the rook on the open file. } ) Re8 
12. Bc2 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gd1d3]} { The inclusion of Re1-...Re8 helps White. We are in a better position to fight for the e-file if we ever trade on d5. } Qh4 { Nakamura played few games like this too. } 
13. Ng3! ( 13.g3?! Qh5 { is OK for Black, as in Caruana-Nakamura (2021). } ) Bd7 
14. Nce4! { I would suggest this move which hits the bishop and threatens Bg5. Black has two options now. } ( 14.Re4 { was tried by Sarana, and again, it is not an ideal move. } 14...Qd8 15.Qd3 f5 $132 { and Hikaru was doing well and went on to win this game eventually. } ) Bf4 { Though possible too, this allows the knight to jump to c5 unopposed. } 
15. Nc5 Re7 
16. Be4 $14  { The simplest. The pressure in the center and the queenside is quite annoying for Black. } ( 16.Bxf4 { is another option, leading to a complicated tactical fight: } 16...Nxf4 17.Re4!? f5! 18.Nxf5 exf5 19.g3 { with a huge mess which is probably not necessary, e.g. } 19...fxe4!! 20.gxh4 Bh3! 21.Bxe4 Nxd4 22.f3 Rf8= $13 { . } ) *

