5. Bd3 d5 ( { This is the most popular variation. If Black does not do anything in the center, White wants Ne2, O-O etc. For this reason Black should react in the center with either } 5...d5 { or } ) ( 5...c5 { (I cover the alternatives as well, but they are not really critical and White should be better there). } { 5.Bd2!? is another approach that is a modern innovation in Rubinstein Variation. White wants to recapture with the bishop on c3 and avoid doubled pawns. } ) 
6. a3 { I would recommend this line. White attempts to get a pair of bishops right away hoping that it will prove beneficial in the long term. } Bxc3+ ( { The main move. } 6...Be7 { and } ) ( 6...Bd6 { are analyzed after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.e3 d5 5.a3 . } ) 
7. bxc3 {[%mdl 32768]} dxc4 
8. Bxc4 c5 
9. Nf3 ( 9.Ne2 { is another move, but I prefer the text. } ) Qc7 { Black puts some pressure on the c-file, which is typical in these positions. } 
10. Be2 ( { I think that this move is objectively better than } 10.Ba2 { , when } 10...b5! { is strong, as I recommend for Black in my book. } ) b6 
11. Bb2! ( { This is a subtle but correct move order. White prevents ...Ba6 ideas. } 11.O-O Ba6 { is an additional option for Black when they likely equalize without much trouble. The bishops are forced off the board, which generally helps Black. } ) cxd4 
12. cxd4 Ba6 { A recent trend here, forcing a trade of light-squared bishops. On the other hand, though, the tension in the center has been released and this gives White other ideas. } 
13. O-O Bxe2 
14. Qxe2 Nbd7 
15. e4! Rac8 
16. Rfc1! Qb7 
17. Re1 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gd2f1][%csl Rb2]} { A swift maneuver - kicking away the queen from the c-file so that ...Qc2 is not possible. Right now, a very important idea for White to know is Nd2-Nf1, but first, we should protect the bishop (Nd2 can be met by ...Rc2), so White should begin with Rab1. } Qc6 { Here ...Rc2 is not an idea anymore. } 
18. Nd2 Qc2 
19. Rab1 {[%cal Ge1c1]} { With Rec1 next. } Rfd8 
20. Rec1 Qa4 
21. Nf1 { The position looks playable. } *

