[ECO "E49"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd3 d5 ( { This is the most popular variation. If Black does not do anything in the center, White wants Ne2, O-O etc. For this reason Black should react in the center with either } 5...d5 { or } ) ( 5...c5 { (I cover the alternatives as well, but they are not really critical and White should be better there). } { 5.Bd2!? is another approach that is a modern innovation in Rubinstein Variation. White wants to recapture with the bishop on c3 and avoid doubled pawns. } ) 
6. a3 { I would recommend this line. White attempts to get a pair of bishops right away hoping that it will prove beneficial in the long term. } Bxc3+ ( { The main move. } 6...Be7 { and } ) ( 6...Bd6 { are analyzed after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.e3 d5 5.a3 . } ) 
7. bxc3 dxc4 
8. Bxc4 c5 
9. Nf3 ( 9.Ne2 { is another move, but I prefer the text. } ) Qc7 { Black puts some pressure on the c-file, which is typical in these positions. } 
10. Be2 ( { I think that this move is objectively better than } 10.Ba2 { , when } 10...b5! { is strong, as I recommend for Black in my book. } ) b6 
11. Bb2! ( { This is a subtle but correct move order. White prevents ...Ba6 ideas. } 11.O-O Ba6 { is an additional option for Black when they likely equalize without much trouble. The bishops are forced off the board, which generally helps Black. } ) Bb7 
12. O-O Nbd7 ( { Now } 12...Ng4?! { is premature due to } 13.Re1 $14 { and ...Bxf3 is not a concern anymore, while the knight pretty much just has wasted a tempo. } 13...Bxf3? 14.Bxf3 Qxh2+ 15.Kf1+- { . } ) ( { The most played. Here, White has two interesting approaches, and I would recommend both. } 12...Rd8 { is a move order that has been seen a couple of times as well, but it would likely just transpose. } 13.Re1 Nc6 { and } { 13...Nbd7 14.c4 may transpose soon too. } ) 
13. Nd2!? { This would be the first of my recommendations. The idea of this move is to keep the center the way it is for now, and later decide later how to proceed. The key ideas on White's agenda, apart from deciding whether to play e4 or c4 in the future, are a4-a5, challenging the queenside, and Re1. The rook would potentially support a future e4 or, in the event of c4 followed by ...cxd4-exd4, would be placed perfectly too. Rc1 is also possible. } Rfd8 { This strikes me as the most accurate. The idea is to prepare ...e5, followed by ...Nf8 and ...Ne6 if needed. } ( { In contrast, } 13...Rac8 { is less flexible } ) ( 13...e5 { is a bit premature. Black should bring the rooks to the game first. Still, it should transpose to some of the other lines: } 14.Qb3 Rac8 15.a4 Rfd8 16.Rfd1 { transposing to 13...Rfd8. } ) 
14. a4!? ( { Playing for e4 is not that great now: } 14.Rc1 e5 15.Re1 Nf8! 16.Bd3 Ne6= { and Black has successfully rearranged his pieces. } ) Rac8 { Here, White can transpose to the 13.c4 line by playing } { 14.c4 . There are alternatives, too: } 
15. Re1 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 
16. Bd3 { With ideas of Bf5. Also, Rc1 is coming soon, and then White will perhaps try to get e4 in. } ( 16.Qb3!? { can be played too, though normally we would want our rook on d1 (see this previous line. [/variation/21649353/#/16/w]) } ) e4?! { Generally, this is not what Black should do. This releases the tension in the center and White will want to play c4 and d5, with some advantage. } 
17. Bf1 cxd4 ( { This is the most principled. } 17...h6? 18.c4 $16 { is a dream position for White. } ) 
18. cxd4 $14  {[%cal Gb2a3,Ga4a5,Gd2c4]} ( { The simplest, though } 18.exd4 { was also good. Now White wants Ba3, maybe a5, potentially Nc4. and play on the queenside. The d5-square is not that important. } ) *

