Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 c5 { A good reaction to the 5.Bd2 line, which I employed myself in my own games as Black and also suggested in my book on Nimzo Indian. } 
6. a3 { Anything else promises nothing. } Bxc3 
7. Bxc3 Ne4 
8. Ne2! { The recent trend. Only here White can look for some ideas. } b6! 
9. d5 d6 
10. dxe6!? {[%mdl 32768]} { Following Bluebaum again! } fxe6 
11. f3 Qh4+ 
12. g3 Nxc3 
13. Nxc3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gf3f4]} { This is similar to 11...Nxc3 [/variation/21571751/#/11/b] but I think that provoking g3 actually helps White - now, White can play Bg2 and f4, which in the long term can be unpleasant to Black. } Qh6 ( 13...Qe7 14.Bg2 Bb7 15.O-O Nd7 16.f4 $14 { . } ) 
14. Qe2! {[%cal Gf3f4,Gf1g2]} -- ( { With the idea of f4 and Bg2. Play may continue } 14...Nc6 15.f4 Ba6 16.Qc2 Na5 17.Bg2 Rab8 18.b3 $14 { . } )
