[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "27) Nimzo Indian: Alternative 5.Bd2!? c5"]
[Black "6...Bxc3 7.Bxc3 Ne4 8.Ne2 b6 #14 Alternative to 13.Qxc3 #2"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21571755"]
[ECO "E46"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 c5 { A good reaction to the 5.Bd2 line, which I employed myself in my own games as Black and also suggested in my book on Nimzo Indian. } 
6. a3 { Anything else promises nothing. } Bxc3 
7. Bxc3 Ne4 
8. Ne2! { The recent trend. Only here White can look for some ideas. } b6! 
9. d5 Ba6!? { I think this is the best move in this position. At first it happened in Yuffa-Aronian (2019) but later I played this against Bluebaum too. Black immediately puts pressure on the c4-pawn. } 
10. b3 ( { White should not fall for } 10.f3?! Nxc3 11.Nxc3 Bxc4! 12.Bxc4 Qh4+ 13.g3 Qxc4 $15 { , which gives Black an extra pawn. } ) ( 10.Qd3 { was Bluebaum's choice against me but here Black is fine after } 10...exd5 11.Qxd5 Qe7!= { followed by ...Nc6 and ...Nxc3 at some point. } ) b5! 
11. Qc2!? ( { I would recommend this. I looked at it in my book too, but perhaps not deeply enough. } 11.Qd3 { was played in the above-mentioned Yuffa-Aronian (2019). In my book, I showed an improvement over Aronian's } 11...exd5?! { when } 12.Qxd5!? { is possible, but after } { 12.cxb5! Bb7 13.Bb2 $14 White is better thanks to the pair of bishops.

The strong @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/p2p1ppp/b3p3/1ppP4/2P1n3/PPBQP3/4NPPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@ 11...Nxc3 $146 equalizes by force. Black gets an even better version of the 10.f3 line as White's queenside is weakened, which gives Black time to complete the development and hold the extra pawn. 12.Nxc3 bxc4 13.bxc4 exd5 followed by ...Nc6, ...Qa5 etc. with lots of dynamic play. Black is fine, as seen in, for example, 14.Nxd5 Nc6 15.Be2 Qa5+ 16.Qc3 Rab8 17.O-O Qxc3 18.Nxc3 Na5= . } ) ( 11.f3? { runs into the same trick: } 11...Nxc3 12.Nxc3 bxc4 13.bxc4 Bxc4! 14.Bxc4 Qh4+ 15.g3 Qxc4 $16 { . } ) exd5 
12. cxd5 Nxc3 { Both recaptures offer White some practical chances, even though objectively the position is equal. } 
13. Nxc3 b4! { This is a strong reply. } 
14. Nb5!? { Only this move could potentially pose some problems to Black, which is also a move I missed in the book. } Qf6 { This is less accurate. } 
15. Rc1! bxa3 
16. Qxc5! Qg6!! ( { Here, Black is under some pressure. Note that if } 16...a2?! 17.Qa3 $14 { we are just in time to catch the pawn! } { Instead, 16.Nc7 Bxf1 17.Kxf1 Na6 18.Nxa8 Nb4= $13 gives Black a tremendous compensation. }) { The only move that keeps is relatively equal! But it is an incredibly difficult move to play. } 
17. Qd6!? {[%mdl 32768]} { The best try. 17. Nxa3 Bxf1 18.Kxf1 Qd3+ 19. Kg1 Qxb3= is also equal. } Qxd6 
18. Nxd6 Bxf1 
19. Kxf1 { After 19...Na6 20. Ra1 Rfb8! 21. Rxa3 Nc5= Black wins back the pawn with an equal endgame. } *

