11. a3 ( { I would recommend going for positional play with this move. In blitz, I tried to immediately exploit Parham's unorthodox play in the opening with } 11.Ne5? { but this doesn't work now due to } 11...Nxe5 12.dxe5 Ng4! 13.f4 d4! { $17 and Black is better. } { The game was unclear after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/5ppp/1pp2n2/p2pP3/1b6/2NBP3/PP1B1PPP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@ 12...Nd7? 13.f4 and with help from my opponent, I managed to build a strong attack on the kingside and win quickly: 13...Nc5 14.Bb1 d4? 15.Ne4 Ba6? 16.Nf6+!! gxf6 17.Bxh7+ Kxh7 18.Qh5+ and checkmate is inevitable. 18...Kg7 19.Qg4+ Kh8 20.Rf3 Bd3 21.f5 Bxf5 22.Rxf5 1-0 Swiercz, D (2649)-Maghsoodloo, P (2676) Chess.com INT 2020. } ) Be7 ( 11...Bxc3 { is generally good news for White. } 12.Bxc3 Ba6 13.Bxa6 Rxa6 14.Ne5 $14 { . } ) 
12. Qc2 Ba6 ( 12...Bb7 { allows } 13.Ne5! g6 14.f4 $14 { . } ) 
13. Bxa6 Rxa6 
14. e4! { Breaking through in the center, taking advantage of the awkward rook on a6 and the weak c6-pawn. } dxe4 
15. Nxe4 Nxe4 
16. Qxe4 c5 
17. Rfd1 $14  {[%csl Ra6]} { White has better pieces, with a striking contrast between our rooks and our opponent's. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "29) Nimzo Indian: Alternative 5.Bd2!? d5 6...Nbd7"]
[Black "7...c6 8.Bd3 dxc4 9.Bxc4 Qe7 #1"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21667873"]
[ECO "E46"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 d5 
6. Nf3 Nbd7 ( { It is worth noting that playing } 6...c6 { here lets White save on Rc1 and play } 7.Bd3 $14 { right away. I think that is just better for White, as it is an improved version of the main line. } ) 
7. Rc1 ( { White should start with this move. If } 7.Bd3 dxc4 8.Bxc4 b6 { White has wasted a tempo on Bd3 and Bxc4 and Black has not played ...c6, therefore keeping an option of playing ...c5. } ) c6 { The position now resembles a Semi-Slav, or simply a Meran to be more precise. Compared to a 'normal' Meran, White has already played Bd2 and Rc1, which I believe can be useful. Also, the bishop is not necessarily well placed on b4 and probably Black needs to waste a tempo on ...Bd6, where it really belongs. In these positions, typically, after supporting the d5-pawn, Black's plan involves ...e5 at some point. } 
8. Bd3 dxc4 { The most direct, and sooner or later Black should play it. } 
9. Bxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} Qe7!? { Black can keep the bishop on b4 and support ...e5 in another way. In some positions, Black may consider ...Bxc3, or simply wait for White to play a3 and only then ...Bd6. This was played by Carlsen. } 
10. O-O e5 { White has two interesting options now. } 
11. Bb3 $146  { I think that this is quite challenging. I would recommend it as it has not been played yet so it can be a surprise to someone playing it with Black. } Bd6 { Not the best. } 
12. h3!? { Black is stuck in some way, as neither ...h6 nor ...e4 are good. } e4 ( { If } 12...h6 13.Nh4!↑ { with Nf5 and Ng6 ideas. } ) 
13. Ng5 h6 { It seems like the knight is trapped. However - White is doing great! } 
14. Nxf7!? Rxf7 
15. f3 -- ( { With strong initiative. A possible continuation is } 15...exf3 16.Qxf3 Nb6 17.Bxf7+ Qxf7 18.e4 $14 { . } )
*

