1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 d5 
6. Nf3 Nbd7 ( { It is worth noting that playing } 6...c6 { here lets White save on Rc1 and play } 7.Bd3 $14 { right away. I think that is just better for White, as it is an improved version of the main line. } ) 
7. Rc1 ( { White should start with this move. If } 7.Bd3 dxc4 8.Bxc4 b6 { White has wasted a tempo on Bd3 and Bxc4 and Black has not played ...c6, therefore keeping an option of playing ...c5. } ) c6 { The position now resembles a Semi-Slav, or simply a Meran to be more precise. Compared to a 'normal' Meran, White has already played Bd2 and Rc1, which I believe can be useful. Also, the bishop is not necessarily well placed on b4 and probably Black needs to waste a tempo on ...Bd6, where it really belongs. In these positions, typically, after supporting the d5-pawn, Black's plan involves ...e5 at some point. } 
8. Bd3 dxc4 { The most direct, and sooner or later Black should play it. } 
9. Bxc4 Bd6 { The most popular move. Black prepares ...e5. } 
10. O-O e5 
11. Qc2 { Stopping ...e4. } h6 $146  { Black wants to prepare ...e4 by first covering the g5-square and playing ...Re8 next. Please note that this move is good now with the queen on d8 instead of e7 - there are no Nh4 ideas! It is a top suggestion by the engine, so it should be covered. I believe Black should equalize here eventually. } 
12. dxe5 { Probably the most challenging. } Nxe5 
13. Nxe5 Bxe5 
14. f4 Bc7 ( 14...Bd4 { is flashy, but White can transpose to } ) ( 14...Bc7 { after } 15.Kh1 b5 16.Bd3 Bb6 { . } ) 
15. Kh1 { White's plan is to play e4 at some point. Black needs to play dynamically to prevent it, or at least get ready for it. } b5! 
16. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bb6 
17. h3 { White wants to prepare e4. } Bb7 ( 17...b4 18.Ne4 $14 { . } ) 
18. e4 b4 
19. Na4 ( 19.Ne2!? { is also playable, e.g. } 19...Ng4 20.Bc4 Nf2+ 21.Kh2 Nxe4 22.Bxb4 c5 23.Be1 $13 { . } ) Qd4! { With precise dynamic play, Black manages to keep the game level. } 
20. Rcd1 ( 20.e5 { is possible too but after } 20...Rfd8! { Black is fine. } 21.exf6 Qxd3 22.Qxd3 Rxd3 23.Bxb4 c5 24.Bxc5 Rd2 25.Rg1 gxf6= $13 { and Black has sufficient compensation. } ) c5 
