7. Bd3 ( 7.Rc1 { is another option, but I like it less. Note that after } 7...b6 { , at the very least White can transpose to the 6...b6 line with } 8.cxd5 exd5 { and we are back at the main line. However, @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/p1p2ppp/1p2pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2NBPN2/PP1B1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 8.O-O is also good: 8...dxc4 9.Bxc4 is analyzed after 7...dxc4. } ) c5 { The most logical follow-up to 6...Re8 as when the center opens, Black may try to play ...e5. } 
8. O-O ( { White goes for a playable position with an IQP. } 8.a3!? { is a decent option for White. We immediately get the pair of bishops. Unfortunately, Black has here a pretty simple path to equality. } 8...cxd4?! 9.axb4 dxc3 10.Bxc3 dxc4 11.Bxc4 $14 { is typically better for White, but after } { 8...Bxc3 9.Bxc3 not 9...Nbd7?! 10.b3! $14 with the bishops pair, but @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/2PP4/P1BBPN2/1P3PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ 9...cxd4! Black equalizes after 10.exd4 dxc4 11.Bxc4 b6= or @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp3ppp/4pn2/3p4/2Pp4/P1BBPN2/1P3PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10.Bxd4 Nc6= .

