[White "31) Nimzo Indian: 5.Bd2 d5 6...b6 8.Bd3 others"]
[Black "8...Bd6 #12"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21649424"]
[ECO "E46"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 d5 
6. Nf3 b6 
7. cxd5 exd5 
8. Bd3 Bd6 { This is one of the best move orders available to Black, though not the most popular. The idea is to prevent Ne5 ideas by playing ...Re8. Additionally, Black may try a quick ...c5 without losing the dark-squared bishop. GMs like Vidit or Huschenbeth have played this move. } ( { After } 8...Re8 { , White can try something like } 9.Ne5 { or just transpose by playing } { 9.O-O Bd6 . I would most likely stick with 9.O-O to keep the repertoire simple. } ) 
9. O-O Re8 
10. Nb5 ( 10.Qb1 { is not as great as it was with ...Bb7 instead of ...Re8. Among many options, I consider } 10...Nbd7!? { the best. Black can comfortably equalize after } 11.b4 c5= { or @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/p1pn1ppp/1p1b1n2/3p4/3P4/2NBPN2/PP1B1PPP/RQ3RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ 11.e4 dxe4 12.Nxe4 Bb7 13.Nxd6 cxd6= . } { Note White can meet the immediate @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/p1p2ppp/1p1b1n2/3p4/3P4/2NBPN2/PP1B1PPP/RQ3RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10...c5? with 11.e4!↑ . } ) Bf8 
11. Ne5 { I think going for Ne5 is generally the most challenging. } Ba6 
12. Be1 $146  { This move is new in this particular position. Black has two main options here: ...c6 or ...c5. } c6 { I think Black should play this move to trade light squared bishops. } 
13. Nc3 Bxd3 
14. Qxd3 { This position is objectively equal, of course, but again White has a very simple plan: f4 and Bh4. Black really needs to come up with some counterplay, but first, they need to complete the development of the queenside. } Qc8 ( { Other moves like ...Qc7 are also possible, of course, but it would result in similar positions: } 14...c5?! 15.f4! $14 { and Bh4. } ) 
15. Rc1 Nbd7 
16. f4 Qb7 
17. Bh4 Rac8 
18. a3!? { A useful waiting move. The point is that, in some lines, Black wants ...b5-...b4 to chase the knight away, and the a3-pawn slows it down. }a5 ( { Again, } 18...c5?! { is weakening the center. } 19.Rfd1 $14 { there are potential ideas of Nxd7 and dxc5 and go after the d5-pawn. } ) ( 18...b5 19.Bxf6 Nxf6 20.g4↑ { followed by g5 is similar to the main line. } ) 
19. Bxf6 Nxf6 
20. g4 c5! { The standard reaction to aggression on the side of the board is to counter in the center. That's precisely what Black does. } 
21. dxc5 Bxc5 
22. g5 Nh5 
23. b4! axb4 
24. axb4 { Black is under some pressure here. } Nxf4!! { Black should sac a piece, which is not obvious at all and it is a rather difficult practical decision. } 
25. Rxf4 {[%mdl 32768]} Rxe5 
26. bxc5 Rxg5+ 
27. Kf2 bxc5 
28. Rb1!? Qc6 
29. Rg1 $13  { Black has sufficient compensation for the piece. Still, it is already move 28, and Black has had many options on the way. Even if by some miracle this position arises on the board, it is still playable, and with the extra piece we need to consolidate and then look for chances. } *

