15. O-O! {[%cal Gb1e1,Gf2f3,Ge3e4]} { Black wanted ...Rb8 and ...b4 - now, White has the Qe1 resource if needed. And normally White wants f3-e4. Also, b3!? may be considered. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "31) Nimzo Indian: 5.Bd2 d5 6...b6 8.Bd3 others"]
[Black "8...c5 #9"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21649435"]
[ECO "E46"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 d5 
6. Nf3 b6 
7. cxd5 exd5 
8. Bd3 c5 { One of the main alternatives. } 
9. h3!? {[%cal Rc8g4]} { I like this move, whose idea is to prevent ...Bg4 in some lines. I tried it myself twice and I got good positions. } ( 9.a3 Bxc3 10.Bxc3 c4 11.Bc2 Bg4! { is OK for Black. If not for ...Bg4, White would be better though... For this reason I suggest 9.h3!?. } ) Nc6 
10. a3 Bxc3 { The most obvious 'automatic' move, a very safe approach that is also the most expected. } 
11. Bxc3 c4 
12. Bc2 { I think that this position is playable. } Ne7 {[%cal Gc8f5]} { One of the most logical moves here, typical for Ragozin structures. } 
13. Qb1 {[%mdl 32768]} { White should prevent ...Bf5 for now, even if only temporarily, given Black's next move. } g6! {[%cal Gc8f5]} { Here White has some choice. } 
14. Ne5! Bf5 
15. f3! { I think this is White's best practical option. } Bxc2?! { The more human approach. } 
16. Qxc2 Nf5 
17. Qf2 $14  {[%cal Ge1g1,Ge3e4]} { Black's knights are restricted. White wants now O-O and then prepare the e4 break. } *

