1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 d5 
6. Nf3 b6 
7. cxd5 exd5 
8. Bd3 ( 8.Rc1 { is another way to play this position. However, I like playing these positions without Rc1 - more often than not, it seems like White simply does not need this move. } ) Bb7 
9. O-O {[%mdl 32768]} { White has a couple of possible plans in these positions. The most popular one is Ne5 followed by f4, then transfer the bishop to h4 via e1 and attack on the kingside. Another option is a queenside minority pawn attack (the Qb1!?-b4 idea in the main line).

Finally, White may consider playing in the center by breaking through with e4, but that is rather rare and it usually occurs if Black plays something like ...c6. Then, the b7-bishop is blocked, or there is some tactical justification. } Nbd7 {[%cal Gb4d6,Rf3e5,Rf2f4]} 
10. Qc2!? {[%cal Gf3e5]} ( { Black wants ...Bd6 and control the e5-square, prevening Ne5 and f4 ideas. And } 10.Ne5 { , as discussed soon, does not work either. } ) { White prepares Ne5. This is also a prophylaxis against ...Bd6. } ( { Just to illustrate, } 10.Ne5 { is premature now: } 10...Nxe5 11.dxe5 Nd7 12.f4 Nc5! $132 { with ...d4 next and lots of counterplay. } ) c5 { It makes sense to attack in the center right away. White has many options here. } 
11. a3 { The most natural move. } Bxc3 
12. Bxc3 c4 
13. Bf5 ( 13.Be2 Ne4 14.a4!? { is interesting too. Rfb1 intending b3 is an idea. } ) Ne4 
14. Nd2 ( 14.Bxe4 dxe4 15.Nd2 { is also possible, winning a pawn, but Black should have a very good compensation. } 15...Nf6 16.Nxc4 Qd5 17.Ne5 Qe6= $13 { . } ) Nxc3 
15. bxc3 Nf6 
16. f3 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gf1e1]} { Preparing a future e4. The position is playable. } *

