1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 d5 
6. Nf3 b6 
7. cxd5 exd5 
8. Bd3 ( 8.Rc1 { is another way to play this position. However, I like playing these positions without Rc1 - more often than not, it seems like White simply does not need this move. } ) Bb7 
9. O-O { White has a couple of possible plans in these positions. The most popular one is Ne5 followed by f4, then transfer the bishop to h4 via e1 and attack on the kingside. Another option is a queenside minority pawn attack (the Qb1!?-b4 idea in the main line).

Finally, White may consider playing in the center by breaking through with e4, but that is rather rare and it usually occurs if Black plays something like ...c6. Then, the b7-bishop is blocked, or there is some tactical justification. } Be7 { As ...c5 right away does not work too well, Black may try to retreat the bishop first and then play ...c5. Many top players have recently tried this, including Liem Le Quang and Levon Aronian. } 
10. Ne5 c5 
11. Qf3!? {[%cal Gf3h3]} ( { I would recommend this active plan. } 11.f4?! Nc6 { is fine for Black. } ) Nc6 
12. Qh3! h6 ( { Black cannot win the d4-pawn: } 12...cxd4 13.exd4 Nxd4? { runs into } 14.Nd7 $16 { and White wins an exchange, as in Travadon-Sonis (2021). } ) 
13. Rad1! Bd6 ( { Capturing the d4-pawn is still not good: } 13...cxd4 14.exd4 Nxd4? 15.Bxh6 $16 { and now: } 15...gxh6 16.Qxh6 { leads to a winning attack for White and if @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2bpp1/1p3n1B/3pN3/3n4/2NB3Q/PP3PPP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@ 15...Qc8 16.Qg3 Nh5 17.Qe3 Nf5 18.Qf3 Nxh6 19.Qxh5 $16 White has a clear advantage. } ) 
14. Ng4! ( 14.f4?! { is not that great here on account of } 14...cxd4 15.Nxc6 Bxc6 16.exd4 b5! $132 { with counterplay. } ) Nxg4 
15. Qxg4 { I like White's chances here. Black's center is slightly weak, and White can put pressure on it. } Ne7 
16. dxc5 $146  {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Opening up the center and going for central play. } 16.Bc1?! { is too passive. In Travadon-Fedorchuk (2021) things turned quite badly for White after } 16...c4 17.Bc2 f5 $15 { . Suddenly, White has little space and no active plan. Black went on to win the game. } ) bxc5 
17. e4! { Everything works great for White tactically: } c4 ( 17...d4 { is met by } 18.Bxh6+- { . } ) 
18. Bxc4! dxc4 
19. Bf4 {[%csl Rd6]} h5 {[%csl Rf4]} 
20. Qf3 {[%csl Gf4]} { The queen must keep on protecting the f4-bishop. } Nc8 
21. Bxd6 Nxd6 { Here, White has a pleasant choice. } 
22. Qg3 {[%cal Gd1d6][%csl Rd6]} { Next, we'll get our piece back. } Nxe4 
23. Nxe4 $14  {[%cal Ge4d6][%csl Rc4]} { White has strong initiative. } *

