Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 d5 
6. Nf3 b6 
7. cxd5 exd5 
8. Bd3 ( 8.Rc1 { is another way to play this position. However, I like playing these positions without Rc1 - more often than not, it seems like White simply does not need this move. } ) Bb7 
9. O-O { White has a couple of possible plans in these positions. The most popular one is Ne5 followed by f4, then transfer the bishop to h4 via e1 and attack on the kingside. Another option is a queenside minority pawn attack (the Qb1!?-b4 idea in the main line).

Finally, White may consider playing in the center by breaking through with e4, but that is rather rare and it usually occurs if Black plays something like ...c6. Then, the b7-bishop is blocked, or there is some tactical justification. } Bd6 
10. Qb1!? { There are other moves, like Nb5 or Ne5, but I like this flexible move the most. The idea is to improve on Qc2 - in some of the lines, the queen runs into some attack on c2. Additionally, White wants to gain space on the queenside with b4. } c5!? { The most natural move. It is worth to note that with the queen on c2, this move would be very good, as I will explain soon. } 
11. dxc5 bxc5 
12. e4! { Now White plays in the center as the dynamics works in our favor. } d4 { This seems logical, but is highly risky for Black. } 
13. e5! { Going for the initiative. Black is under pressure and perhaps can eventually equalize with perfect play, but it is far from easy... Some sample lines: } dxc3 
14. Bxc3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bxf3 
15. exf6 {[%cal Gd3h7,Gf6g7]} g6□ { Forced. } 
16. gxf3 Nd7 { This position results nearly by force. Thanks to the pair of bishops and dynamic play, White retains good chances despite the weakened king: } 
17. Rd1! {[%cal Gd1d8]} Nxf6 
18. Bc4 { White has a lot of pressure. } Nh5 
19. Qe4 Nf4 
20. Kh1 {[%cal Gd1g1]} { Freeing the g1-square for the rook. } Qg5 
21. Rg1↑ -- ( { White has a strong initiative. Maybe, with perfect play, Black can eventually equalize, but it will not be by any means easy. For example, } 21...Qh6 22.Rg3 Rae8 23.Qc6 Rd8 24.Rd1 Nh3 25.Kg2 Nf4+ 26.Kg1 Be7 27.Re1 Bd6 { and the engine claims that it holds, but even if it does, it looks very shaky... } { Or 21...Qh5 22.Bxf7+ Kxf7 23.Qb7+ Be7 24.Rg4 Ne6 25.Re1 Qf5 26.Re5 Qf6 27.Rh5 gxh5 28.Bxf6 Kxf6 29.Rg1 Rad8 30.Qe4↑ , and with such a weak king, Black still needs to work hard to prove equality. } )
