1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein Variation in Nimzo Indian is one of the oldest and the most tested in practice classical approaches in this opening. Developed in the early 1900s by the top players of that era, popularized mainly by Rubinstein and his e3-Ne2 idea (the Rubinstein Variation in its purest form), these days it went through well-scrutinized analysis by modern top players with the support of best engines.

Over the years many variations were tested and tried. With such a strategically sound opening like Nimzo, it is pretty much impossible to find an objective advantage if Black plays sound lines. And it is neither my objective to refute 100+ years of theory that Stockfish and Lc0 support. But finding playable positions that pose some practical problems for players who are not thoroughly familiar with the ideas is highly possible. } O-O ( { This is by far the most accurate variation as it offers the most flexibility in the subsequent choice of setups, depending on what White chooses to play. Generally, I would suggest two different setups for White here, just to add more flexibility and choice when facing } 4...O-O { . } ) 
5. Bd2 d5 
6. Nf3 c5 { Black immediately challenges White in the center. } 
7. a3! Bxc3 
8. Bxc3 Ne4 { The main move. Black ensures that White's pair of bishops will not last for long. Without this move, Black may not ever get to trade this bishop. My analysis of the sidelines shows what might happen. } ( 8...b6 9.dxc5 bxc5 10.Bd3 $14 { . } ) ( 8...Nbd7 9.dxc5 Nxc5 10.cxd5 { when the position opens and White retains the pair of bishops. } 10...Qxd5 11.Bb4 $14 { or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/4pn2/2nP4/8/P1B1PN2/1P3PPP/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10...Nxd5 11.Bd4 b6 12.Be2 $14 . } ) ( 8...Nc6? { is bad for Black: } 9.dxc5 Ne4 10.Qc2 Nxc5 11.b4 Ne4 12.Bb2 $16 { . } ) 
9. Rc1 Nxc3 { Black can try some other moves, but sooner or later Black should play ...Nxc3 anyway. } 
10. Rxc3 cxd4 
11. Nxd4 dxc4 
12. Bxc4 Bd7 {[%cal Gb8c6]} { That's the most normal way to develop pieces. } 
13. O-O {[%mdl 32768]} Nc6 
14. Nf3 $14  {[%cal Gd1c2,Gf1c1,Gc4a2,Ga2b1,Yc4d3,Yd3e4]} { An important nuance. White should keep the knights on the board. Even though the position is nearly symmetrical, White has an edge here due to our more active pieces and various plans available.

The most obvious plan for White is to play on the queenside (Qc2, Rc1, b4 for instance) but in combination with some kingside play (Ba2-Bb1!? or Bd3-Be4, maybe h4-h5!?) Black's defensive tasks will be likely kind of hard.

The position is simply playable and, in my view, direct move-by-move analysis is of little use - we should try to understand plans and ideas instead. For this reason, I include some possible courses of the game that are logical from both sides. As we will see, White has good chances! } Qe7 
15. Qc2 Rac8 
16. Rc1 ( { Or } 16.Bd3!? h6 17.Bh7+ Kh8 18.Be4 $14 { and it could be difficult to Black to untangle on the queenside. } ) Rfd8 
17. h4!? { aggressive option. } h6 
18. Qe4 Be8 
19. g4 $14  -- ( { Intending to either attack on the kingside or simply create some weaknesses there for Black. White is better: } 19...g6 20.b4 a6 21.Qf4 Kg7 22.g5 hxg5 23.hxg5 Bd7 24.Ne5 Nxe5 25.Qxe5+ f6 26.Qe4 $14 { is a sample line. } )
