1. d4 Nf6 ( { • } 1...g6 { Black may play also without ...Nf6. } 2.c4 Bg7 3.e4 d6 4.Nc3 e5 5.Nf3 exd4 { 5...Nd7 6.Be2 Ne7 7.O-O O-O 8.Be3 I don't think this can be equalizing. } 6.Nxd4 Nc6 7.Be3 Nge7 8.h4 f5 { 8...h5 9.Qd2 O-O 10.O-O-O f5 11.f3! Stabilizing the center. The main idea is to break through at some point in the center (c5!?) 11...f4 12.Bf2 intending c5. } 9.h5 fxe4 { After 9...O-O 10.hxg6 hxg6 11.Nf3!? Black's king is in grave danger. } 10.Nxe4! { A stronger alternative to 10. hxg6. Black struggles here: } 10...Nf5 { 10...Bf5 11.h6! is one of the benefits of keeping the tension. } 11.Bg5 Qd7 12.Nb5! ) ( { • } 1...g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.e4 d6 4.Nc3 Nc6 { is another option. } 5.d5 Nd4 { Black hopes to install and retain a strong knight on d4, supported by ...e5 or ...c5. It does not quite work, though: } 6.Be3 c5 { 6...e5 7.Nge2 is not any better for Black. } 7.Nge2 Qb6 { The only way to keep the knight on d4. } 8.Na4! Qa5+ 9.Bd2 Qa6 10.Nxd4 Bxd4 { 10...cxd4 allows 11.c5 ideas, but 11.b4 is also strong. } 11.Nc3 { White is clearly better. } ) ( { • } 1...g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.e4 d6 4.Nc3 e5 5.dxe5 { I tried this endgame a few times quite successfully, but Black should be fine here when Black plays through ... f6: } 5...dxe5 6.Qxd8+ Kxd8 7.Nf3 f6! ) ( { • } 1...g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.e4 d6 4.Nc3 e5 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.dxe5 { Going for the endgame now is a much better version than immediate 5. dxe5. Black does not get comfortable with...f6 setup. } 6...Nxe5 { 6...dxe5 is a much better endgame for White. 7.Qxd8+ Kxd8 8.Bg5+ f6 9.O-O-O+ } 7.Nxe5 Bxe5 8.Be2 Nf6 9.O-O O-O 10.Bg5 $14 ) ( { • } 1...g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.e4 d6 4.Nc3 e5 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.dxe5 { is also good now, as the resulting endgame is worse for Black. } 6...dxe5 7.Qxd8+ Kxd8 8.Ng5 Nh6 9.Be2!? { I analyze this endgame quite extensively and I believe White is better. } ) ( { • } 1...g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.e4 Nc6 { is similar to other lines, but this order is rarer. I recommend development with } 4.Nf3 { when the immediate } 4...e5 { would allow us to transpose and } { 4...d6 5.d5! grants us a space advantage: 5...Ne5 6.Nxe5 Bxe5 and the simplest is 7.Bd3 intending to complete our development with O-O, Nc3, Bg5, etc. } ) ( { • } 1...g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.e4 e6!? { Black can play without ...d6; this looks bizarre, but Black wants to take advantage of our move order, as 3.Nc3 works best against this, but it takes us out of our repertoire. } 4.Nc3 Ne7 5.Nf3 d5 { and here, instead of closing the center, } 6.Bd3!? { is a very important move, focusing on normal development. } ) 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 Bg7 
4. e4 d6 { The usual move order in the King's Indian. } ( { • } 4...O-O { Black may try this move order too. } 5.Be2 { Of course, ...d6 would transpose. But there are other options for Black, too. } 5...c6 { with the idea ...d5 is one of them. } 6.Be3 d5 7.cxd5 cxd5 8.e5 Ne4 9.h4! { This would be my recommendation. Opening the h-file makes a lot of sense. } ) ( { • } 4...O-O 5.Be2 c5 6.d5 e6 { is another option. Here, White can exploit lack of ...d6: } 7.e5! Ne8 8.Nf3 d6 9.Bg5! Qc7 10.h4! { with strong attack. } ) 
5. Be2 O-O 
6. Be3 { A trendy line recently against the King's Indian. Many games have been played there recently. I like this line for its versatility with Benoni, as we can essentially use the same setup no matter the move order. } e5 { The most popular move here. } ( { • } 6...Na6 { a tricky move order which avoids h4 lines (or at least reduces the strength of h4). } 7.Nf3 { I would recommend going for the main line of ...Na6 King's Indian. } 7...e5 8.O-O { Black has many options here. } 8...Qe8 9.dxe5 dxe5 { 9...Ng4 10.Bc1 Nxe5 11.Nd4 Normally White is better in such positions, as is the case here. } 10.h3! { Preventing ...Ng4 and ... Bg4. } 10...b6 { is considered the best move here, preventing c5 ideas and maybe intending ...c5 as well. } 11.Qc2 Nb4 { 11...Bb7 12.a3 with next b4. } 12.Qb1 c5 13.Nd5 { I believe White is better here. } ) ( { • } 6...Na6 7.Nf3 e5 8.O-O Qe7 { is a recent trend. } 9.d5!? { Not the most popular, but I like it the most. } 9...Ng4 10.Bg5! { is the point - with ...Qe8 instead of ... Qe7 White would not have had this tempo move. } 10...f6 11.Bh4 g5 12.Bg3 { followed by Nd2 would be my recommendation. } ) ( { • } 6...Na6 7.Nf3 e5 8.O-O Ng4 9.Bg5 Qe8 { is similar to 8... Qe8, but here I would recommend something fresh. } 10.Rc1!? { this move is incredibly strong, as the analysis shows, and it could be a refutation of this line. } 10...exd4 11.Nxd4 Nxh2 { is the main continuation. White can claim a big advantage after: } 12.Re1 Ng4 13.Bxg4 Bxg4 14.Qxg4 Bxd4 15.e5 $16 { Or 12.Kxh2 Qe5+ 13.f4 Qxd4 14.Qe1 $16 }) ( { • } 6...Na6 7.Nf3 e5 8.O-O exd4 9.Nxd4 Re8 10.f3 { White stabilizes the center and should be better. } ) ( { • } 6...Na6 7.Nf3 e5 8.O-O h6 { this move prevents Bg5 tempo in some lines. } 9.dxe5! Ng4 10.Bd2 dxe5 { 10...Nxe5 11.Nd4 $14 } 11.Qc2 { with central and queenside play. } ) ( { • } 6...Na6 7.Nf3 e5 8.O-O c6 { A flexible setup for Black. White should go here for space advantage. } 9.d5 Ng4 10.Bg5 f6 11.Bh4 c5 12.Ne1 { White has a typical plan of playing on the queenside via a3-b4. } 12...Nh6 { 12...h5 I found that this move is generally weakening in similar positions. White now can play through g4 at some point, thanks to the h5 pawn being a hook. 13.Bd3!? I analyze this move deeply, preparing g4 at some point in the future. } 13.Rb1 { preparing a3 and b4. It is important not to rush with Nc2 and Nd3, as for now, it is not entirely clear where the knight should go. In general, White is slightly better thanks to more space. } ) ( { • } 6...Nc6 { A provocative line that invites White to build a huge center, planning to challenge it later. } 7.d5 Ne5 { Other moves like 7... Nb8 or 7... Nb4 are worse. } 8.f4 Neg4 9.Bd2 Nh6 { Getting the knight out of the way immediately and preparing ...c6 and ... e6. I analyze the alternatives too, but they are just bad. } 10.Nf3 { I recommend this. } 10...c6 { 10...e6 is an alternative. Here I suggest 11.dxe6 fxe6 12.Ng5 Nf7 13.h4! } 11.a4! { preventing ...b5. } 11...e6! { The best move. } { 11...cxd5 12.cxd5 e6 13.dxe6 Bxe6 14.O-O is another option that I analyze quite extensively. Black does not equalize here, in my opinion. Whenever ...d5 is played, White usually responds with e5. } 12.dxe6 Bxe6 13.O-O Nd7 14.Ng5 a5 { White has two options here. } 15.g4!? { extremely entertaining idea that puts lots of pressure on Black. With perfect play, Black may equalize here eventually, but it is really testing. } { 15.Nxe6 fxe6 16.Kh1 is more positional and also quite challenging. }) ( { • } 6...Nbd7 7.Nf3 e5 8.O-O { Transposing to ...Nbd7 King's Indian. Black has many options now. } 8...exd4 { Probably the best try to play for Black is to open the center. } 9.Nxd4 Re8 10.Qc2 { I like this setup here. } 10...c6 11.Rad1 Qe7 12.f3 a6 { preparing either ...Ne5-b5 or ...c5. } 13.Bf2 Ne5 14.Qc1!? { I think that this move gives White an advantage. } ) ( { • } 6...Nbd7 7.Nf3 e5 8.O-O c6 { is usually met by } 9.d5 { and after } 9...c5 { I would recommend fresh } 10.Kh1!? { preparing g4 at some point, especially in case of ...Ne8. } 10...Ne8 11.g4 { preventing ...f5, which would leave the e6-square chronically weak. } ) ( { • } 6...c6 7.Nf3 e5 8.d5 Ng4 9.Bg5 f6 10.Bh4 { as the general rule of thumb, this is an improved version for White of similar lines with ...Na6 and O-O included. White's king may always go to queenside now, leaving Black without an option of A potential kingside attack. } 10...c5 11.Nd2 ) ( { • } 6...c6 7.Nf3 e5 8.d5 Na6 9.Nd2 { is an ideal setup for White. Potentially there will be g4-h4 ideas while the king feels comfortable in the center (but O-O-O also should be kept in mind). Finally, playing without g4 and O-O instead is also an option, depending, of course, on what Black is doing. } ) ( { • } 6...c5 7.d5 { would transpose sooner or later to Benoni. } 7...e6 8.Nf3 exd5 9.cxd5 { and we are at Benoni. } ) 
7. d5 Na6 
8. h4 Nc5 ( { • } 8...h5 9.f3 { helps White a lot. White will want to prepare g4 idea at some point in the future, while Nh3-Nf2 (or Ng5) are among the main setups for White. } ) ( { • } 8...c6 9.g4! { is really problematic for Black too. } ) 
9. Qc2 c6 
10. h5 ( 10.Bxc5 { is a potential alternative, which I acknowledge could also be really challenging for Black, so I cover it as an alternative. [/course/131435/64] Now } 10...dxc5 11.h5 { leaves Black stuck with a bad bishop. } ) cxd5 
11. cxd5 Qa5! 
12. h6! Bh8 
13. f3 {[%csl Gh6,Rg8]} { The main position. } Nh5 {[%cal Gh5g3,Gh5f4][%csl Rf4,Rg3]} { I believe Black should look for immediate counterplay. } ( 13...Bd7 { was played by Grischuk against Nakamura, and here White has a comfortable advantage. } 14.Rb1! Na4 { 14...Nxd5!? is interesting but it does not work: 15.exd5 Bf5 16.Qd1 Bxb1 17.Qxb1 e4 18.Kf2 $16 } 15.Qd2! Nxc3 16.bxc3 Qc7 17.g4 $16 { with idea Nh3-Nf2 is better for White, as Nakamura proved. } ) 
14. a3 Qd8 ( 14...Ng3 { a bit inaccurate move order. White gets an additional resource on move 18. } 15.b4 Qd8 16.Rh2 Nxe2 17.Ngxe2 Na6 { here, apart from 18. g4 which just transposes to the main line, White may try } 18.Nb5!? { trying to exploit c7-square and also target a7-pawn in some lines. } ) 
15. b4 Na6 ( 15...Nd7?! 16.Nb5! { targeting c7 and d6. } ) 
16. g4 Ng3 
17. Rh2 Nxe2 
18. Ngxe2 Bd7 { Probably the main position in this line. } 
19. Qd3!? { would be my recommendation. White will play Kd2 next, keeping the king in the center. Thanks to the space advantage, White has a long-term edge. The idea is to prevent any counterplay and ideally go for 'a squeeze'. } *

