[White "37) King's Indian: Black plays without ...d6"]
[Black "1...g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 e6 - The problem with 6.e5"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23332415"]
[ECO "A40"]

1. d4 g6 
2. c4 Bg7 
3. e4 ( { We don't begin with } 3.Nf3 { as then Black can transpose to either KID or Grunfeld, and in either way, I recommend playing without Nf3 in these openings. } ) e6!? {[%cal Gd7d5]} { This idea looks bizarre at first: Black plays weird moves in the opening that perhaps only those who are new to chess may play. But in reality - this is quite a legit line with the idea of hitting the center with ...d5.

The first time I saw it in a game Onischuk-Ipatov (2018), I thought that... it was some sort of joke :) But then I realized things are not necessarily that easy. Generally, one of the best ways to deal with this line is unavailable to White right now, and that is h4, provoking ...h6, and then Bf4-Qd2, all before e4 is played. Then, playing with ...d5 at best leads to awkward QGD positions with ...Bg7 and ...Ne7, while Bf4 and Qd2 hit the h6-pawn, preventing Black from castling (for more details, see the informational line [/variation/23332414] after 3.Nc3).

Here, we have already played e4, so there is no such option, but White is better anyway, as my analysis shows. } 
4. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} Ne7 { Renewing the idea, and unfortunately, there is no good way to stop it, as White does not want to play d5 this early. } 
5. Nf3 d5 { Black got his idea to work, but with correct play, White retains a clear advantage. } 
6. e5 { This seems like the most obvious move, but this is exactly what Black hopes for. } c5! ( { After this, Black gets a decent game. } 6...Nbc6?! { is too extravagant, perhaps. It was tried in the aforementioned game Onischuk-Ipatov (2018), but it is less logical. } ) 
7. dxc5 O-O 
8. Be2 Nd7 
9. Bf4 Nxc5 
10. O-O dxc4 
11. Bxc4 a6 { With a complicated position as in Gajewski-Heberla (2020). } 
*

