4. Nc3 Ne7 { Renewing the idea, and unfortunately, there is no good way to stop it, as White does not want to play d5 this early. } 
5. Nf3 d5 { Black got his idea to work, but with correct play, White retains a clear advantage. } 
6. Bd3!? { A very important move. White should NOT close the center with e5 as it may run into ...c5 ideas. Instead, White focuses on normal development, not minding either ...dxc4 or ...dxe4. } dxe4 
7. Bxe4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Generally, this trade executed prematurely helps White. } O-O ( { After } 7...Nbc6 8.Be3 { there is hardly anything better than } 8...O-O { with a transposition. } ) 
8. O-O Nd7 { This is an option for Black, preparing either ...c5 or ...Nf6. But it hardly equalizes... } 
9. Qe2 Nf6 ( 9...c5? { is bad due to } 10.dxc5! Nxc5 11.Rd1 Qa5 12.Bd2 $16 { . } ) 
10. Bf4!? ( { Surprisingly, the engine likes it the most. } 10.Bc2 $16 { is more human, and it also offers an advantage. } ) Nxe4 
11. Qxe4 Nf5 
12. Rad1 Nd6 
13. Qe2 $16  { A huge lead in development, more active pieces, and a space advantage all translate to White's big edge. } *

