8. d5 Ng4 ( { If now } 8...cxd5 9.cxd5 Ne8 10.Nd2 f5 11.Nc4 f4 12.Bc1 $16 { , as White hasn't castle yet, Black has no attack on the kingside. } ) 
9. Bg5 f6 
10. Bh4 { Here, Black has many options, but in my understanding, they all lead to very similar positions. For this reason, I will not dive too much into the analysis of this line but attempt to present the main ideas. } c5 { It is quite common for Black to close the center. Objectively, White is better in these positions, of course, but it may not be easy to play if one doesn't know or understand the ideas. } 
11. Nd2! Nh6 
12. f3 { It is important for White not to castle kingside. Usually, Black seeks counterplay with ...f5 at some point, hoping to create a kingside attack. If White goes to the queenside or simply keeps the king in the center, Black pretty much has no targets. } Nf7 
13. Qc2 Bh6 
14. Bf2 { Preventing ...Be3. White has a simple plan here: expand on the kingside, keep the king in the center or the queenside and prevent any counterplay. Also, if the king remains in the center, it is worth noting that we could play a3-b4. It is difficult to analyze this position move by move due to its closed nature. However, I decided to go on a bit deeper to understand possible plans and setups. } Na6 { The problem with Black's position is that it is very cramped, and there are no active plans. Normally, Black would want to play ...f5, but it is simply not good in these positions. And if not that, then what else? Black must sit still while White, in the meantime, develops various ideas. } 
15. a3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bd7 
16. h4! {[%cal Gh4h5]} { By playing h4-h5, White does not necessarily want to launch a kingside attack. Instead, we want to gain more space and restrict Black's possibilities. } Qe7 
17. h5 Kg7 
18. Bd3!? ( { Stopping ...f5 and making space for the king on e2, where it would feel pretty safe. } 18.O-O-O { is not bad either, but I would rather keep the option of playing b4 in the future. After O-O-O, that may be pretty hard to do. } ) Nc7 
19. Ke2 b6 { Black lacks active counterplay, but there is no way to develop an attack on the kingside. For this reason, White should look for queenside play. } 
20. b4! {[%cal Ga1b1]} -- ( { It's time to play this move! White is, of course, much better. Black needs to be always careful, but with good maneuvering play, White should be able to put a lot of pressure. Here are some sample continuations: } 20...Rab8 21.Rab1 Rh8 { Black has no active plan. } 22.Rb2!? { with the idea of Qb1 with pressure on the b-file. At some point, White will want to play bxc5 and then either control the b-file (if ...bxc5) or play a4-a5 (if ...dxc5). After } 22...Rbg8 23.Qb1 Rf8 24.bxc5 bxc5 25.Bc2+- { or @@StartFEN@@5r1r/p1nbqnkp/1p1p1ppb/2PPp2P/2P1P3/P1NB1P2/1R1NKBP1/1Q5R b - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@ 24...dxc5 25.a4 Nd6 26.a5+- eventually, White breaks through. } )
