9. Qc2 {[%csl Ge4]} { Protecting the e4-pawn. } c6 ( { White has some choice here. } 9...exd4 10.Nxd4 { would sooner or later transpose to 8...exd4. [/variation/21808923/#/8/b] } ) 
10. Rad1 ( { Closing the center with } 10.d5!? { makes sense too. } 10...c5 11.Kh1?! $16 { is similar to 8...c6 9.d5 c5. [/variation/21808919/#/9/b] @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp1nqpbp/2pp1np1/3Pp3/2P1P3/2N1BN2/PPQ1BPPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10...Ng4 11.Bg5 f6 12.Bd2 Nh6 13.b4 $16 is a typical King's Indian position where White is better thanks to the space advantage. } ) h6 {[%cal Gf6g4]} { The idea of this move is to prepare ...Ng4 that way White does not have Bg5 resource with a tempo. But the drawback is that with the pawn on h6, Black has less control over the g6-square. This can be a factor in positions where White closes the center and plays d5. } ( 10...exd4 11.Nxd4 { should transpose, sooner or later, to the mainline. } ) ( 10...Ng4 11.Bg5 Bf6 { 11...f6 12.Bc1 $16 } 12.Bxf6 Ngxf6 13.Rfe1 $16 { White is much better. } ) 
11. d5! {[%mdl 32768]} c5 
12. g3! { A strong move, potentially preparing Nh4 one day to prevent Black from playing ...f5. However, this is not the only idea, as we will see shortly. } Nh7 
13. Qc1!? ( { A useful move, tickling the h6-pawn and provoking to go to ...h5.

Gawain Jones in his Chessable course analyzes } 13.Qd2 { only (apart from the standard } ) ( 13.Nh4 { ) but 13.Qc1 feels a bit better to me as it gives the room for the bishop to go back to d2 if needed. } ) h5 ( 13...g5? { is of course terrible for Black - all the light squares are horribly weak. } 14.h4 g4 15.Nh2 h5 16.f3+- ) 
14. Kg2! {[%cal Gh2h3][%csl Rg4,Rh3]} { A very strong idea for White, improving on Nh4 ideas analyzed deeply by Gawain in similar positions.

The idea of this move is to prevent Black from ...Ndf6 and ...Bh3 and play h3, covering the h3 and g4 squares. With full prophylaxis against Black's active play, it is a difficult position for Black. And White has room for improvement thanks to the space advantage, as we will see in the main line. } Ndf6 ( 14...f5 { runs into } 15.Nh4+- { and the softness of the g6-pawn is telling. } ) 
15. h3! {[%cal Gf1h1]} { The point - now Black is in a way stuck. There is no active plan. And White - will play for surprising Rh1, Rdg1, Rh2, Kh1 and slowly prepare the g4 breakthrough with an attack on the kingside! In case Black wants to open the queenside, White should make sure to close it. } Bd7 
16. Rh1 a6 
17. a4! { Not allowing any pawn breaks. } b6 
18. Rdg1 $16  {[%cal Gh1h2,Gg2h1]} { White slowly but surely executes his plan. At some point, some pawn break like g4 will happen on the kingside which will leave Black in a pretty bad shape. The lack of counterplay is the biggest issue for Black here. } *

