1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 Bg7 
4. e4 d6 
5. Be2 O-O 
6. Be3 Nbd7 ( { Here, I discuss lines connected with the development of Black's knight to d7. If Black begins with } 6...e5 7.d5 Nbd7 { White does not have to play Nf3. Instead, we can play } 8.h4 { , and there is pretty much nothing better than } 8...Nc5 { , transposing to this line. [/variation/21833062/#/8/b] } ) 
7. Nf3 e5 ( { Note } 7...c5!? 8.d5 { is, of course, a great position for White because the moves ...Nbd7 and ...c5 don't usually go well together. } ) 
8. O-O { With this move, White transposes to a main KID system usually reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP2BPPP/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 2 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Nf3 e5 7.O-O Nbd7 , which is considered as a somewhat inferior line than 6...Nc6 or 6...Na6. Now, White could play 8.d5 too, but I think there is no reason to avoid this line. Now, Black has a vast number of options. } c6 
9. d5! { Generally, White's d5 is a reaction to Black's ...c6, seizing space and provoking Black into closing the center with ...c5. Other potential ideas include dxc6 targeting the d6-pawn. Black can play either ...cxd5 or ...c5. Delaying the decision is also possible, but sooner or later, Black has to define the center. } c5 
10. Kh1!? { A rare move in this particular position, but the idea is pretty common - playing g4 at some point, especially if the knight retreats to e8. } ( 10.Ne1 { is the main move here and also good. It contains the same idea of g4, but I like the text more. After } 10...Ne8 11.g4 f5 12.exf5 gxf5 13.gxf5 Ndf6 { White is, of course, better, but the knight is slightly misplaced on e1, and White would rather have Kh1 already on the board. } ) Kh8 {[%cal Gf6g8,Gf7f5,Gg7h6]} { Perhaps Black should replicate White's play. The idea could be ...Ng8 and prepare ...f5 or maybe ...Bh6. } 
11. Bg5!? {[%mdl 32768]} { A useful move, typical in such structures. White tries to provoke ...h6 weakening the kingside. There is not much theory, so let's just see what can happen. } Qe8 
12. a4!? { Expanding on the queenside as ...Ng8 is not working yet. If ...a5, the b5-square will be chronically weak. } a6 ( 12...Ng8? 13.Nb5+- { . } ) 
13. a5 Ng8 
14. Na4 $16  {[%cal Gb2b4]} { With the idea of b4. } *

