10. Qc2 ( { I like this approach for White as, in some lines, if Black delays ...exd4, White plays Qc2 anyway. Therefore, this keeps the repertoire unified. However, } 10.f3 { is also completely fine. White's plan is pretty straightforward: bring the pieces to the center, secure the e4-pawn, prevent any counterplay by Black, and enjoy some space advantage. } ) c6 ( { I think this is the right setup for Black, who should aim at a flexible piece configuration. } 10...Nc5 11.f3 { leads to a typical position in the King's Indian where White enjoys more space and a strong center thanks to the c4- and e4-pawns. White is much better, as illustrated by } 11...Nh5 12.Rad1 Ne6 13.Nxe6 Bxe6 14.c5 $16 { or @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/ppp2pbp/3p1np1/2n5/2PNP3/2N1BP2/PPQ1B1PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ 11...a5 12.Rad1 Bd7 13.Ndb5 $16 . } ) ( { Black can begin with } 10...Qe7 11.f3 c6 { , but after } 12.Rad1 { , we reach a transposition to the main line. } ) 
11. Rad1 Qe7 
12. f3 { This is the main position. } a6 { I consider this the best move for Black. There are two main ideas connected to this pawn move: preparing a future ...b5 (say, ...Ne5 and ...b5) or ...c5!? as the a6-pawn controls the b5-square. } 
13. Bf2 {[%mdl 32768]} Ne5 
14. Qc1 $146  { An excellent move which is technically a novelty. The idea is pure prophylaxis: the queen makes room for the knight in case of ...c5. If Black goes ...b5, the queen not only puts some pressure on the c-file but also does not run under a tempo with ...Nc4. } ( { To illustrate this point, let's say } 14.Qd2 b5 15.cxb5 axb5 { and now ...Nc4 will always attack the queen, and perhaps Bxc4 would be necessary. For this reason, c1 is a better square for the queen. } 16.a3 Qb7 17.h3 Nc4 { is a possible continuation. } ) ( 14.a4?! { stopping ...b5 has some merit, but Black can play } 14...c5! { and there is no Nc2-Ne3 maneuver. } 15.Nb3 Be6 16.Nd2 Nc6 $13 { is unclear. } ) Qc7 { If Black does not play ...b5, White can stop it. } 
15. a4!? {[%cal Rb7b5]} { Depriving Black of any counterplay. } c5 
16. Nc2 Be6 
17. Ne3 $16  {[%cal Rb7b5][%csl Rd5]} { And this is much better for White. } *

