[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "41) King's Indian: Be2-Be3 with 6...Na6"]
[Black "8...c6 #1"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21811860"]
[ECO "E73"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 Bg7 
4. e4 d6 
5. Be2 O-O 
6. Be3 Na6 ( { A tricky move order. Black switches the order of ...Na6 and ...e5. Surprisingly, that does not allow us to play the same plan as after } 6...e5 7.d5 Na6 { , where I suggest } 8.h4 { . } ) 
7. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { White should transpose to the regular main line of the ...Na6 variation in the King's Indian. Here, } 7.h4 { is not as great. Black can play } 7...h5 { and, unlike in the scenario including ...e5-d5, Black may hit the center now with ...c5. I don't think this position is really clear: Perhaps the best is } 8.Nf3 { but I find it difficult to believe that h4 helps White... After } { 8.f3 and now not 8...e5? 9.d5 $16 but @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppb1/n2p1np1/7p/2PPP2P/2N1BP2/PP2B1P1/R2QK1NR b KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 8...c5! 9.d5 Nc7 $132 with ideas of ...e6 and/or ...b5 with an unclear game. } ) e5 
8. O-O { In this position, Black has many options. } c6 { This setup is quite flexible - Black keeps his options wide open and can potentially choose to play ...exd4, maybe ...Ng4, and the queen can still go to e8 or e7. And if White pushes d5, Black may consider closing the center with ...c5 at some point, trying to play for the ...f5 break. } 
9. d5!? { Still, I think White should close the center and try to prove the value of space advantage. } Ng4 ( 9...c5? 10.Ne1 $16 { is clearly worse. I analyze something similar in the 6...Nbd7 chapter [/course/131435/53]. White plays g4, Kh1 etc. } ) 
10. Bg5 f6 
11. Bh4 c5 { A typical position in the King's Indian. White has more space, but Black is solid, and there are ideas of playing through ...f5, which are not necessarily easy to react to if one doesn't know how. I have played such positions myself with Black with decent results; generally, they are far from easy to play. White has already castled kingside, which doesn't help - Black's kingside attacks could be potentially dangerous. However, I found interesting ways to handle this position. } 
12. Ne1 {[%cal Ge1c2,Ge1d3]} { The knight will normally go to d3, but we'll wait for Black to show their plans. Sometimes the knight is useful on c2. } h5 { Played in Wojtaszek-Ding (2015), and also by myself in Gallego-Swiercz (2021). The idea is to advance the kingside pawns quickly, but this also weakens Black's kingside, as I discuss in many similar positions. I found a very challenging idea. } 
13. Bd3!? {[%cal Gd1e2,Gf2f3,Rf6f5][%csl Gd3]} { An interesting new setup. The idea is to play Qe2 and then f3. The bishop on d3 will be very well placed as it will act as a sort of prophylaxis against ...f5, as we will shortly see. One of the ideas for White here is to prepare g4!?, exploiting the h5-pawn being a hook. There are no games here, and this idea is very fresh. } Nh6 
14. f3 Nf7 
15. Kh1 { Of course, other moves are possible, but this is always useful. We intend to push g4 and use the g-file. } Bh6 {[%cal Gh6e3]} 
16. Bf2 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge1c2,Gf1g1,Gg2g4]} ( { Just in case, preventing ...Be3. Another option is } 16.Qe2!? $16 { . } ) f5 
17. exf5 { Remember: we never allow ...f4. } gxf5 
18. g3 $16  {[%cal Ge1g2,Gg2h4,Gf1g1,Gg3g4]} ( 18.Rg1!? $16 { is another option. Either way, we'll try to get g4 in, opening up the kingside to launch an attack against the black king. } ) *

