[ECO "E73"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 Bg7 
4. e4 d6 
5. Be2 O-O 
6. Be3 e5 
7. d5 { White should close the center. The benefit of having played Be2 and delaying Nf3 is that White now has additional options of kingside play, namely g4!? but also h4.

Typically, Black wants to play the ...f5 break, which now tougher - not only ...Nh5 is off the table, but very often White plays g4, stopping any ...f5. } Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5][%csl Re4]} { I consider this the most reasonable option for Black. The idea is to put quick pressure on the e4-pawn. } 
8. h4!? { Not the most popular move here overall but it has recently gained some popularity and I think it puts a lot of pressure. } Nc5 {[%csl Re4]} 
9. Qc2 { Protecting the e4-pawn. } c6 { Sooner or later, Black must challenge the center. } 
10. h5 ( { I would recommend this move here. Most notably, it was played in a recent game Nakamura-Grischuk (2022), in the FIDE Grand Prix in Berlin. } 10.Bxc5!? { is an alternative with its own chapter. [/course/131435/64] } ) cxd5 
11. cxd5 Qa5! {[%cal Ga5e1][%csl Re4]} { Black should provoke f3. } 
12. h6! ( { It is useful to include this move to lock the bishop on h8. White can follow up with f3 as well, but not } 12.hxg6? { due to } 12...Ncxe4! $13 { with an unclear game. } ) Bh8 
13. f3 { This is the main position of this line. } Nh5!? {[%cal Gh5f4,Gh5g3,Re2h5][%csl Re2]} { I think this is Black's best response. It makes sense to exploit that the f3-pawn is blocking the e2-bishop and try to jump to g3 or f4. } 
14. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} ( { This strikes me as slightly more accurate than } 14.Rb1 { as White now sometimes has the option of O-O-O. Also, the a3-b4 construction is very solid, and the rook may go to c1. } ) Qd8 
15. b4 Nd7?! {[%csl Rc7]} { Not a good retreat - Black needs to have the c7-square covered. On the other hand, White must be very precise in this complex position to prove an advantage. } 
16. Nb5! {[%cal Gb5c7,Gc2c7][%csl Rc7]} Nf4!? ( { Black should try to create chaos on the board. } 16...Ng3 17.Rh2 f5 18.Nc7+- { is just winning for White. } ) ( 16...Nb6? 17.Qc7! $16 { and with queens off the board, Black is strategically nearly lost. } ) 
17. Rh2! { Now we enter a computeresque type of play, but what to do? - White is on the verge of winning here! } f5 
18. Nc7! { Ignoring the d6-pawn and going for the rook. } Qg5 
19. g4! { Black has no way to break through successfully } fxg4 
20. fxg4 Nf6 
21. Nxa8 { We have nothing to fear on the kingside. } Nxg4 { Another unsuccessful try. } 
22. Bxg4 {[%mdl 32768]} Qxg4 
23. Kd2 { And again, everything is protected. } Ng2 
24. Qd3 -- ( { White should stabilize sooner or later with a winning position, e.g., } 24...Bf6 25.Rxg2 Qxg2+ 26.Ne2 Bg4 27.Nc7 Rc8 28.Rc1+- { . } )
