12. h6! ( { It is useful to include this move to lock the bishop on h8. White can follow up with f3 as well, but not } 12.hxg6? { due to } 12...Ncxe4! $13 { with an unclear game. } ) Bh8 
13. f3 { This is the main position of this line. } Nh5!? {[%cal Gh5f4,Gh5g3,Re2h5][%csl Re2]} { I think this is Black's best response. It makes sense to exploit that the f3-pawn is blocking the e2-bishop and try to jump to g3 or f4. } 
14. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} ( { This strikes me as slightly more accurate than } 14.Rb1 { as White now sometimes has the option of O-O-O. Also, the a3-b4 construction is very solid, and the rook may go to c1. } ) Qd8 
15. b4 Na6 ( 15...Ng3 { transposes to 14...Ng3. [/variation/21833071/#/15/w] } ) 
16. g4 Ng3 
17. Rh2 Nxe2 
18. Ngxe2 Bd7 { I consider this one of this line's most important positions. Right now, White needs to choose a plan, and a couple of them are available. } 
19. Qd3 {[%cal Ge1d2,Gh2h1,Gh1c1]} { I think White should keep the king in the center for now and play on the queenside. In the future, we should bring our rook from h2 by Rhh1-Rhc1. Advancing the queenside pawns is also on White's agenda. Generally, White should not really worry about ...f5 - that would weaken Black's king. I think White is better here. } Nc7 
20. a4! ( { White should begin with this move to prevent Black's potential queenside counterplay. After } 20.Kd2 { Black can play } 20...Rc8!? { intending to regroup the knight to b6, and suddenly it is not so clear, e.g., } 21.Bxa7 Na8!= $13 { or @@StartFEN@@2rq1rkb/ppnb1p1p/3p2pP/3Pp3/1P2P1P1/P1NQBP2/3KN2R/R7 w - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@ 21.a4 Na8 22.a5 a6! , and the knight comes back via b5. 23.b5 Nc7 24.b6 Nb5 $13 . } ) Bf6!? {[%cal Gf6g5]} { The bishop on h8 was really bad, so it makes sense to improve it or trade it with ...Bg5. } 
21. Kd2 { Black may try to delay ...Bg5, but not forever. } Bg5 { Sooner or later, this move should be played anyway. } 
22. Bxg5 ( { I would recommend entering the endgame here. I spent lots of time analyzing } 22.Rhh1 { delaying the bishop trade, but I could not find anything great after } 22...Rc8 23.Bxg5 Qxg5+ 24.Qe3 Qf6! { . Black seems to have some counterplay connected with either ...Na6-...Rc4 or ...Na8-...Nb6 ideas. For example, } 25.b5 Na8! 26.Qxa7 Qxf3 27.g5 f5! 28.gxf6 Qxf6 29.Rhf1 Qg5+ 30.Qe3 Qxe3+ 31.Kxe3 Rxf1 32.Rxf1 Nb6= { and Black should be fine in this endgame. Instead, @@StartFEN@@2r2rk1/ppnb1p1p/3p2pP/3Pp1q1/PP2P1P1/2N1QP2/3KN3/R6R b - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@ 24...Qxe3+?! 25.Kxe3 $14 is a better version of a queen trade for White as here there is no ...Rfc8 and ...Kf8. } ) ( { Still, the best moves for Black seem to be quite difficult to find, so } 22.Rhh1 { could still be playable, of course. } ) Qxg5+ 
23. Qe3 Qxe3+ { Black should enter the endgame. } 
24. Kxe3 Rfc8! {[%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e7]} ( { Followed by ...Kf8 and ...Ke7. } 24...b5? 25.axb5 Bxb5 26.f4+- { or @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/p1nb1p1p/3p2pP/1P1Pp3/1P2P1P1/2N1KP2/4N2R/R7 b - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@ 25...Nxb5 26.Nxb5 Bxb5 27.Nc3+- are worse. } ) 
25. b5 Kf8 
26. Rf2!? {[%cal Gg4g5,Gf3f4]} { I think Black is under some pressure in this endgame. Lack of space can be annoying in the long run. White's plan is to play at some point g5 and f4. } a6 ( 26...Ne8 { simply allows } 27.Kd3 Rc5 28.Nc1 Rac8 29.Rc2 { consolidating. } ) 
27. b6 {[%mdl 32768]} Ne8 
28. Kd3! {[%csl Rc4]} { Preventing ...Rc4. } Rc5 ( 28...Nf6 29.g5 Nh5 { and now } 30.f4 { followed by Raf1 looks pretty annoying for Black. } ) 
29. Nd1! {[%cal Gd1e3]} { The knight will be great on e3. } Rac8 
30. Ne3 Ke7 
31. Rff1 Ra5 ( 31...Kf6? 32.f4! $16 { . } ) 
32. Nc3 Rac5 
33. Ra3 Kf6 
34. Rc1 Kg5 
35. Rh1 $14  {[%cal Gc3d1,Gd1b2,Ge3c4]} -- ( { There is lots of maneuvering play, but at the end of the day, White is pushing for a win, and Black needs to be careful. At some point, it may be worth it to sac the h6-pawn to reroute the knight to a5 somehow (perhaps Ncd1-Nb2 and then Nec4). For example, } 35...Ra5 36.Kd2 Nf6 37.Rha1 Kxh6 38.Ncd1 Kg5 39.Nb2 Ne8 40.Nec4 Rac5 41.Rc3 { with the idea of Rac1 and Nd3. White is making some progress, even though Black should be able to hold with perfect play. } )
