[White "44) King's Indian - Alternative 10.Bxc5!? dxc5 11.h5"]
[Black "11...Bd7 #1"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21826865"]
[ECO "E73"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 g6 
3. Nc3 Bg7 
4. e4 d6 
5. Be2 O-O 
6. Be3 e5 
7. d5 Na6 
8. h4 Nc5 
9. Qc2 c6 
10. Bxc5!? {[%mdl 32768]} { An alternative approach to our main line 10.h5. [/course/131435/68] The idea is to force a change in the pawn structure before Black manages to play ...Qa5, and start to play on the light squares, trying to exploit Black's bad dark-squared bishop. It is very plausible, and engines generally like it, but there are certain drawbacks too. If Black's g7-bishop becomes active one day, things may get really unpleasant for White.

Additionally, despite the nice grip over the light squares, it may not be easy to suggest an actual plan, especially if Black does not change the pawn structure in the center. Still, the position is definitely playable and relatively unexplored, so definitely worth trying. } dxc5 
11. h5 Bd7?! ( { This move allows h6, forcing the bishop to go back to h8. } 11...Qe7 { was played in Niemann-Kotronias (2021). Similarly to the text, White should lock up the bishop. Niemann played } 12.O-O-O { and won the game, but for some reason, my database does not have the notation of the entire game. Instead, } { 12.h6 Bh8 13.Nf3 with a similar position (and a likely transposition) to 11...Bd7. } ) 
12. h6! { White should go for it. } Bh8 {[%csl Rh8]} 
13. Nf3 Qe7 ( 13...Ne8 14.Qd2 $16 { . } ) 
14. Qd2!? {[%cal Gd2e3,Gd5d6][%csl Rc5]} { I think this position is very uncomfortable for Black. It is difficult to analyze it, as both sides have so many moves available, so it is more useful to talk about it in terms of ideas. White's last move aims at Qe3 to potentially target the c5-pawn at some point, but also supports the h6-pawn and, in some instances, prepares d6!? } Rfd8?! {[%cal Ga8b8,Ga7a6,Gb7b5]} { With this move, Black keeps the other rook on a8 to help with some queenside play unlikely to come true. } 
15. a4!? {[%cal Ga4a5]} { Not the only move, but I like the idea of preventing ...b5. } a5 ( 15...Ne8 16.a5 { is also good for White. For example, } 16...Nd6 17.Qe3 b6 18.O-O $16 { with some annoying pressure on the queenside. } ) 
16. O-O-O!? {[%cal Rb7b5][%csl Ya4,Ya5,Gc1]} { With the inclusion of a4-...a5, White's king will be safe on the queenside. } Qd6 ( 16...cxd5?! 17.cxd5 { clearly helps White, who controls all the important light squares. } ) 
17. Kb1 $16  {[%csl Rh8,Gb1]} { With a stable advantage. Of course, the position is playable for Black, but in the long run, our grip on the light squares will pay off.

One possible plan is to increase the pressure on c5 to provoke ...b6. Then, we can take on c6 and exploit the d5-square. } *

