[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "45) The Benoni Defense: Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21827606"]
[ECO "A65"]

1. d4 Nf6 ( { • } 1...e6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 exd5 4.cxd5 d6 5.Nc3 g6 { Playing without ...Nf6 is also possible but not great either. } 6.e4 Bg7 7.Be2 { intending to transpose back to the main line. } 7...Ne7 { Black plays this move to play through .. .f5. } 8.Bf4!? { a typical idea in Benoni - pressuring the d6-pawn. } 8...O-O 9.Qd2! { anticipating ...f5, as now Bf4 will be defended. Black is in trouble. } ) ( { • } 1...g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.e4 c5 4.d5 d6 5.Be2!? e6 6.Nc3 Ne7 { In this way Black not only delays ...exd5, but also develops the knight to e7, instead of f6. } 7.Bf4 { Attempting to achieve the same setup as with ...exd5 included. } 7...O-O 8.Qd2 e5 9.Bh6!? { with intention of pushing pawns on the kingside. } ) 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 e6 ( { • } 3...g6 { Black may delay ...exd5 and this is what I look at in this move order. } 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 d6 6.Be2 O-O 7.Be3 e6 8.Nf3 Re8 { 8...Na6 9.O-O Nc7?! allows 10.e5! with bid advantage for White. } 9.Nd2 { generally this is what White wants to achieve in Be2-Be3 line. The Nd2 defends the center and in the event of trades on d5, the c4-square will be vacated. } 9...Na6 10.O-O Nc7 11.a4 { Preventing ...b5 in any case. It also weakens the b4-square but it is not that relevant. White wants to play f4 at some point. To prepare it, White may play Bg5 and f4, or Ra3 and f4. The details are in the specific analysis. } ) ( { • } 3...e5 { The Old Benoni (or Czech Benoni) allows White to build a very strong center. } 4.Nc3 d6 5.e4 { Black may try to develop either through ...g6 or ...Be7. } 5...g6 { 5...Be7 6.Be2 O-O now g4 is also possible, but with ...Be7 it is not that good as Black may try to remove the knight from f6 and play ...Bg5, fighting for the dark squares. Therefore, White should play 7.Nf3 generally, White should not hurry with castling kingside. } 6.Be2 Bg7 7.g4!? { As my analysis shows, this is very strong. Black does not have active play. } ) ( { • } 3...a6 4.a4 { The best reaction. Black cannot play through ...b5 anymore. The game should transpose to Benoni anyway, however Black's resources will be reduced, as there will be no ...b5 pawn sac in some lines or ...Na6 ideas. } ) 
4. Nc3 exd5 
5. cxd5 d6 { The Benoni is a very fighting, yet strategically risky setup for Black. In order to create an unbalanced position Black concedes control over the center and attempts to create counterplay by either challenging it (ideas of ...Re8, maybe ...f5 sometimes) or trying to play ...b5.

There are many systems available for White. There is a very sharp system connected with quick e4-f4 and Bb5+, there is more classical e4-Nf3-Nd2, there are also systems with g3, e4-Nge2-Ng3 or even Nf3-Bf4. In this course I decided to keep things rather simple and suggest a system that can be achieved from the King's Indian move order. This simplifies the repertoire and makes it very flexible, regardless of the move orders and other subtleties. } 
6. e4 g6 
7. Be2 Bg7 
