[ECO "A40"]

1. d4 { There are many move orders that Black can use to achieve a Benoni setup without ...Nf6. Let me present two of them. } g6 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 {[%mdl 32768]} Bg7 
4. e4 d6 { From this move order I will illustrate what to do when Black delays ...exd5, unlike in the other move order where Black plays ...exd5 early. This is perhaps better way of playing this line as White does not get here a comfortable setup with Bf4 that pressures d6-pawn, as shown above. } 
5. Be2!? { I think that this move order is the most flexible here. } e6 
6. Nc3 Ne7 ( { This move order happened in my game against GM Vitaliy Bernadskiy. } 6...exd5 7.cxd5 { is analyzed in another move order. } ) 
7. Bf4!? { Just like with ... exd5-cxd5 included, I would suggest this move. There is a threat of dxe6. This idea (Bf4) is not as strong as earlier as Black has here additional option of closing the center with ...e5 as the bishop goes under tempo, but closing the center generally helps White. } O-O! ( { Black should give away the pawn and seek compensation for it. } 7...e5?! 8.Bd2 { helps White. } 8...f5 9.h4 $16 ) 
8. Qd2!? { And White should not accept it! Instead, White tries to get the same thing as in the other line with trades on } { d5 included. White can also grab the d6-pawn now, but Black would have a decent compensation after 8.dxe6 Bxe6 9.Qxd6 Nbc6 $13 } e5 ( { After } 8...f5 { White can win the pawn again with } 9.dxe6 { , or go for more positional } { 9.Bg5!? $16 } ) 
9. Bh6 f5 
10. g4! { An important move - trying to seize control over the light squares or force closing of the kingside. } f4 
11. Bxg7 Kxg7 
12. g5 $16  -- ( { This is also bad for Black, e.g. } 12...Ng8 13.h4 h6 14.gxh6+ Nxh6 15.Nf3 $16 )
*

