1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 e6 
4. Nc3 exd5 
5. cxd5 d6 { The Benoni is a very fighting, yet strategically risky setup for Black. In order to create an unbalanced position Black concedes control over the center and attempts to create counterplay by either challenging it (ideas of ...Re8, maybe ...f5 sometimes) or trying to play ...b5.

There are many systems available for White. There is a very sharp system connected with quick e4-f4 and Bb5+, there is more classical e4-Nf3-Nd2, there are also systems with g3, e4-Nge2-Ng3 or even Nf3-Bf4. In this course I decided to keep things rather simple and suggest a system that can be achieved from the King's Indian move order. This simplifies the repertoire and makes it very flexible, regardless of the move orders and other subtleties. } 
6. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} g6 
7. Be2 ( { I would recommend starting with this move to avoid ...a6-Bg4 line. } 7.Nf3 a6 8.a4 Bg4 { is quite a decent option for Black. } ) Bg7 
8. Nf3 Bg4 ( { Right now, the main move, of course, is } 8...O-O { . Then we play } 9.Be3 { and we transpose to a position that can be achieved from the KID move order. The only way to deviate from a regular Benoni/KID is to play 8... a6. } ) ( { This is another possibility, an alternative to } 8...a6 { , but it should nonetheless transpose to the main line. } ) 
9. Bf4! ( { GM Eliade analyzes } 9.Nd2 { in his course and there is no transposition. However, } ) ( 9.Bf4 { instead solves this problem! } )Bxf3 { 9...a6?! 10.Qa4+! transposes here. [/variation/21843213/#/10/w] }{ 9...O-O 10.O-O a6 11.a4 Preventing ...Nbd7 and ...Qe7. } { Black can prevent White from playing the Nd2 idea by capturing the knight right away, but it has its own drawbacks. } 
10. Bxf3 O-O 
11. O-O { Here, White is not obliged to play with a4 and it is a much improved version of the position with pawns on a4 and a6, as the following analysis shows: } Ne8 { Perhaps Black needs to play this passive move with ...Nd7 next. But it is far from optimal, compared to the ideal setup with ...Qe7-...Nbd7, keeping the knight on f6. } ( 11...Qe7? 12.e5! { is stronger now than with pawns on a4 and a6, as in case of a future Bxb7 the a8-rook is trapped! For example, } 12...dxe5 13.d6 Qd7 14.Bg5! $16 { or @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/pp2qpbp/3P1np1/2p1p3/5B2/2N2B2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@ 13...Qe6? 14.Bxb7+- . } ) ( { After } 11...a6 12.e5! { White manages to break through in the center right away without needing to play a4. } 12...dxe5 13.Bxe5 Nbd7 14.Bg3 $16 { The d5-pawn is a strong passed pawn, also well supported by the bishop pair. } ) 
12. Qd2 Nd7 
13. Be2 a6 
14. a4 $16  {[%cal Rb7b5][%csl Re8]} { Preventing ...b5. We can go on with our play and Black has no constructive plan. } *

