[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21830648"]
[ECO "A65"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 e6 
4. Nc3 exd5 
5. cxd5 d6 { The Benoni is a very fighting, yet strategically risky setup for Black. In order to create an unbalanced position Black concedes control over the center and attempts to create counterplay by either challenging it (ideas of ...Re8, maybe ...f5 sometimes) or trying to play ...b5.

There are many systems available for White. There is a very sharp system connected with quick e4-f4 and Bb5+, there is more classical e4-Nf3-Nd2, there are also systems with g3, e4-Nge2-Ng3 or even Nf3-Bf4. In this course I decided to keep things rather simple and suggest a system that can be achieved from the King's Indian move order. This simplifies the repertoire and makes it very flexible, regardless of the move orders and other subtleties. } 
6. e4 g6 
7. Be2 ( { I would recommend starting with this move to avoid ...a6-Bg4 line. } 7.Nf3 a6 8.a4 Bg4 { is quite a decent option for Black. } ) Bg7 
8. Nf3 a6 ( { Right now, the main move, of course, is } 8...O-O { . Then we play } 9.Be3 { and we transpose to a position that can be achieved from the KID move order. The only way to deviate from a regular Benoni/KID is to play 8... a6. } ) ( 8...O-O 9.Be3 { transposes back to the King's Indian move order. } ) 
9. a4 Bg4! { I think this is acceptable for Black. The idea of this move is to immediately solve a problem of the light-squared bishop which very often lacks good squares in these structures. Additionally, as White has more space, it makes sense for Black to reduce the amount of material on the board. White can play in two ways now: allow ...Bxf3 or get the knight away from f3 and reroute it to c4. } 
10. Nd2 ( { This move has been scoring well, but Stockfish find a path to a decent position for Black. If White plays } 10.Bf4 { now, Black has not castled yet and has the additional option } 10...Bxf3! 11.Bxf3 Qe7 12.O-O Nbd7 { By delaying castling and focusing on completing the development and controling White's e5 breakthrough idea, Black managed to achieve a solid setup with a typical Benoni position (this is NOT possible when White starts with 9.Bf4) . Engines typically claim White is better but in my feeling, proving an advantage is not an easy task. } ) Bxe2 
11. Qxe2 O-O 
12. Nc4 Nbd7 $146  { A stunning novelty. Unlike after 9. Bf4, Black has some dynamics here that make his position good. } 
13. Nxd6 { Even though not the best, this is of course critical for the entire line. After all, it is a 'free' pawn. } Ne5 
14. Nc4 Nxc4 
15. Qxc4 Qa5! { With plenty of compensation. Next, ...b5 is coming. } 
16. O-O b5 
17. Qxc5 Rac8 
18. Qd4 b4 
19. Na2 Rfe8 
20. Qxb4 Qxb4 
21. Nxb4 Rxe4 
22. Nxa6 Nxd5= $13  { And despite being two pawns down I believe Black has enough compensation to hold his ground here. Ideas of ...Re2 (or ...Rc2) and ...Bd4 are hard to meet comfortably. Additionally, the a6-knight is quite awkward and may be attacked with ...Rc6, potentially forcing some repetition of moves (...Rc6-Nb8-...Rc7-Na6 etc). } 
*

