[ECO "A65"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 e6 
4. Nc3 exd5 
5. cxd5 d6 { The Benoni is a very fighting, yet strategically risky setup for Black. In order to create an unbalanced position Black concedes control over the center and attempts to create counterplay by either challenging it (ideas of ...Re8, maybe ...f5 sometimes) or trying to play ...b5.

There are many systems available for White. There is a very sharp system connected with quick e4-f4 and Bb5+, there is more classical e4-Nf3-Nd2, there are also systems with g3, e4-Nge2-Ng3 or even Nf3-Bf4. In this course I decided to keep things rather simple and suggest a system that can be achieved from the King's Indian move order. This simplifies the repertoire and makes it very flexible, regardless of the move orders and other subtleties. } 
6. e4 g6 
7. Be2 Bg7 
8. Nf3 O-O 
9. Be3 { I like this system against the Benoni mainly for two reasons: one, it is quite unpleasant for Black and objectively very testing, and two, it is flexible - it can be achieved from both King's Indian move order and classical Benoni as well. This reduces the number of lines one needs to learn and unifies the repertoire. } Bg4 { The most popular move here. Of course, it is logical, just like in similar positions [/variation/21830648/#/9/b] resulting from 8...a6. } 
10. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4]} { White should keep the knight and bring it to c4 if possible. } Bxe2 
11. Qxe2 { Black has three main possible setups here but, fortunately for White, none offers equality:

1) ...Na6-...Nc7 and trying to play ...b5.

2) ...Nbd7-...Re8-... a6.

3) ...Nbd7-...Ne8-...Nc7, preparing ...b5 in this way. } Re8 
12. O-O {[%mdl 32768]} Na6 ( { After } 12...Nbd7 { White has the strong typical move } 13.h3!? { preventing any ...Ng4 ideas, especially if Black plays ...Ne5. } 13...a6 14.a4 Rb8 15.Rfe1 $16 { . } ) 
13. Kh1!? {[%cal Rb6g1][%csl Gh1]} { Stepping out of the g1-a7 diagonal to avoid any ...Nxd5 tactics after f3 or f4. } Nc7 
14. a4 Nxe4 { This simplifies the position but does not solve the problems. } 
15. Ndxe4 f5 
16. f3! fxe4 
17. Nxe4 $16  {[%csl Ge4]} { And the e4-knight is very strong. } *

