1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 a6 { This dubious move has been played in some games. Black prepares ...b5 not having to sacrifice a pawn now, or actually prepares ... e6-...exd5, achieving a Benoni structure with ...a6 already played, which allows ...b5. Unfortunately for Black, neither of these ideas is really sound! } 
4. a4 {[%cal Rb7b5]} { I think this is the simplest solution - any ideas connected with ...b5 are stopped for good. In reality, we are likely to transpose to some Benoni where ...a6-a4 is already on the board. This is beneficial to White - not only there won't be ...b5 sacrifices, but also Black won't have ...Na6-...Nc7 ideas. } g6 
5. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bg7 
6. e4 d6 
7. Be2 O-O 
8. Nf3 e6 
