[ECO "A57"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 b5 
4. cxb5 a6 { Alternatives to this move are much worse. } ( { • } 4...e6? 5.Nc3 exd5 6.Nxd5 Bb7 7.e4! { this is pretty much a refutation of this line. White wants to develop his pieces as quickly as possible. } ) ( { • } 4...g6? 5.Nc3 Bg7 6.e4 d6 7.a4 a6 8.Nf3 { is the same as the main line but with an extra tempo for White. If the main line is much better for White, this logically must be just winning. } ) 
5. e3 { I would suggest this move against Benko. My rationale for the choice of this line is the following. First, Black cannot get a typical 'Benko position' in which Black gets an easy game on a and b files - here, White plans on recapturing with the bishop on b5. A quick setup with a4 and Ra3 further restricts Black's play on the queenside. And second, this line is not as popular as 5. bxa6 which makes it a choice that is less expected and there is a chance people playing with Black may not be too familiar with this line. Nonetheless, I believe this system against Benko Gambit can be played often, making it a good choice for a Lifetime Repertoire. Black has three main approaches here:

1) playing with ...g6;

2) playing with ...e6 quickly;

3) playing with ...Bb7 and then attacking the center with ...e6. There are also others that are less popular. } g6 ( { • } 5...e6 6.dxe6 fxe6 7.Nf3 d5 8.Nc3 Nbd7 { a move tried by Daniil Dubov in an online game. } ) ( { • } 5...e6 6.dxe6 fxe6 7.Nf3 d5 8.Nc3 c4 { a logical alternative, disconnecting Bf1 from the b5-pawn. White should complete his development first and then most likely undermine Black's pawn chain with b3. } 9.Be2 axb5 10.Nxb5 Bd7 11.Nc3 Bb4 12.Bd2 { preparing b3 with a big advantage. } { 8...Bd6 is strongly met by 9.e4! which is a typical breakthrough in the center in such and similar positions. } ) 9.bxa6 Bd6 { here White is much better after both } 10.Nb5 { and } { 10.e4!? } ( { • } 5...axb5 6.Bxb5 Qa5+ 7.Nc3 Bb7 { is one of the main options for Black. The d5-pawn pretty much falls now, but it does not matter much, as White gets in return a huge lead in the development. } 8.Bd2 Qb6 9.a4 Nxd5 10.Nf3 e6 11.O-O Be7 12.e4! { dynamic and strong play in the center. } 12...Nb4 { The best option for Black. } { 12...Nxc3 13.Bxc3 O-O 14.Ne5! is strong. } 13.Bf4 N8c6 { Here, among many options, I like the most } 14.Qd2!? { with the idea of installing the blockade on d6 square. } { 14.Bd6 Qd8 is not that bad for Black. } 14...O-O { everything else is just bad. } 15.Bd6! { and now White manages to install a blockade on d6. Black does not have now } 15...Qd8 { due to } 16.Rad1 { and with king castled the d7-pawn falls. } ) ( { • } 5...Bb7 6.Nc3 e6 { is less good than instant 5... e6. } 7.e4 Qa5 8.Bd2 Qb6 9.a4! { White needs to protect the b5-pawn. } 9...exd5 10.exd5 Nxd5 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Nh3↑ { White has a strong initiative here. } ) 
6. Nc3 Bg7 
7. a4! { A typical way to strengthen the queenside. As the queenside is rather taken under control by White, Black needs to play through ...e6 to somehow open the center. } O-O 
8. e4 d6 ( { • } 8...e6 { is premature due to } 9.e5! ) ( { • } 8...Bb7 { Preparing ...e6. } 9.Bg5! { a nice prophylaxis. } 9...Qa5 10.Bd2 { The pressure on the Qa5 proves useful in many lines. Perhaps Black needs to go back to d8, but this gives White an extra tempo. } ) ( { • } 8...Bb7 9.Bg5! { After } 9...h6 { White does not mind giving the bishop pair. } 10.Bxf6 Bxf6 11.Nf3 { If Black does not do anything quickly, White will complete the development, establish a blockade on the light squares (c4 and b5), and will have an easily winning position. It makes sense to open the position with } 11...e6 { but now } 12.e5 $16 { is also really unpleasant for Black. } ) 
9. Nf3 e6 ( 9...axb5 10.Bxb5 { is generally great for White. Black does not get to achieve a counterplay on the a and b files. } ) 
10. dxe6 Bxe6 
11. Be2 d5 
12. e5! Ng4 
13. Bg5 Qd7 
14. O-O { No need to defend the e5-pawn, as the analysis shows! White is much better. } *

