1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 c5 
3. d5 b5 
4. cxb5 a6 { Alternatives to this move are really dubious. } 
5. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} { I would suggest this move against Benko. My rationale for the choice of this line is the following. First, Black cannot get a typical 'Benko position' in which Black gets an easy game on a and b files - here, White plans on recapturing with the bishop on b5. A quick setup with a4 and Ra3 further restricts Black's play on the queenside.

And second, this line is not as popular as 5.bxa6 which makes it a choice that is less expected and there is a chance people playing with Black may not be too familiar with this line. Nonetheless, I believe this system against Benko Gambit can be played often, making it a good choice for a Lifetime Repertoire. Black has three main approaches here:

  1) playing with ...g6;

  2) playing with ...e6 quickly;

  3) playing with ...Bb7 and then attacking the center with ...e6.

} ( { There are also others that are less popular. } 5.bxa6 { is the most popular and there would be for sure some courses in the future on that. } ) e6 { Black consequently attacks White's center. This reminds me of a Blumenfeld Gambit but in this case White has a really nice version of it. } 
6. dxe6 { White does not mind giving away a control over the center and focuses on development. The idea is to get ready to undermine Black's central pawns in the future. } fxe6 
7. Nf3 Be7 { This move makes little sense as the bishop is passively placed on e7, while normally it should go to d6. } 
8. Nc3 O-O 
9. a4 { Securing the queenside and trying to get Bxb5 in one move. } d5 
10. b3 {[%cal Gb3c4][%csl Rc4]} { Preventing ...c4 in any case. } Bb7 
11. Be2 Bd6 ( { Now Black's best move is } 11...Bd6 { which is some sort of a waste of tempo. } ) ( 11...Nbd7?! { is even worse as after } 12.bxa6 Bxa6 13.Bxa6 Rxa6 14.O-O $16 { with Nb5 next; White has just a healthy extra pawn. } ) 
12. O-O e5 
13. Bb2 ( { Completing the development is the most human approach. } 13.Ng5!? Qe7 14.f4! { is something Stockfish really likes too, claiming a big advantage! } ) d4 ( 13...e4 14.Nh4! $16 { with ideas of Nf56, but also f3 or even f4!?. } ) 
14. bxa6! Nxa6 
15. Nb5 $16  { With an extra pawn. I don't think Black has sufficient compensation. } *

