8. e4 { It seems that White wasted a tempo playing e2-e3 first and now e3-e4. In reality, e3 had the purpose of having an option of meeting ...axb5 with Bxb5 and now, once this goal has been accomplished and Black does not have easy queenside play, it makes perfect sense to strengthen the center. Black has a couple of options now but I believe there is no way for Black to equalize. } Bb7 { The idea of this move is to prepare ...e6. } 
9. Bg5!? { Further prophylaxis against ...e6. } h6 { Black forces White to declare what to do with the bishop, but White gladly will take on f6. } 
10. Bxf6! { Not fearing the bishop pair - the priority here is not to allow Black comfortably break through in the center with ...e6 (without Nf6, ...e6 will be less strong for sure) and not allow queenside play. Right now, White manages to accomplish it. } Bxf6 ( 10...exf6 11.Bc4 d6 12.Nf3 $16 { is close to winning for White. } ) 
11. Nf3 Qa5 { GM Dhopade suggests this continuation, which is very logical. } 
12. Ra3! ( { The usual square for the rook there, as seen in many similar positions. } 12.e5?! Bg7 { is not that clear as it overextends White's center which can be soon undermined with ...d6. } ) d6 ( 12...e6 13.Be2 exd5 14.exd5 $16 { is not really helping Black either. } ) 
13. Be2 { Completing the development. Black should try to react fast, otherwise, he will be left down a pawn with no compensation. } Qb4 ( { Perhaps the most resilient. } 13...axb5 14.Bxb5 { does not change much. } 14...Ba6 15.e5! dxe5 16.Nd2 $16 ) 
