[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21808810"]
[ECO "A52"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e5 { The Budapest Gambit is a risky opening for Black but the positions may get there pretty entertaining. Its history is dated back to early 1900s when Hungarian Geza Maroczy won a brilliancy in this opening. In modern computer era this opening is also played time to time on top level, but it is not that frequent due to its risky nature. } 
3. dxe5 Ng4 ( { • } 3...Ne4 { This is the Fajarowicz Gambit. If Budapest is risky, then imagine a dubious line in a risky opening - it hardly can yield anything good to Black. } 4.a3! { Prophylaxis. Black often intends ...Bb4 here so playing a3 simply kills this idea. Black has many possibilities here but nothing is even close to be equalizing. } 4...d6 { Perhaps Black should play this, seeking quick development and counterplay } 5.Qc2! Nc5 { If Black plays oddly-looking 5...d5 then 6.Nd2! is the most precise. And if 6...Bf5 7.cxd5 Qxd5 then 8.g4!! is a refutation. } 6.exd6 Bxd6 7.Nc3 O-O 8.Nf3 { Black should not have sufficient compensation for the missing pawn. } 8...Bg4 9.g3 $16 { 8...Qf6 9.e4 Bg4 10.Be3! }{ 8...a5 9.Bg5 Qe8 10.g3 $16 }) ( { • } 3...Ne4 4.a3! b6 { Fianchetto of the bishop supports Ne4 and is quite common in this line. I would recommend here } 5.Nf3 Bb7 6.g3!? { to counter Bb7 with own Bg2. } ) ( { • } 3...Ne4 4.a3! Nc6 5.Nf3 d6 { is worse than immediate ...d6 as } 6.Qc2! { is the refutation. } ) ( { • } 3...Ne4 4.a3! Qh4 5.g3 Qh5 { was played in some games. Black wants to get the pawn back but wastes precious time for moving the queen several times in the opening. } 6.Nf3 { 6.Bg2!? is also great. } 6...Nc6 7.Qd5 { White simply has an extra pawn and Black does not have any compensation. } ) 
4. Nf3 Bc5 ( { Black should begin with this move. } 4...Nc6 { is inaccurate as White can play now } 5.Bg5! Be7 6.Bxe7 Qxe7 7.Nc3 Ncxe5 8.e4 { White gets a comfortable edge. } ) ( { • } 4...Nc6 5.Bg5 Bb4+ 6.Nc3! { is even worse, as here White will have an extra pawn. } ) 
5. e3 Nc6 
6. Nc3 O-O ( 6...Ngxe5?! { is premature as now White can play } 7.Nxe5 Nxe5 8.f4! { kicking away the knight and developing the bishop to d3 where it is better placed than on e2 as in the main line. } ) 
7. Be2 Re8 ( 7...Ngxe5 8.Nxe5 Nxe5 9.f4! { I think that kicking the knight right away is strong. Black does not get to play ...a5 and ...Ra6, swinging the rook to the kingside with a potentially strong attack. } 9...Nc6 10.O-O Re8 11.Bd3!? { Even having wasted a tempo, this move remains strong. } ) 
8. Nd2!? { A rare but strong idea which I like. Most notably it was played in Vitiugov-Shimanov (2015). } Ngxe5 
9. Nde4 d6 ( 9...Bf8 10.f4! { is very strong. } ) 
10. O-O Qh4 
11. h3!? { Preventing ... Ng4 and ...Bg4 ideas. White is strategically better, as the analysis shows. } *

