[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "55) The Queen's Fianchetto: Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21813806"]
[ECO "A50"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 b6 { I have never known the name of this line until I looked at it for the needs of this course. The Queen's Fianchetto Defense is a rare guest at the top level but still, it is used sometimes either as a surprise weapon or as a way to deviate from the main lines in Nimzo and instead achieve a Queen's Indian setup. White should try to get to play e4 as soon as possible. } 
3. Nc3 ( 3.f3 { is an alternative, generally considered as the main idea against 2... b6, but I did not find anything convincing after } 3...Nc6! { as I show in the analysis. } ) Bb7 
4. Qc2 { I would recommend this line. White prepares e4. } d5 ( { Other moves make little sense. } 4...e6 5.e4 Bb4 6.Bd3 { is a great version of some Nimzo-style position as White built his strong center without any resistance. } ) 
5. cxd5 Nxd5 
6. e4 Nxc3 
7. bxc3 { Black has two main options here, both trying to undermind White's strong center. } e6 ( 7...e5 { a temporary pawn sac that intends to disrupt White's center. } 8.Nf3! { White should ignore the pawn and go for quick development, seeking an edge in the dynamic play. } 8...exd4 9.Bb5+! { This would be my recommendation. The idea is to provoke ...c6 and worsen Bb7. } 9...c6 10.Bc4 { In comparison with 9. Bc4, the Bb7 is bad now. The lag in development is more serious than before. My analysis shows that White is clearly better. } ) 
8. Nf3 Be7 
9. Bf4!? { I would recommend this move here. The detail is that now ...c5 is not possible due to Bb5! } O-O ( 9...c5? 10.Bb5+! Bc6 11.Bxc6+ Nxc6 12.Rd1+- { is just winning for White according to the engine! } ) 
10. Bd3 c5 
11. d5! { The point. White waited until Black castled to have the option to play 11. d5 now, targeting the h7-pawn in many lines. } exd5 
12. exd5 Qxd5 ( 12...h6 13.c4 $16 { is simply unpleasant for Black. } ) 
13. O-O! { White does not recapture the pawn and instead goes for dynamics! } Qh5 
14. Rae1↑ { With a very strong initiative. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Swiercz's 1. d4 - Part 1"]
[White "56) Queen's Fianchetto"]
[Black "3.f3"]
[Date "2023.01.24"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21813825"]
[ECO "A50"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 b6 { I have never known the name of this line until I looked at it for the needs of this course. The Queen's Fianchetto Defense is a rare guest at the top level but still, it is used sometimes either as a surprise weapon or as a way to deviate from the main lines in Nimzo and instead achieve a Queen's Indian setup. White should try to get to play e4 as soon as possible. } 
3. f3 { Before creating this course I have always believed that the best reaction against 2... b6 is 3. f3, aiming to play e4. Upon further investigation, things became not so obvious and I decided that the Nc3-Qc2 system is better. } Nc6! { A sort of unorthodox way of developing the knight, especially together with ...b6, but this move attempts to exploit the lack of Nf3. } 
4. Nc3 ( 4.e4 e5! { is Black's idea, fighting for the dark squares, especially d4. } ) d5!? ( { This move is extremely rare but I think it is kind of close to equalizing or at least reducing White's chances. } 4...e5 { is the main move, but here after } 5.d5 Ne7 6.e4 $16 { or the more aggressive } { 6.g4 $16 White is much better. } ) 
5. Qa4!? ( 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.e4 Nxc3 7.bxc3 e5! { is OK for Black } ) Qd7 ( 5...Bd7? 6.cxd5+- ) 
6. cxd5 Nxd5 
7. Nxd5 Qxd5 
8. e4 Qd6! { This position resembles some sort of QID or Grunfeld without g6 (however weird it sounds...). White is a bit better, but his edge is very minimal. } ( { The endgame after } 8...Qa5+ 9.Qxa5 Nxa5 10.Be3 $16 { is pretty bad for Black. } ) 
9. Bf4!? ( 9.d5 Qb4+ 10.Qxb4 Nxb4 11.Kd2 a5 { followed by ...e6 in the future is not clear either. } ) ( 9.Bb5 Bd7 10.d5 Nd8! { with trades to follow and ...c6 that simplifies the position. I am not sure if White has anything special. } 11.Ne2 Bxb5 12.Qxb5+ c6 13.dxc6 Qxc6 14.Nd4 Qxb5 15.Nxb5 Ne6 { with only minimal edge. } ) e5 
10. dxe5 Qb4+ 
11. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 
12. Kf2 Bc5+ 
13. Be3 Bxe3+ 
14. Kxe3 Nxe5 { With close to equality endgame. } 
*

