1. d4 Nf6 ( { • } 1...g6 2.c4 Bg7 3.e4 d6 4.Nc3 c5 5.d5 Bxc3+!? { This idea, followed up by ...e5, is a somewhat new trend here. Initially, I dismissed it because it does not look right, but even Magnus Carlsen has decided to play it recently, so... } 6.bxc3 e5! { and now I recommend the concrete approach } 7.f4!? exf4 8.Bxf4 Qh4+ 9.Bg3 { A very challenging novelty. } ) 
2. c4 d6 { The Old Indian Defense is quite a rare guest at the top level. There are possible transpositions to King's Indian or some sort of Philidor with c4. I remember that in 2014 I employed it in one of my games as Black when I tried to avoid Saemisch Variation in King's Indian and get some other pawn structure. I succeeded in doing so in my game but if we are going for relatively standard lines in King's Indian, there is no need to fear this. } ( { • } 2...Nc6 { The knights' Tango (at least I am pretty sure that is the name of this line!) is a rather speculative opening choice. } 3.Nc3 { The most natural move, intending e4. } 3...d5 { 3...e6 It is dubious to allow White play e4. 4.e4 } 4.Nf3 dxc4 { Perhaps this is the most critical - but after } 5.e4 { it transposes to Queen's Gambit Accepted 3. e4 Nc6, which is out of fashion and perhaps for a reason, as my analysis indicates. } ) ( { • } 2...Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 { Generally this is the main idea behind playing ...Nc6. } 4.d5 Ne7 5.Nf3 Ng6 6.h4! { White can challenge the Ng6 and gain space on the kingside. } ) 
3. Nc3 e5 ( 3...Bf5 { This is the Janowski Variation. The idea is to stop White from constructing a strong center with e4. This idea is pretty good when White already developed the knight to f3 as it is harder than to get to play e4. Here, however, it should be easier. } 4.g3! { A very simple and strong move. Now the bishop goes to g2 and the e4-square is under control, rendering ...Bf5 idea useless. } ) 
4. Nf3 Nbd7 { This is the Philidor setup but with White's pawn already on c4, which allows White to gather more space than in a 'normal' Philidor with the pawn on c2. } ( { • } 4...exd4 5.Nxd4 { This is typically a very nice position for White. Next, e4 is coming with standard Maroczy bind position. } ) ( { • } 4...e4 { This move would be legit without Nc3 and Nf6 on the board (say, from the following move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.Nf3 e4 ) as Black would have a possibility to support the e4-pawn with ...f5. With Nf6 on the board, the e4-pawn is just a weakness. 5.Ng5 Black has problems with the e4-pawn here. } ) ( { • } 4...Nc6 { This move transposes to some version of 'Tango'. } 5.d5! { The most logical response is to seize space with a tempo. } ) 
5. e4 Be7 
6. Be2 O-O 
7. O-O c6 
8. Be3 { The most standard move. It goes well with other King's Indian lines that I recommend where White plays Be2 and Be3 anyway. White's plan is pretty simple: centralize all the pieces and/or consider playing d5 at some point to gather even more space. } *

