1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 d6 { The Old Indian Defense is quite a rare guest at the top level. There are possible transpositions to King's Indian or some sort of Philidor with c4. I remember that in 2014 I employed it in one of my games as Black when I tried to avoid Saemisch Variation in King's Indian and get some other pawn structure. I succeeded in doing so in my game but if we are going for relatively standard lines in King's Indian, there is no need to fear this. } 
3. Nc3 e5 ( 3...Nbd7 { is a possible move order too but it would most likely transpose to 3... e5. } 4.e4 e5 5.Nf3 { and we are back to the main line. } ) 
4. Nf3 Nbd7 { This is the Philidor setup, but with White's pawn already on c4, which allows White gather more space than in a 'normal' Philidor with pawn on c2. } 
5. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} Be7 
6. Be2 O-O 
7. O-O c6 
8. Be3 { The most standard move. It goes well with other King's Indian lines that I recommend where White plays Be2 and Be3 anyway. White's plan is pretty simple: centralize all the pieces and/or consider playing d5 at some pont to gather even more space. } Re8 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gd7f8,Gf8g6]} { The idea of this move is generally to play ...Nf8 and ...Ng6. Playing ...Bf8 should not be good as at best this bishop can come to g7, but this results in a terrible version of King's Indian. } 
9. Qc2 Qc7 ( 9...Bf8 10.d5 $16 ) 
10. h3 { Not a necessary move, but just in case. } Nf8 { Here White can play either with d5, or without. } 
11. Rfd1 ( { An alternative is } 11.d5 Ng6 12.Rfd1 c5 13.a3 $16 ) Ng6 
12. b4 exd4 
13. Nxd4 Bf8 
14. Rab1 $16  { Of course, White's position is great. } *

